<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Missionaries 1stLd-Writethru a0780 03-13 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Missionaries, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0780,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Traffickers Release Two American Missionaries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT hometowns, ADDS details, quotes
from family members. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two American missionaries who were
abducted from a religious retreat two months ago, apparently by drug
traffickers, were released unharmed, police and family members said
Monday.
   Roy Libby, of Portland, Ore., and Richard Grover, of Warroad,
Minn., were kidnapped January 3 by an armed group near the
municipality of Florida in the department of El Valle, 180 miles
southwest of Bogota. They were participating in a meeting of the
Evangelical Missionary Union.
   Libby and Grover were released unharmed Sunday night near Florida
and flew immediately to Ecuador to meet with their families, said
Hector Pardo, president of the Evangelical Confederation.
   The missionaries ``were well treated by their captors. They were
released unharmed and there was not paid any ransom money,'' Pardo
said.
   Grover's mother, Helen Grover, said Monday night from her home in
Warroad that her son had called from Quito, Ecuador, Monday
afternoon.
   ``He told about how they were released,'' she said. ``They walked
out. One of the captors walked with them for an hour and a half,
then they walked an hour and a half more before they waved at a car
and the car stopped and picked them up and took them to a little
town.''
   She said her son told her he did not know who his captors were.
``He said he knew they were a subversive group,'' she said. ``He was
never told why they took them or why they released them.''
   She said Grover told her they were ``treated very well.''
   Radio stations on Monday received a statement signed by ``The
Extraditables,'' a gang of drug traffickers, saying Libby and Grover
were ``tried'' under suspicions they were working for the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration.
   The statement said the missionaries were released after their
kidnappers established they had no links to the DEA.
   ``The Extraditables'' has been accused of killing Colombia's
justice minister, Rodrigo Lara Bonilla, and attorney general, Carlos
Mauro Hoyos, after the officials authorized the extradition of some
important cocaine dealers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
