<FIRST>u a AM-Vincennes-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru a0687 03-13 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vincennes-Bomb, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0687,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Men Of Apparent Mideastern Extraction Seen In Rogerses' Neighborhood</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th graf, `FBI spokesman...,' to UPDATE
with reports that bomb was too crude to be work of well-known Iranian groups,
investigators beginning to doubt international terrorist group.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men of Mideastern appearance were seen in
the neighborhood of the commander of the USS Vincennes in the weeks
before the Navy captain's van was destroyed by a bomb, a law
enforcement official said Monday.
   Sharon Rogers, wife of Capt. Will Rogers III was alone in the van
when the bomb detonated Friday while she drove alone to work. She
got out of the van moments before it caught fire and was not injured.
   Rogers gave permission last summer to shoot down a plane over the
Persian Gulf that was presumed from radar data to be a fighter, but
actually was an Iranian civilian passenger jet.
   The official, who disclosed the information on condition of
anonymity, said it was not clear if investigators had been able to
piece together detailed descriptions of the two men. The information
was based on interviews with neighbors, the official said.
   The official spoke after a report in Monday's New York Times that
one man of Middle Eastern appearance had asked passers-by: ``Where
does the captain live?''
   FBI spokesman Gary Laturno said he could neither confirm nor deny
the report.
   Investigators, however, were beginning to move away from their
suspicions that the bombing was directed from abroad by
international terrorists, The Times reported in Tuesday' editions.
   Sources told The Associated Press that based on intelligence
information and initial reports from investigators, the explosive
device was believed to be very crude and not of the quality that
would be expected from prominent Iranian-supported terrorist groups.
   Last week, Oliver ``Buck'' Revell, a top FBI official, testified
before Congress about the potential terrorist threat posed by
Iranian students in the United States. He cited the San Diego region
as one area where there was a high number of students.
   But the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, cautioned
against drawing the inference that students were behind the Rogers
bombing.
   The FBI said it was chasing hundreds of leads as it tried to
determine if the bombing was a terrorist act in retaliation for the
shooting down of the airliner. All 290 people aboard the airliner
were killed.
   There has been no claim of responsibility for the bombing.
   Rogers and his wife remained at an undisclosed location Monday
under the protection of Naval Investigative Service agents.
Officials at the school where Mrs. Rogers teaches said they do not
expect her to return to work this week.
   The FBI, which is coordinating the investigation, has made a
public appeal asking for calls from anyone who may have seen
something suspicious before, during or after the blast.
   The FBI has described the bomb as ``an improvised explosive
device'' rather than a manufactured military device. Types of such
devices include pipe bombs.
   Investigators with the San Diego Fire Department and the Metro
Arson Strike Team concluded on the day of the blast that the
explosion was caused by a pipe bomb. The FBI then assumed primary
jurisdiction of the investigation.
   Meanwhile, Navy officials said Monday that enhanced security at
Navy installations in the San Diego area would remain in effect
until the FBI concludes its investigation of the bombing.
   ``There's been no change in our security posture since it was
increased Friday,'' said Chief Petty Officer Craig Huebler, a
spokesman at the San Diego Naval Base. ``There'll be no change until
the FBI can complete its work and report back on what we are dealing
with.''
</TEXT>
