<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--SinkholeKillings     03-13 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Sinkhole Killings,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Trying To Identify Bodies Found In Sinkhole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRAWFORDVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities worked Sunday to identify
three young men who were shot to death before their bodies turned up
in a sinkhole, the sheriff said.
   The bodies were discovered Friday in the small sinkhole known as
Moody cave, which is about five miles northeast of this northern
Florida town near the Gulf Coast, said Wakulla County Sheriff David
Harvey.
   Harvey said two of the victims were 15 or 16 years old, and the
third was about 18 to 20.
   Autopsies indicated the three shooting victims had been dead five
to 10 hours, he said.
   Cave divers found the first body on a ledge, and deputies found
the others in the water, the sheriff said.
   ``Right now we have a forensic artist making up sketches,''
Harvey said. ``And our crime people are still out working the site.
That's about all I can say.''
   Sinkholes in Florida are saucer-shaped depressions produced when
limestone or other underlying material collapses.
</TEXT>
