<FIRST>r i AM-NIreland-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru a0403 03-13 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NIreland-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0403,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defuse large bomb placed near army base</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name of town to Castlederg 2d graf and makes location
west stead southwest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British army specialists on
Sunday defused a 1,500-pound bomb found in a van parked outside a
military base, police reported.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army issused a statement asserting
responsibility for the attempted bombing of the army-police base at
Castlederg, 68 miles west of Belfast and less than 3 miles from the
border with the Irish Republic.
   An army bomb-disposal team took nearly 12 hours to defuse the
huge device, according to police. They said the explosives were
packed in the vehicle that had been reported stolen in Dublin nine
months ago.
   A police station said the terrorists had ``shown little regard
for lives of the local people.''
   The predominantly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to unite
Northern Ireland, a British province where Protestants outnumber
Catholics 3-2, with the mainly Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
