<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TowerAftermath     03-13 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower Aftermath,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Senate Tries to Heal Wounds from Tower Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate members are in the position of two
brothers who, badly bruised after an unwanted fight, need to put the
past behind them and get on with life.
   The angry intensity of the fight that scuttled John Tower's
nomination as secretary of defense won't make that easy.
   But President Bush's quick decision on Friday to nominate Rep.
Richard Cheney, R-Wyo., a former White House chief of staff and the
No. 2 Republican leader in the House, may start the process of
calming the Senate's turbulent political waters.
   Bush acted only 24 hours after the Senate voted 53-47 to reject
Tower. His choice of Cheney received favorable reviews from members
of both parties and quick hearings were promised by the Senate Armed
Services Committee.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole, who had said the Tower defeat
would not be forgotten by the GOP, retained an edge of bitterness.
   ``This will be a confirmation, not an execution,'' he said of the
Cheney nomination.
   But he soon was looking as much forward as back.
   ``I believe this will help to put all of the Tower business
behind us,'' Dole said.
   What does the Senate have to put behind it?
   Here are some of the words that jolted the chamber's stately
marble-walled facade and its old-boy-club traditions of courtesy,
comity and civility.
   _Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo.: ``I have to rage at a Senate that
has lost its sense of responsibility, its sense of fairness, a
Senate which will never willingly shoulder responsibility. ...
   ``The nomination process is now a tool of intrigue, of arrogance
and of raw political power.
   ``We have no need of smoking guns to ruin a man's career anymore,
just enough smoke to cover the vicious partisan intentions of those
who would seek to run the executive branch from Capitol Hill.''
   ``This has been a confirmation process corrupted, contaminated,
hijacked by character assassination, by the cowardly leakage of
unsubstantiated allegations.''
   _Sen. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn.: ``There are very strong feelings
on this side of the aisle that we have been had. ... It is going to
be hard to put the pieces back together. It will not be automatic.
... We feel abused and hurt.''
   But some Republicans such as Sen. John Warner of Virginia say
they already feel ``a spirit of reconciliation creeping over this
place.''
   Many Democrats hastened to speed reconciliation along, help
restore the Senate's normal courtliness and rekindle the fragile
bipartisan flame that was at least temporarily snuffed out in the
storm over Tower.
   But Democrats also were upset at the fierceness of the battle
over Tower.
   ``Charges and countercharges of partisanship, hypocrisy and bad
faith are being hurled from the White House to Capitol Hill and back
again,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. ``The debate in the Senate
has been as personal and acrimonious as I have seen in my 14 years
here.''
   But Leahy added: ``While things may get worse before they get
better, I am confident they will get better.''
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., the chamber's most senior Democrat,
said ``the harsh words should stop.''
   ``We must not rub salt into the wounds that have been opened. Let
us act like adults, not like warring children in a sandlot football
game,'' he said.
   Tower's problems in the Senate stemmed from allegations in a
massive FBI report that he abused alcohol, had improper relations
with women and had lucrative links to giant defense contractors that
posed the appearance of conflict of interest.
   After Bush announced the selection of Cheney as a replacement
candidate, Wallop was asked the inevitable questions about the new
nominee's personal life.
   He made it clear that in Cheney's case another bruising fight
over personal matters is unlikely.
   ``A smart straight arrow,'' Wallop said of his home-state friend.
   ``I do not know what possible skeletons could exist in that
closet.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence L. Knutson covers Congress for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
