<DOCNO> AP890313-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MoneyLaundering     03-13 1191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Money Laundering,1222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Alleges Jewelry Firms Were Conduits In Cocaine Operation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Profits from illegal cocaine sales are so vast
these days that government agents measure drug dollars by weight and
cocaine dealers, in a scramble to launder the bulky cash, have even
gone so far as to buy banks.
   ``The cocaine organizations are generating a horrendous amount of
cash,'' said U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner.
   ``If they can't convert this cash and get it out of the United
States, the whole point of the illegal drug operation is frustrated.
   ``Most people don't realize the physical space and weight taken
up by cash proceeds... Until it is counted, we are measuring this
money in weight. $1 million in cash is well over 100 pounds of
currency.''
   So drug dealers devise ingenious schemes to get money out of the
country. The arrests of 37 jewelers and their employees has exposed
what authorities say was a clever new mechanism: using bogus gold
transactions to hide drug profits.
   In recent years Bonner's office has prosecuted money-laundering
rings that went so far as to buy their own banks, but nothing has
matched the scope of the ring broken by the federal ``Operation
Polar Cap,'' which allegedly involved whole families as defendants
and more money than any case before it.
   The case broke open Feb. 22 as federal agents searched 85
locations in Los Angeles, New York and Miami and U.S. marshals swept
into Los Angeles' wholesale jewelry mart, arresting proprietors of a
dozen jewelry and bullion outlets.
   Jewelers allegedly laundered more than $1 billion in just over
two years.
   A federal grand jury here indicted 33 jewelers and associates
Wednesday. Four other defendants were indicted in San Jose the
previous week.
   Authorities also confiscated $80 million in property, including
jewelry, $12 million in gold, $6.74 million in cash, a condominium,
apartment complex, five houses and a 10-story building in the center
of the downtown mart.
   ``This investigation certainly will pay for itself,'' Bonner said
at a news conference announcing the indictments.
   According to court documents, the money-laundering operation was
run primarily from Ropex Corp., owned by Wanis ``Joseph''
Koyomejian, and Andonian Brothers Manufacturing Co., owned by Vahe
and Nazareth Andonian. One defendant, Raul Vivas, is in custody in
Uruguay, from where he allegedly ran the ring.
   The defendants were charged with aiding the distribution of
thousands of pounds of cocaine by laundering hundreds of milllions
of dollars in cash from drug sales across the country. They also
were charged with conspiring to violate the Money Laundering Control
Act and to avoid reporting currency transactions over $10,000 as
required by law.
   The maximum sentence for conspiracy is life imprisonment. The
maximum for money laundering is 20 years in prison and fines up to
$25 million.
   Most of the defendants are different from any arrested in the
past. Instead of Colombian nationals deep into the drug trade, they
are of Armenian, Syrian, Turkish and Lebanese extraction, emigres
who seemed to have grabbed a piece of the American dream with their
thriving gold and jewelry businesses.
   The defendants, through their lawyers, have declared their
innocence.
   Government officials won't comment in depth on Polar Cap, but
some 300 pages of affidavits show their view of how the gold and
jewelry trade became a nearly perfect cover after the 1986 arrests
of major money-launderers.
   According to affidavits, here's how one gold-related transaction
worked:
   On Dec. 12, 1988, nine boxes of cash _ $2,568,000 _ were shipped
from Z&amp;G Gold in New York by armored car to Andonian Brothers' API
subsidiary in Los Angeles, where it was counted and phone calls were
made confirming the amount.
   The next day, Nazareth Andonian ordered 177 kilograms of gold
credited to a gold brokerage account of Ronel Refining of Hollywood,
Fla., a gold refining company, and deposited the $2,568,000 in a Los
Angeles bank.
   He later wire-transferred $2,491,152 to Ronel, keeping $76,848 as
API's 3 percent commission for laundering. Ronel owner Richard
Ferris used the money to pay for the gold, keeping a 4 percent
commission. At that point, according to an affidavit, ``Ronel is
positioned to repeatedly sell the same gold to API-LA via various
gold brokers.''
   Cash was delivered daily by drug couriers to about a dozen
jewelry stores in New York and Los Angeles, then transported to API
or Ropex for counting and deposit under the guise of gold sales, the
government said. Millions then were transferred to banks in Panama
and Uruguay for delivery to Colombia as payment for cocaine that had
been shipped on consignment to the United States.
   ``The amount represents proceeds of approximately 70 tons of
cocaine sold in the United States in two years,'' Bonner said.
   The scheme worked without detection until early last year, when
incidents on two continents led federal agents to begin
surveillance, including wiretaps, bugs, hidden cameras and secret
trash collections, in several U.S. cities.
   Everything began to unravel in January 1988 when Wells Fargo Bank
reported ABI was making extraordinarily large deposits of U.S.
currency into specific accounts. In one three-month period, $25
million had been deposited.
   Drug Enforcement Administration Agent Michael Orton said in an
affidavit that the government learned from a New York cocaine dealer
that drug proceeds were being delivered to an API office there for
laundering.
   Then, an agent working in Montevideo, Uruguay, learned from a
cocaine dealer of ``a money laundering operation in Los Angeles,
Miami and New York that was initiated in April 1986 by Panamanian
and Colombian drug traffickers. (He) described the money laundering
operation as utilizing bogus gold shipments and transactions to
conceal the laundering...,'' Orton said.
   The source named two Latin American partners in the scheme, but
it wasn't until last September that multiple informants, apparently
seeking leniency in their own cases, began spilling details of the
operation, naming the principals and pinpointing its center in the
Los Angeles jewelry district.
   At one point, 23 DEA and FBI agents were intercepting calls to
Andonian Brothers and Ropex. They heard apparently coded talk of
large amounts of money and saw deliveries of duffle bags, boxes and
catalog cases filled with money.
   The currency would be piled on tables, sometimes to the ceiling,
said a prosecutor. And it would be counted by high-speed counting
machines.
   Gathering evidence became complicated, when API began using a
paper shredder to destroy documents and black spray paint to
obliterate the return addresses on packages delivered to the
company. Orton said he found a chemical solvent which dissolved the
paint and revealed the address of a jewelry company in New York
which allegedly was shipping money to be laundered.
   According to Bonner, increasing seizures of money and cocaine in
Los Angeles indicate that it has supplanted Miami as the nation's
cocaine capital as Mexican and Colombian cartels join forces to ship
drugs from Mexico.
   ``We've had a definite shift of cocaine coming across the Mexican
border, rather than being shipped in from Florida,'' he said. The
result is that ``Los Angeles now has become the major distribution
point for cocaine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
