<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     03-13 0953</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Super-Tractor Sales on the Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of big, four-wheel-drive tractors, the
kind that go for as much as a quarter-section of land in some parts,
rebounded sharply in 1988 and are expected to show further gains
this year.
   Preliminary estimates by the Agriculture Department show that
2,729 of the big tractors were sold last year, up 65 percent from
just 1,653 in 1987. The gain may be around 14 percent in 1989 to
about 3,100 units, says the department's Economic Research Service.
   But the gains still leave sales of the big machines far short of
the more than 10,000 a year purchased in the late 1970s, just before
heavy debts, falling commodity prices and other problems put a
financial crunch on the nation's farm economy.
   The four-wheel-drive models are not the only tractors or machines
that figure into today's huge agricultural investment. But they are
one of the barometers, and their costs are formidable. As of last
October, according to USDA surveys, the tractors cost an average of
$76,800 each.
   A few other machines cost more, however. Large grain combines
averaged $91,600 each last fall, and self-propelled cotton pickers
were $84,800 each. Comparatively, farmland nationally averaged only
$548 per acre a year ago.
   The USDA agency says in a new report that total farm machinery
expenditures gained in 1987 after seven consecutive years of
decline. Overall, it said, farmers spent $5.77 billion on machinery
in 1987, up from $4.61 billion in 1986.
   Preliminary estimates put 1988 expenditures in a range of $5.9
billion to $6.5 billion, and the forecast for 1989 calls for a
further increase to $6.4 billion to $7.1 billion.
   Machinery sales rose to a record of almost $12 billion in 1979
before beginning a slide of more than 60 percent to the $4.61
billion of 1986. Now, with farmland prices rising and credit more
easily available, farmers are looking harder at machinery.
   ``The drought, improved farm equity and the increasing age of the
farm machinery stock will likely have a significant influence on
1989 farm machinery sales prospects,'' the report said. ``A
continuing rise in land prices not only improves farm equity, but
indicates an optimism on the future profitability of agriculture.''
   Most new farm machinery sales were up last year, although the
drought and its shriveling of grain yields ``probably caused the 16
percen fall in sales of self-propelled combine units,'' which
dropped to 5,995 from 7,172 in 1987, the report said. Sales this
year could rise to 7,300 units.
   ``Farm machinery sales in the latter half of 1988 slipped as the
extent of the drought became apparent,'' the report said. ``Farmers
who saw yields declining delayed purchases of tractors, combines and
other equipment.''
   However, those farmers who did raise crops or had large
quantities stored from previous harvests saw commodity prices climb.
Thus, many of these found it advantageous to replace or upgrade
their equipment.
   ``Although the growth in sales continues to be good news for farm
machinery manufacturers, there is still significant room for
improvement,'' the report said. ``Within most machine categories,
1989 sales will likely approach only one-third of their 1978-80
average.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pellet made mostly from bagasse, the crushed
stalks that remain after sugar cane is processed, shows possibility
as a feed base for small-scale shrimp producers, according to
Agriculture Department scientists.
   Donald W. Freeman, who works for the department's Agricultural
Research Service at the A.B. McKay Food Laboratory in Mississippi,
said the cane-based food might make it easier and cheaper to grow
shrimp in Hawaii and other tropical areas.
   Tests in Hawaii showed that the shrimp not only ate the bagasse
pellets _ which are fortified with inexpensive forms of protein,
fats and minerals _ but also the bacteria, algae and microscopic
zooplankton that feed on the pellets.
   Feed costs are one of the shrimp farmer's biggest costs. The
bagasse is cheap and plentiful in Hawaii, a major sugar cane
production area, and the experimental pellets cost only about $100 a
ton, compared with $300 to $450 for commercial feeds.
   Growth of the bagasse-fed shrimp was said to be comparable to
those grown in ponds and provided the regular feed.
   The report said that 76 percent of the shrimp consumed by
Americans in 1987 _ 765 million pounds valued at least $1.2 billion
wholesale _ was imported.
   Freeman said small-scale fish farmers in Hawaii, the Virgin
Islands, Puerto Rico and other tropical areas might be able to raise
shrimp economically by feeding bagasse pellets.
   Dried feedlot manure also works well as a source of nutrients for
pond microorganisms which the shrimp eat, and costs about the same
as the bagasse pellets, but Freeman said manure has ``image
problems.''
   The bagasse pellets aren't intended for high-yielding intensive
fish farming, where most of the nutritious microorganisms aren't
allowed to grow, he said. In the highly intensive pond operations,
shrimp must have better quality feed to make up for nutrients that
the microorganisms would provide.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is the world's largest
exporter of agricultural products, and it is also one of the top
importers.
   Last year, says the Agriculture Department, exports were valued
at $35.3 billion. While rebounding modestly, exports still are well
below the record levels of the early 1980s.
   Meanwhile, imports of agricultural products are at record value
levels, totaling $21 billion in the fiscal year that ended last
Sept. 30, says the department's Foreign Agricultural Service.
   The top-valued group of imports was horticultural products _
fruits, nuts and vegetables _ worth about $3.7 billion. Beef and
pork imports were next at $2.7 billion, closely followed by
unroasted coffee beans at $2.6 billion.
</TEXT>
