<DOCNO> AP890313-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Election     03-13 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Election,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadorans Have First Chance To Vote Out Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadorans, for the first time
in their history, have the chance to keep one party in power or
replace it with a completely different party's program and ideology.
   The choice to be made Sunday is between presidential candidates
of the incumbent Christian Democratic Party and rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena. Five other parties are running
candidates but acknowledge they have no chance of winning.
   That there is a choice at all, along with prospects of a
constitutional transfer of power, demonstrates how far this nation
has progressed toward democracy.
   But security forces and right-wing death squads continue to
summarily execute suspected leftists, the leftist Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front terrorizes elected officials, and a brutal
civil war that has left 70,000 dead drags on.
   Whatever the outcome, the term of President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
a linchpin of U.S. policy in the region, ends June 1. The
constitution forbids re-election, and Duarte is dying of cancer.
   ``Duarte's great legacy is this election and this transition,''
said a senior U.S. diplomat. ``It's ironic that his enemies, Arena,
are the ultimate beneficiaries of Duarte and the democratic
conditions he created.''
   Washington's role in El Salvador cannot be underestimated. The
country receives $500 million in aid every year, almost as much as
it collects in taxes.
   Arena favors a smaller state role in the economy and is
considered less open to negotiations to end the war. One of it's
slogans is a militaristic ``Win the Peace.''
   The question in many minds remains: Has progress toward
democratic government been great enough to prevent the country
sliding into chaos?
   Arena trounced the incumbents in last year's legislative and
municipal elections and is favored to win, though a runoff probably
will be necessary.
   Independent polls give Arena candidate Alfredo Cristiani a lead
of three to nine percentage points over Christian Democratic Fidel
Chavez Mena.
   Arena, founded by right-wingers linked by many to death squads,
says it has changed. Its campaign refrain is ``Vamos al Cambio,''
meaning ``Let's change.'' But many fear an Arena victory will bring
more violence and intensify the war.
   ``Arena's antecedents make us worry about the prospect of their
victory ... Violence will undoubtedly increase,'' Gregorio Rosa
Chavez, auxiliary Roman Catholic archbishop of San Salvador, said in
a recent homily.
   The rightists count on pervasive dissatisfaction with the
Christian Democrats, who have failed to bring peace.
   No independent poll gives Arena the 51 percent necessary for
victory in the first round. Polling is complicated by the war,
people who fear revealing their preference, and the possibility of
coalitions in a second round, which would be held in late April.
   U.S. pollsters Greenberg-Lake, in a survey released last month,
said 27 percent of those consulted intend to vote for Arena.
Eighteen percent said they will vote for the Christian Democrats,
while nearly 40 percent were unwilling to divulge their preference
or were undecided.
   In the most telling element of the survey, 58 percent said they
believe the Christian Democrats do not deserve re-election.
   ``The people want alternation in government. Alternation
contributes to the establishment of democracy,'' Armando Calderon
Sol said in an interview. He is mayor of San Salvador and one of
Arena's top four leaders.
   Duarte's 1984 victory was the first semblance of a democratic
presidential election in El Salvador's history. He took power from a
provisional regime that had emerged from a 1979 coup.
   The coup was the start of a reform process to end a monopoly on
power exercised by an alliance of the military and a landowning
oligarchy.
   Arena was founded in 1981 by ousted army intelligence Maj.
Roberto D'Aubuisson, who has been linked with death squads by human
rights organizations, the Christian Democrats and the U.S. Embassy.
The squads connected to security forces ran rampant in the early
1980s and were blamed for thousands of slayings.
   D'Aubuisson, a legislator, denies the charges. His party has
sought to refurbish its image of violence and fanaticism by
promoting Cristiani, an urbane businessman educated at Georgetown
University.
   But the charismatic D'Aubuisson still is the party's big drawing
card and he continues to be introduced at rallies as ``our maximum
leader.''
   Vice President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount recently called Arena
``a party of fascists.'' The party anthem is belligerant, almost
morbid, with refrains that ``Liberty is written with blood'' and
``El Salvador will be the tomb of the Reds.''
   Voting will take place under difficult conditions. The guerrillas
have told their supporters to boycott the vote and have decreed a
nationwide road transport ban beginning Wednesday. Such bans usually
are quite effective.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle 3rdLd-Writethru a0736 03-13 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0736,0852</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Set For First Shuttle Launch of Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with fueling of rockets beginning;
pickup 3rd graf pvs, `Tomorrow morning ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CSB3-4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buoyed by a flawless countdown and a
good weather forecast, NASA was set to launch space shuttle
Discovery on Monday with five astronauts and a cargo that includes a
$100 million satellite and four crippled rats.
   At 11:58 p.m., launch pad workers began to pump 528,000 gallons
of supercold liquid hydrogen and oxygen into the shuttle's external
tank. The chemicals will fuel the three main rocket engines that
must fire for 8{ minutes to put Discovery into orbit.
   Liftoff was set for 8:07 a.m. EST. Forecasts called for clear
skies, and mild temperatures _ ideal for launch of the first shuttle
mission of 1989. Only the possibility of strong high-altitude winds
gave any concern, and NASA officials said wind conditions at
midnight were favorable for the launch.
   ``Tomorrow morning is a great day to go fly,'' shuttle boss
Richard Truly said at a Sunday afternoon news conference. ``The
weather has been getting prettier and prettier. We're in good
shape.''
   The countdown proceeded so smoothly on Sunday that preparations
skipped two hours ahead of schedule.
   ``It seems a little scary it's going so well,'' said Chuck
Henschel, launch test director. ``We're ahead of where we want to
be.''
   The fault-free countdown was in sharp contrast to the troubles
that plagued NASA in getting Discovery ready for the mission. The
flight originally had a Feb. 18 target date, but a series of faulty
or suspect parts delayed the launch four times.
   Workers changed out turbo pumps in the main engines when flaws
were found in the pumps on sister shuttle Atlantis. Last week, tests
showed a failure in the system that commands the separation of the
two booster rockets and the external tank. The unit was replaced
with a part removed from Columbia.
   Launch of Discovery sets in motion NASA's ambitious plan for
seven shuttle missions this year while building toward a
once-a-month flight rate by 1992. The flight will be the third since
the nation returned to manned spaceflight following the Challenger
disaster of 1986.
   Discovery's five-man crew is to be awakened about 3 a.m. Monday
and will board the shuttle at 5:15 a.m.
   Waiting for them in cages aboard the ship will be four rats, part
of an experiment on the effects of weightlessness on the healing of
injured bones.
   A small piece of bone was clipped from each of the rats, and how
well these injuries heal during five days in weightlessness will be
studied when the rodents are returned to Earth.
   Discovery's main job for the 28th shuttle mission is to deliver
to orbit a $100 million communications craft called the Tracking and
Data Relay Satellite. The satellite is the final point in an
orbiting communications network that will keep the shuttle and other
spacecraft in almost constant radio contact with the Earth. The
network will enable NASA to shut down six ground tracking stations,
saving $3 million a month.
   The satellite, called TDRS-4, will be released from Discovery
about six hours after launch. Two later rocket firings will send the
TDRS to a stationary orbit 22,300 miles over the Atlantic Ocean.
   NASA already has two such satellites in orbit, but TDRS-1 has
been in use since 1983 and is ailing. It will be moved to a new
location in orbit for use as a spare.
   TDRS-2, which was to have been the second in the network, was on
board Challenger when that spacecraft exploded shortly after launch.
   Last September, TDRS-3 was deployed from Discovery, during the
first shuttle flight after the Challenger accident. The satellite
now is over the Pacific Ocean and will be used during the current
mission.
   Discovery's crew is led by Navy Capt. Michael L. Coats, 43, who
is making his second spaceflight. His pilot is Air Force Col. John
E. Blaha, 46, on his first shuttle mission.
   The three missions specialists on the crew are James F. Buchli,
43, a Marine colonel who has twice before flown into space; Marine
Col. Robert C. Springer, 46, and Dr. James P. Bagian, a 37-year-old
physician. Both Springer and Bagian are space rookies.
   In addition to monitoring the rats, the astronauts will conduct
other experiments.
   Two types of plants will sprout in a small garden on board to
test the effects of weightlessness on root growth. Officials said
this study may develop ways to grow plants aboard the space station.
   Scientists also will study the effects weightlessness on the
development of embryos by flying 32 fertilized chicken eggs. The
eggs will be incubated throughout the mission and the embryos will
be compared later with some grown at the same time on the ground.
   Discovery is to orbit for five days, one hour and land on
Saturday at Edwards Air Force Base in California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
