<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Voices     03-13 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Voices,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Voices, Four Visions Of El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador-Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following are visions from
four people interviewed on the future of El Salvador, which holds
presidential elections Sunday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Armando Calderon Sol. Mayor of San Salvador and a leader of the
rightist opposition Republican Nationalist Alliance, known as Arena,
which is favored to take the presidency:
   ``In 1980, Washington turned El Salvador into a sociological
laboratory, breaking apart the system of private property with
agrarian reform, nationalization of the marketing of export crops
and nationalization of the banks.
   ``We intend to rescue our sovereignty and independence.
   ``... We want a broad capitalism, not just for a small group, but
capitalism for the masses.
   ``We will call on the honorable military technicians to enforce
the laws.
   ``We're not afraid of communists, of debating them in the
political arena, competing with them in elections. The problem is
they break the law, planting bombs, killing.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Diego.'' A midlevel commander in the guerrilla Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front:
   ``The FMLN is fighting to put the resources of the country at the
disposal of the entire people, not just of one sector. And we're
fighting to form a new Salvadoran ... a dignified and educated man
...
   ``The basic problem is that the regime, despite its democratic
facade, is still fundamentally repressive ...
   ``We need to create the political conditions in which we can not
only cast a ballot, but in which we can work politically without
getting our throats cut. The bodies that continue appearing each
week by the roadside, in a grain sack, their hands tied, tortured,
their faces painted red, they don't have the good fortune to be
named Ungo and Zamora (prominent leftist politicians).''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Ruben Zamora. Coordinator of the Democratic Convergence leftist
coalition running third in polls:
   ``The first thing that has to be done is putting the state of war
behind us ... It is only possible through negotiated accord among
the principal _ or all _ the sectors of society. Then we work on a
program that attacks the causes of the war _ social injustice and
the lack of real democracy.
   ``We have to have a program of economic recovery, but designed
with the poor in mind, improvement of their buying power, increased
wages. Then would come the process of real democratization ... That
means rescuing our sovereignty, which has been sold like a plate of
beans to the United States.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte. His five-year term ends June 1
and his Christian Democrats are trailing in polls:
   ``There is absolute freedom of expression, which never in our
history has there been. All political and social sectors have access
to the media, which reflect ideological pluralism.
   ``But the FMLN has responded to that by permanently attacking the
most elemental rights of the population ...
   ``Each day the people's `No!' to authoritarianism and its
violence is louder. That clamor must carry us to a definitive peace
along the only acceptable path _ democracy within the framework of
law.''
</TEXT>
