<FIRST>r a PM-PresidentialBootmaker Bjt   03-13 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presidential Bootmaker, Bjt,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>These Boots Are Made For ... Presidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When President Bush rolled up his pants and showed
off his cowboy boots at an inaugural ball, Rocky Carroll couldn't
have asked for better advertising.
   Not that he needs it. Carroll's boots _ which he makes for
presidents, country-western singers and professional athletes, among
others _ are so popular that longtime customers have to drive around
the block a few times just to park at his RJ's Boot Co. shop.
   ``Before he became famous, he used to fix all my high heels,''
Donna Meyer said recently while picking up a pair of boots Carroll
repaired. ``Oh, he is still fixing them for me, but he is so busy
now.''
   ``I love what I do,'' Carroll said. ``I was raised in a shoe
shop. My mother said I used to suck on a leather heel and cut my
first tooth on an old heel.''
   Carroll's grandparents started the business in the east Texas
town of Tenaha. The craft was passed to his parents, who taught
Carroll. Carroll, who made his first boot at age 10, has passed the
trade to his son and daughter. They, in turn, operate two other
shops in Houston.
   Bush, for one, is getting to be a regular customer. The
president's office called before his recent Far East trip. The
request: four pairs of boots.
   The call came on a Friday afternoon. The White House wanted the
boots by Tuesday, a day before the president's departure.
   Carroll had the boots in Washington by Monday night. Among them
was a black pair that had a Chinese flag on the front shoe and an
American flag on its companion. Bush gave a pair to Chinese Premier
Li Peng.
   The 51-year-old bootmaker had earlier made a pair for Bush at the
request of Houston Police Department officers who escort the
president when he visits his hometown.
   The black size 11D had the outline of the state of Texas with the
Texas flag inside and his initials on the side.
   Bush apparently showed off his boots to then-President Reagan,
who called Carroll to place his own order _ two pair, size 10{B, of
brown and black ostrich.
   Carroll and his wife made their first trip to Washington late
last year to deliver the boots to Reagan. Carroll also gave another
pair to Bush, this time black alligator with the presidential seal.
   ``When we went into the Oval Office, he and the president were
teasing each other saying, `My boots are better looking than
yours,''' Carroll recalled. ``Bush was like a kid with a new toy.''
   His handmade boots are expensive toys, though, ranging in price
from $295 to $6,500.
   Among Carroll's other customers are country-western singers Larry
Gatlin and Willie Nelson; actor Patrick Swayze; race car driver A.J.
Foyt; several Houston Oilers; and Ringling Bros. and Barnum &amp; Bailey
Circus clowns.
   At the Black Tie and Boots Inaugural Ball, Bush wore black patent
leather boots with a Texas flag set in a gold map of the state with
a star designating Houston.
   Bush picked Carroll out of the crowd and thanked him. Since then,
the bootmaker said, his phone ``hasn't stoppped ringing.''
   ``One even wanted my autograph. I was so embarrassed. Why would
they want my autograph? I'm just an old cowboy,'' Carroll said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-IraqBattlefront     03-13 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Iraq Battlefront,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Settles On Gulf War Killing Ground</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Postwar Iraq, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   RAS AL-BISHA, Iraq (AP) _ The Iraqis manning their army's
southernmost observation post on the Iran-Iraq cease-fire line lay
in the sun, idly watching the Iranians in their outpost a few
hundred yards across the mouth of the Shatt-Al-Arab waterway.
   The Iranians do the same, peering through binoculars across the
estuary that flows into the Persian Gulf.
   The soldiers on both sides are waiting for a peace treaty between
their governments that will allow them to go home.
   The only sounds to intrude on the overpowering quiet are the
cries of sea gulls that wheel above and the waves from the gulf
breaking on the seaweed-strewn beach.
   The soldiers' biggest problem is the boredom _ and the hordes of
bugs that buzz over the marshy shoreline.
   Despite reports of violations of the 7-month-old cease-fire
further north, life in what was one of the bloodiest battlegrounds
of the 8-year Iran-Iraq war has assumed a sleepy tranquility.
   ``We've plenty of time now for fishing, playing cards and
reading,'' says the Iraqi officer who commands the small squad
manning the sandbagged post.
   ``Don't do that,'' a young Iraqi lieutenant quips as a reporter
tries to photograph the remains of an Iranian-built bridge and a
sunken vessel. ``The Iranians will take that as a violation of the
cease-fire.''
   Eleven months ago, this area was under constant Iraqi air and
artillery attack _ the main target the concrete bridge the Iranians
built to link the bridgehead on Iraq's Faw peninsula that they
captured in February 1986.
   For two years, the Iraqis tried and failed to dislodge Iranians
dug in around the marshlands ringing the battered oil terminal town
of Faw.
   Then, last April, they launched a surprise attack after weeks of
diversions and stealthy infiltration and recaptured Faw in a 36-hour
battle.
   It was the first of a chain of victories that pushed the Iranians
out of all Iraqi territory they had overrun and forced Tehran to
unconditionally accept a U.N. cease-fire resolution.
   A large sign erected at the entrance to Faw says 52,948 Iraqis
and more than 120,000 Iranians were killed in the battles for the
sandy peninsula.
   The Iraqi toll was the first indication that reporters for
Western news organizations have had of the scale of Baghdad's
losses. Unofficial estimates have put the Iraqi death toll for the
whole war at around 150,000.
   The claim of 120,000 Iranians killed merely in the fighting for
Faw is impossible to verify. The Iranians have only admitted to some
130,000 dead for the whole war, although Western analysts estimate
that is only a fraction of the true total.
   Iranian losses generally were considered to be at least three
times the Iraqi casualties, mainly because of the carnage in the
Iranians' human wave attacks against the well-entrenched Iraqis.
   Iraqi officers said more than 6.5 million shells were fired by
the two armies during the Iranian occupation of Faw.
   The ruined town, one of the few Iraqi towns overrun by the
Iranians, ``stands as a symbol of our sacrifices and heroism,'' said
Anwar Sa'eed al-Hadithi, governor of nearby Basra.
   He told The Associated Press that plans have been completed to
build a new urban center in Faw to replace the old town.
   Iraqi authorities last year launched a nationwide donation
campaign to collect money to rebuild Faw, which had a pre-war
population of 56,000.
   Similar drives were launched in neighboring Kuwait and other
Persian Gulf countries.
   Reliable Iraqi sources say millions of dollars have been
collected for the reconstruction, which is expected to start next
month on the anniversary of the liberation of Faw.
   The government has not spelled out its plans for the Faw port,
which before the war was a key oil export outlet to Japan and Europe.
   Rebuilding the port cannot start until Iran and Iraq reach
agreement in their deadlocked peace talks on clearing the
120-mile-long Shatt-al-Arab of sunken ships, war debris and silt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern 5thLd-Writethru a0447 03-13 1148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0447,1180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikebound Carrier Adds More Flights</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to DELETE extraneous word `About'; pickup 3rd
graf pvs, `Eastern ballyhooed ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines renewed flights to seven Latin
American cities Sunday and continued to lure bargain hunters to its
Northeast shuttle in an effort to rebuild despite a week-old strike.
   However, the airline's lure of $12 fares on the shuttle may have
worked too well. Several hundred would-be shuttle passengers in
Boston, New York and Washington were told they'd have to wait for
Monday morning flights because all evening flights were booked solid.
   Eastern ballyhooed the reopening of its Latin American routes as
a new start for the airline, which filed for bankruptcy protection
last week, blaming its pilots for honoring Machinists' picket lines
and plunging the carrier into a cash crisis.
   Service to three more South American cities, two domestic routes
and Montreal will begin later in the week, the airline said.
   ``What we're really saying is it is the start of a new, smaller,
restructured and viable Eastern Airlines,'' said Eastern spokesman
Robin Matell.
   Eastern lured customers on its 62 Boston-New York and New
York-Washington shuttle flights with the $12 weekend fares, down
from $69. Weekday fares begining Monday will be $49 one way, down
from the usual $99.
   Airline officials said 31,500 people crossed picket lines over
the weekend to take the cut-rate flights. Others tried to get aboard
the flights and failed.
   At Logan International Airport in Boston, stranded passengers
were told to show up at the Eastern terminal at 5:30 a.m. Monday,
when the first shuttle was slated to leave for New York.
   Officials at Washington National Airport said over 100 people who
were unable to get onto flights would have to spend the night at the
airport or make other travel arrangements.
   In New York, an undetermined number of people were stranded at
LaGuardia Airport.
   ``It's a bummer,'' said Terianne Tapia, who was up from New York
to visit her boyfriend in Boston. ``I have to be at work at 9 a.m.''
   Eastern officials said those passengers should have gotten to the
airport sooner.
   ``Those people were not stranded. We advertised the flights were
on a first-come, first-serve basis,'' Matell said. ``I'm sorry they
have to wait for the next flight, but they should have gotten there
earlier.''
   Asked if Eastern would pay for hotel accomodations, Matell said,
``Absolutely not.''
   However, Matell later said the passengers who missed flights
would be allowed to fly free during off-peak hours and for the same
$12 rate during peak hours _ if they had purchased round-trip
tickets over the weekend.
   Eastern, just nine days earlier the nation's seventh-largest
carrier with 1,040 daily flights, planned to put 75 planes into the
air Sunday. The first of the renewed Latin American routes took off
just before 4 p.m. for Quito, Ecuador, Eastern spokeswoman Virginia
Sanchez said.
   Matell said the shuttle and international routes were considered
the best place to deploy Eastern's limited resources and generate
revenue. A $365 million sale of the shuttle to New York developer
Donald Trump is pending, and Eastern's international routes are
among its most marketable assets.
   Meanwhile, Secretary of Transportation Samuel Skinner said on
CBS' ``Face The Nation'' that the Bush administration considers the
labor dispute ``none of our business'' and has no plans to
intervene. ``We are not in the business of running Eastern Airlines
or negotiating the contract for labor,'' Skinner said.
   Eastern hopes to be up to 140 flights a day by week's end, Matell
said. The highest number of flights in one day since the strike
began March 4 has been 93.
   During the first week of the strike, Eastern maintained one
thrice-weekly flight from Miami to Buenos Aires, Argentina, and
Santiago, Chile, as well as its East Coast shuttle service.
   Eastern's unions have accused Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern
parent Texas Air Corp., of trying to cannibalize the airline. Pilots
and flight attendants unions have honored Machinists' picket lines,
which went up when the 8,500-member union refused to grant $125
million in concessions to the money-losing airline.
   ``Today, Eastern is up and flying,'' company President Phil Bakes
said Sunday in a statement. ``With this, we begin building the great
airline we've always known Eastern could and should be.''
   Bakes was a vice president at Continental Airlines in 1983 when
Lorenzo filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, as Eastern did
on Thursday in New York.
   Former Eastern Chairman Frank Borman said Sunday on ABC's ``This
Week with David Brinkley that he knew ``of no one in the management
or on the board of Texas Air who wanted bankruptcy.''
   Continental gradually rebuilt its schedule while in bankruptcy
reorganization, but Eastern unions say management won't be helped as
it was at Continental by union workers crossing picket lines.
   Eastern estimated Sunday that out of 3,600 regular pilots it had
200 flying.
   The Air Line Pilots Association said the Latin American routes
are more complicated than the Boston-New York-Washington shuttle,
which had provided nearly all of Eastern's strike service, and it
doubted the company had enough experienced pilots to keep flying
them.
   ALPA also said the company's few pilots will be grounded by
Federal Aviation Administration limits on flying time, such as 30
hours within seven days. Matell said Eastern has had no significant
increase in delays.
   Matell said no decision had been made yet on when to bring in
non-contract workers to replace strikers. The company has 1,500
employees working, having laid off 9,500 non-union workers last week.
   In Atlanta, about 2,000 striking workers and their families
joined for a pep rally near the airport. Lorenzo was the main target
of slogans painted and pasted on shirts, cars, kites and even a dog.
   Matell said Eastern flew 10,200 passengers Saturday, approaching
capacity, and had long lines again Sunday.
   Lawyers for the Machinists plan to go to court this week seeking
an estimated $7.5 million in back wages frozen when the company
filed bankruptcy on payday for most Machinists workers. The pilots'
next paycheck was due March 15.
   ``The only good thing about bankruptcy is that it hinders
(Lorenzo's) ability to slice this thing up like a piece of salami,''
said Rick Chapman, secretary-treasurer of the ALPA local.
   Departures scheduled from Miami starting Sunday were: Bogota,
Colombia; Guatemala City; Lima, Peru; Panama City, Panama; Quito,
Ecuador; Guayaquil, Ecuador; and San Jose, Costa Rica. Thrice-weekly
flights were planned to start later in the week for Asuncion,
Paraguay; Cali, Colombia; and La Paz, Bolivia.
   ``Our loads are looking good,'' said Eastern spokeswoman Virginia
Sanchez, noting heavy passenger turnout for flights to Panama City
and Lima.
   The company also intends to resume thrice-daily flights between
Miami and Puerto Rico on Monday along with service to Montreal, then
add direct flights later this week between Washington and Boston.
</TEXT>
