<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-13 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0457 to restore slugline</HEAD>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Lossia and Connie Whitmer have
teamed up to clean cars and canines, but some customers bark at
their humor.
   The Walnut Lake Car Wash-Dog Wash in West Bloomfield Township are
side-by-side businesses that share a common sign. But Lossia tells
customers their dirty dogs are welcome to ride through the car wash
he manages perched on top of their cars.
   The joke doesn't wash with everybody, he admitted.
   ``Well, the husbands think it's funny, and some say they wish
they could run their dogs through the car wash,'' he said. ``But
some of the wives are real sensitive about their poodles, and they
don't like the idea.
   ``One lady pulled up with her dog and she just took off when I
said, `Don't worry, we haven't had a death in a couple of years.' ''
   Dog owners who stick around can expect to pay about $20 to have
their pet washed, blown dry, brushed and manicured at Whitmer's
establishment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Myron Warshauer's parking garages aren't exactly
like Disneyland, but they do give new meaning to the words ``theme
park.''
   Warshauer has set about filling the buildings with music and
theme floors designed to help drivers find their vehicles. He owns
three garages in Chicago with city, country and show themes,
respectively.
   ``Remember Your Car Location! You Have Parked in New York,''
admonish large signs on the fifth floor of one garage. In the
burgundy-tiled elevator vestibule, a piped-in Frank Sinatra belts
out ``New York, New York.''
   One level up, the strains of ``Moon over Miami'' waft through the
floor.
   ``People historically have kind of looked down on parking
garages,'' said Warshauer, president of Standard Parking Corp. ``You
go to an office building and find millions of dollars of marble in
the lobby, and the garage is a dungeon.''
   The third-generation parking man is changing that.
   He has gotten a trademark on the phrase ``Ambiance in Parking''
and plans two more garages. One will feature large photographs of
Chicago artworks and classical music on each level. The other will
give floors over to singers such as Louis Armstrong and Elvis
Presley.
   ``You could park your car to `Don't Be Cruel' and be listening to
`Blue Suede Shoes' by the time you're at the elevators.'' Warshauer
said.
   Other garages also are using the idea.
   At General Parking Corp.'s new South Loop Self Park Garage, black
and white city scenes on porcelain panels decorate the 12 levels.
And next month, an 8-by-125-foot ceramic mural is to be unveiled. A
montage of Chicago scenes will wrap around the garage exterior.
</TEXT>
