<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0740 03-13 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0740,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stock Prices Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATE with closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen in Tokyo on
Monday, but stock prices closed lower as investors reacted to
concern over rising U.S. inflation.
   After opening higher at 129.38 yen, the dollar continued to post
gains, finishing the day's dealings at 129.57 yen, up 0.69 yen from
Friday's close of 128.88 yen. It moved in a range of 129.38-129.63.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 45.33-point gainer Friday, shed 148.82 points, or
0.47 percent, to move to 31,552.96 by the close of the trading day.
   ``The dollar opened stronger in reaction to gains in New York
last Friday,'' said a dealer with the Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo.
   ``But trading lost steam as investors took to the sidelines ahead
of the release of Wednesday's U.S. trade figures for February,'' he
said, speaking with the condition he not be identified.
   The dollar strengthened in New York Friday when the U.S. Labor
Department reported that non-farm payrolls added 289,000 jobs in
February and civilian unemployment fell to 5.1 percent from the
previous month for the lowest level since December 1973.
   That in turn fueled speculation the U.S. Federal Reserve would
increase interest rates to cool down the economy in a tightening
labor market, creating the prospect of higher interest rates and a
more attractive dollar for foreign investors.
   But stock traders in Tokyo said shares fell as investors reacted
to concern that higher interest rates would in turn spark U.S.
inflation.
   Shares of light electronics and shipbuilders held firm in the
first section of the exchange, while others fell almost across the
board, according to traders.
</TEXT>
