<HEAD>Barry Levinson Wins Directors Guild Award For `Rain Man'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Levinson said the acting of
Dustin Hoffman and Tom Cruise in ``Rain Man'' helped him win this
year's best film direction award by the Directors Guild of America.
   ``Unless you get performances on the screen, all else will
fail,'' Levinson said in accepting the award Saturday night.
   Only three times in 41 years has the guild's award been different
from the Academy Award for directing. The Oscar presentations are
March 29.
   ``Rain Man'' concerns an autistic savant and his hustling young
brother, played respectively by Hoffman and Cruise, who are on a
cross-country journey of discovery.
   Levinson assumed direction of the film after Steven Spielberg,
Sydney Pollack and Martin Brest had undertaken the project and
abandoned it.
   The guild's 9,000 members selected Levinson over four other
nominees: Alan Parker of the controversial civil-rights film
``Mississippi Burning''; Robert Zemeckis, who engineered the
animated-live action blockbuster ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'';
Charles Crichton, director of the crime-caper comedy ``A Fish Called
Wanda''; and Mike Nichols, who brought the corporate Cinderella saga
``Working Girl'' to the screen.
   Zemeckis is the only guild nominee not nominated for the best
director Oscar. In Zemeckis' place, the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences nominated Martin Scorsese, director of the ``The
Last Temptation of Christ,'' which has been criticized by religious
groups as blasphemous.
</TEXT>
