<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident public school teachers are scheduled
to meet in the capital next weekend to discuss a possible nationwide
strike in their demand for a salary increase, the Excelsior news
service said Sunday.
   Excelsior quoted Teodoro Palomino, head of the dissident National
Schoolteachers Coordinate, as saying teachers have tentatively
scheduled a strike for April 17.
   Palomino reportedly called the proposed strike a ``defensive,
desperate action.''
   The dissident teachers have held three massive marches in Mexico
City in the past month to demand a 100 percent salary increase and
the ouster of a labor boss they call corrupt and inept. Teachers
make aboout $170 a month.
   An estimated 50,000 teachers on Tuesday took part in the latest
march, which snarled traffic and closed about 3,800 schools in the
capital.
   There were other scattered one-day walkouts nationwide.
   The dissidents blame the longtime head of the teachers' union,
Carlos Jongitud Barrios, for their plight. They say Jongitud has
used his 17 years as union leader to amass power and a personal
fortune instead of improving the lot of teachers.
   They are an estimated 1.2 million public school teachers who are
members of the National Union of Education Workers. The coordinate
is made up of union members, but is not recognized by the government.
