<FIRST>r i PM-Poland     03-13 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chief Opposition Negotiator Says Future of Political Accord Uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition's chief negotiator says
political reforms laid out during five weeks of talks with the
government are ``hanging by a hair'' because of apparent resistance
by Communist hardliners.
   Historian Bronislaw Geremek said Sunday that his side had
received a government draft on a new electoral procedure that lacked
``basic political decisions that we had agreed upon.
   ``Is it that someone simply forgot about them? Or maybe there are
forces on the other side that are strong enough to block the whole
contract,'' he said.
   The opposition received the draft Saturday, and Geremek made his
comments Sunday at a meeting of the opposition's Citizens Committee.
   The committee gathered to evaluate progress in the historic talks
on reinstating the banned Solidarity free trade union movement and
salvaging the battered economy. The opposition is demanding free
elections, greater access to the media and a say in the formation of
economic policy.
   Hearing the report by Geremek, Citizens Committee members adopted
a statement calling for ``full realization of Solidarity's demands''
and expressing concern at ``the apparent tendency by the government
side to limit democratic changes.''
   ``A dozen days before the end of the round-table talks, it seems
that the whole deal is hanging by a hair,'' Geremek told the
gathering.
   Solidarity spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz, at a news conference
Sunday, also spoke about some points missing in the draft, but he
said it was too early to raise an alarm.
   Neither he nor Geremek said what agreements might be lacking in
the draft.
   The 120-member Citizens' Committee was formed last year by
Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa to bring together leaders of the
main opposition groups.
   On Thursday, government negotiators agreed to democratic
elections for a revived Senate and that 35 percent of the 460 seats
in the Sejm, the present unicameral parliament, could be open to
independent candidates.
   It has not been determined how many seats or how much power the
Senate will have. In return for the Senate, the opposition agreed to
the creation to a strenghthened presidency whose occupant would have
the power to dissolve the legislature.
   Elections are tentatively scheduled for June 4.
   The ruling Communist Party's 230-member Central Committee is
expected to ratify, either this week or next week, the agreements
made at the negotiations.
   Both sides have said a pact on the talks should be signed by
April 3.
   Poland's leader, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, told supporters
Saturday that they must be ready to stand ``face-to-face in a
democratic test'' in the elections, the official PAP news agency
reported Sunday.
   It said Jaruzelski, addressing more than 2,500 party officials,
told them their job ``is not only mobilizing people to come to the
polling boxes anymore.''
   The goal is ``to elect the best so that those best are our people
_ members of the party, members of allied parties, non-party members
_ really independent but standing on the ground of socialism,'' he
said according to the text distributed by PAP.
   Solidarity, legally chartered in the fall of 1980 as the first
free union movement in the Soviet bloc, was crushed by a December
1981 military crackdown and outlawed the following year.
</TEXT>
