<FIRST>r a PM-Colonist-Homecoming     03-13 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colonist-Homecoming,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Descendants Revisiting Birthplace of Massachusetts Pioneer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Plimoth in 7th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen descendants of Massachusetts pioneer
William Bradford are making a pilgrimage to Britain to celebrate the
birth of their ancestor, who fled to the New World four centuries
ago in search religious freedom.
   ``Everybody's very excited, I think it's a once-in-a-lifetime
thing,'' said Marion Vuilleumier, the 11th great-granddaughter of
Bradford and an organizer of the trip.
   The group, members of a descendant's society called the Gov.
William Bradford Compact, are leaving Tuesday for Austerfield,
Yorkshire.
   The celebration of Bradford's 399th birthday will be held there
Sunday and is expected to draw representatives of Queen Elizabeth II
and the American embassy.
   The homecoming was arranged after Ms. Vuilleumier visited
Austerfield and learned that a celebration was planned for March 19,
which is believed to be Bradford's birthday.
   Bradford, who sailed for America aboard the Mayflower, was among
a group of people seeking to separate from the Church of England.
The group formed what later would become the Congregationalist
movement.
   He was the second governor of the Plymouth Colony, which was
established in 1620, and is best remembered for his chronicle of the
settlement. ``Of Plymouth Plantation,'' is a primary source for the
history of Massachusetts colonists, said Jeff Scotland, a spokesman
for the Plimoth Plantation museum devoted to Massachusetts' early
history.
   Bradford, who died in 1657, and his co-religionists found
religious freedom by establishing a community under their own,
sometimes rigid, rules, said Scotland, who occasionally portrays
Bradford at the museum.
   ``It takes a lot of courage to cross the Atlantic in a leaky boat
and to carve out a home in the wilderness,'' Scotland said. ``To be
so principled that you're willing to do that just so you can worship
without being thrown in jail, that makes a statement.''
   The Bradford Compact, formed about 40 years ago, has about 400
members and holds annual meetings in Plymouth.
   Ms. Vuilleumier said the British recognition of Bradford's
historic status seems a fitting ending to the centuries-old rift
with the Mother Country.
   ``I think he would have been pleased to see it,'' she said. ``He
would have been very pleased to be vindicated.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Vietnam-Reunion     03-13 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Reunion,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Point Honors Fallen Vietnam Vet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On April 16, 1968, Army Capt. Thomas Jay
Hayes IV was killed in Vietnam after dragging two wounded comrades
to safety as enemy forces overwhelmed his platoon.
   On Sunday, Hayes became the latest fallen hero to have a building
on the West Point campus renamed in his honor.
   As his classmates from the West Point Class of '66 gathered for
the dedication ceremony in the spotless gymnasium previously known
as the East Gym, they reminisced about Hayes' leadership, heroism
and potential for greatness _ the qualities that led the academy to
rename the gym in his memory.
   ``He inspired all of us,'' said classmate John Wheeler, former
secretary of the Securities and Exchange Commission and president of
the Washington-based Center for the Vietnam Generation.
   ``We knew this guy would (have been) a statesman _ not just a
soldier, but a statesman _ and that gave us an extra boost,'' said
Col. C. Hilton Dunn Jr., now assigned to the Army Corps of Engineers.
   Several other buildings on the campus, which lies 50 miles north
of New York City, have also been named after West Point graduates
who, like Hayes, showed exceptional leadership as a cadet, excelled
in athletics or some area of study, and were killed in action.
   A few weeks ago, a different gymnasium was named after Carl
Robert Arvin, Class of '65, who died in Vietnam at age 24. More men
will be honored in the same way, said Wheeler.
   The program to name buildings after the fallen heroes was
initiated by West Point's commander, Gen. David Palmer.
   ``He's updating West Point by bringing the best of our past into
the present,'' said Wheeler. ``By finding men like Tommy (Hayes),
he's re-igniting at West Point the light of inspiration.''
   Wheeler, who counted Hayes among his best friends, said he
researched Hayes' death until he was satisfied that he knew exactly
what had happened.
   ``His platoon was helicoptered into a landing zone and instantly
hit by a huge force of overwhelming enemy fire,'' Wheeler recalled.
``It was daylight hours, and they were terribly exposed. ... He
dragged one wounded man back to safety and then another back to
safety.''
   The men he rescued lived, but Hayes was shot and killed on the
spot.
   Hayes, whose father and grandfather attended West Point, had been
ninth in his class. Nearly all of Hayes' 579 classmates went to
Vietnam; 30 died there, more than any other class, said Wheeler.
   Hayes was sent over as an engineer to handle battlefield
construction, but instead volunteered for infantry duty. After his
yearlong Vietnam tour was over, he signed up for another. He was
killed halfway through it at age 26 _ ``an old man'' considering the
average age of a soldier in Vietnam was 19, said Wheeler.
   ``It was tough. It was almost like losing a brother,'' Robert
Kesmodel, now a Baltimore businessman, said of learning that Hayes
had died.
   Col. Mac Hayes, now a West Point regiment commander, was in
Vietnam when he read in Stars and Stripes that his classmate had
been killed.
   ``It's always a devastating thing to find out,'' said Hayes, who
was not related to Thomas Hayes. ``The people who tended to do
things and be leaders unfortunately were the casualties'' because
they served on the front lines.
   Wheeler said the survivors share an intense, triple bond: ``It's
Vietnam and (the) Tet (Offensive of '68); then burying the most
killed from any class (in Vietnam); then coming home and feeling so
alone.''
   But he said Sunday's reunion ``took another bite out of the
unnecessary bitterness and pain that our country feels from the war
in Vietnam ... by affirming the integrity in Tom's life and the
choices he made.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-MexicoEarthquake     03-13 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico Earthquake,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Reported near Acapulco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake struck near Acapulco,
Mexico, authorities said today.
   The quake struck at 9:09 p.m. Sunday MST and was centered 50
miles northeast of the Mexican resort, said Russ Needham, a
geophysicist at the U.S. Geological Survey's National Earthquake
Information Center.
   The tremor measured 5.5 on the Richter scale, he said, but added,
``I would not expect any damage out of it.''
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of magnitude 3.5 can cause slight damage in the
local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe
damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of widespread
heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage.
</TEXT>
