<FIRST>u a AM-HelicopterCrash 4thLd-Writethru a0470 03-13 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helicopter Crash, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0470,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helicopter Crashes Over Desert; 12 Dead, Three Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPATE with spokesman identifying model
as twin-engine CH-3E, minor editing, picks up 5th graf pvs; SUBS 9th graf,
`Besich said ...' to conform, include that copter was Vietnam-era; SUBS
final graf with one graf with more background on copter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY12; LaserPhoto NY12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force Reserve helicopter crashed and
burned Sunday during a night training mission, killing 12 people
aboard and leaving three missing, officials said.
   The twin-engine CH-3E ``Jolly Green Giant'' helicopter was flying
with another chopper from Davis-Monthan Air Force to the Air Force's
Gila Bend Gunnery Range when it went down at about 7:45 p.m.,
according to a base spokesman, Capt. Mark Besich.
   The crashed occurred in an uninhabited area 20 miles north of
Tucson.
   ``I looked up and I seen a yellow ball, like flames, coming out
of the back,'' said Mike Skreka. ``About four seconds later it hit
the ground.''
   Emergency crews from Davis-Monthan and Tucson International
Airport were dispatched to the scene.
   Twelve people were pronounced dead at the crash site and three
others were unaccounted for and presumed dead, said Pima County
Sheriff's Sgt. Tom Taylor.
   An unidentified sheriff's office dispatcher said another witness
told deputies that he ``heard a loud pop and then saw it go down.''
   The dispatcher said the second helicopter continued flying on to
Ryan Field, a small airport about 25 miles west of Tucson.
   Besich said the CH-3E helicopter usually carries a crew of four
and has a capacity of 22 passengers. He said he knew nothing about
the people aboard the Vietnam-era helicopter that crashed, or how
many may have been injured.
   Both helicopters are assigned to the 71st Special Operations
Squadron at Davis-Monthan, he said.
   The site of the crash was about half-way between Marana, Ariz.,
and Avra Valley, Ariz., according to Besich.
   He said Air Force officials launched another helicopter to fly to
the crash site, but he had few details about what that crew had
learned.
   The 71st Special Operations Squadron was known as the 302nd
Squadron, and based at Luke Air Force Base near Phoenix, until June
1987 when it was transferred to Davis-Monthan, Besich said.
   The CH-3E ``Jolly Green Giant,'' which was most noted for its use
in combat rescues during the Vietnam War, is made by Sikorsky,
according to Jane's All The World's Aircraft. But Boeing makes
several Chinook helicopters with the CH-designation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
