<DOCNO> AP890313-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan     03-13 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudan Cabinet Resigns, Mahdi Seeks To Form New Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Prime Minister Sadek
Mahdi has resigned under pressure from the military in a move that
could open the way for peace talks with rebels in the south.
   The State Council, Sudan's collective presidency, accepted the
resignation on Sunday and Mahdi began trying to form a new Cabinet.
   Newspaper reports indicated Mahdi, who submitted the resignation
late Saturday, faced a struggle in creating a Cabinet and it was
uncertain when a new government might be formed.
   The reports said the armed forces were insisting on two seats in
what had been a 21-member Cabinet, but Mahdi had not offered them
any. They said Mahdi is trying to neutralize the military' power by
bargaining with trade unions and professional associations.
   Army officers, joined by unions and some political groups, issued
an ultimatum three weeks ago for Mahdi to create a broad-based
government and open peace talks with the Sudan People's Liberation
Army after six years of civil war.
   Mahdi's Umma Party was dominant in the old Cabinet and its junior
party was the National Islamic Front, a Moslem fundamentalist party.
   Newspapers said the National Islamic Front is not expected to
take part in a new government because of disputes over Islamic law.
Islamic law is in force, but it has been largely ignored and its
penalties have not been enforced since the 1985 ouster of dictator
Gaafar Nimeiri.
   Many people in southern Sudan are Christians or animists. They
oppose Islamic law and the Khartoum government, which is controlled
by predominantly Moslem north Sudan.
   The southern rebels demand more autonomy and greater shares in
aid and development programs.
   Mahdi has been facing his worst political crisis since he became
head of the government after general elections in April 1986.
   The centrist Democratic Unionist Party was the second-largest
party in Mahdi's coalition until they walked out in January to
protest the government's economic policies and Mahdi's refusal to
bring a peace plan before the Cabinet. Mahdi then formed a new
Cabinet with the National Islamic Front.
   Ten days ago, Mahdi and representatives of 65 political groups
and unions agreed to a proposed new government and peace overtures
toward the rebels. But the Islamic Front rejected the plan, saying
it jeopardized Islamic law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
