<DOCNO> AP890313-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     03-13 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued to rise against the Japanese
yen in Tokyo today, and stock prices declined because of a spreading
political stock scandal and worry about higher U.S. inflation,
traders said.
   After opening at 129.38 yen, its low for the day, the dollar
finished trading at 129.57 yen, up 0.69 yen from Friday's closing of
128.88 yen. Its highest level during the day was 129.63 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
fell 148.82 points, or 0.47 percent, closing the day at 31,552.96.
On Friday the index gained 45.33 points.
   An estimated 550 million shares were traded on the exchange's
first section, down from 915 million shares on Friday.
   ``There's the Recruit scandal and concern of higher inflation in
the United States and here as well,'' said a trader with Nomura
Securities Co., Japan's largest brokerage.
   Parliamentary debate on Japan's budget for next fiscal year
remained stalled today as opposition parties demanded that former
Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone testify on his links to a
stock-profiteering scandal that has shaken Japanese politics.
   In the scandal, Recruit Co., an information services
conglomerate, allegedly provided bargain-priced shares in a
subsidiary to influential politicians and business leaders in
exchange for special favors.
   The scandal has led to the resignation of three Cabinet
ministers, and news reports today said 15 governing-party
legislators have received Recruit funds since the scandal surfaced.
   The Nomura trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
investors were concerned that U.S. inflation may rise if the U.S.
Federal Reserve raises interest rates following Friday's release of
lower unemployment figures for February.
   He said stock prices also declined because of the upcoming end of
the Japanese fiscal year. ``We'll be more sure of the market's
actual direction later this week or at the start of next week,'' he
said.
   Many Japanese businesses begin their fiscal year April 1.
   The dollar rose quickly in early Tokyo trading following gains in
New York on Friday due to the unemployment report and prospects of
higher U.S. interest rates, which would make the dollar more
attractive to foreign investors, traders said. It then slowed during
the afternoon.
   ``Trading lost steam as investors took to the sidelines ahead of
the release Wednesday of U.S. trade figures for February,'' said a
dealer with a major commercial bank in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
