<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     03-13 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in early European trading
today, upward movement checked by fear of central bank intervention
and a lack of incentive to move before Wednesday's release of new
U.S. trade figures, foreign currency dealers said.
   Gold prices fell slightly.
   Dealers said factors pointing to a higher dollar include
speculation about rising U.S. interest rates following surprisingly
strong February employment figures.
   But the market is too afraid of central banks to push the dollar
aggressively higher, said Bernd Hartwig, chief dealer of
Norddeutsche Landesbank Girozentrale in Hanover, West Germany.
   ``One can assume that interest rate speculation will take the
dollar higher, but the fear of central banks is very much present,''
he said.
   A dealer at a large Frankfurt bank said ``the next point to look
for are the U.S. trade figures.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.69 yen to a closing 129.57. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 129.75 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.8640 West German marks, up from 1.8629
   _1.5915 Swiss francs, down from 1.5918
   _6.3215 French francs, up from 6.3185
   _2.1048 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1020
   _1,367.00 Italian lire, up from 1,306.00
   _1.1972 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1987
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7175, slightly more
expensive for buyers than $1.7159 Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $393.25 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $393.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $392.90, down from $393.50 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 30 cents to close at a bid
$394.85.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.05 a troy ounce,
up from Friday's $6.00.
</TEXT>
