<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BigBendFire     03-13 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Big Bend Fire,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blaze Smaller Than Thought; Additional Crews Arriving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIG BEND NATIONAL PARK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More firefighters were
recruited to battle the biggest blaze in this park's 45-year history
after it blackened 615 acres of oak, pine and juniper woodlands.
   A helicopter flight over the fire Sunday evening revealed it
covered much less than the 1,200 acres estimated earlier.
   ``That actually puts us in better shape, but it's still the
largest fire in the park's history and it probably will keep
spreading for a couple of days before we get it under control,''
said park spokesman Jim Paxon.
   ``Unless winds pick up, we should get a good handle on this thing
Monday. Then I'd say it should be a couple more days before it's
under control. That's if we don't get any winds.''
   The National Weather Service forecast temperatures in the 90s
with light winds and no precipitation for the southwest Texas area
during the next few days.
   More than 100 firefighters from the U.S. Forest Service, the Park
Service, the Bureau of Land Management and the New Mexico Department
of Forestry battled the fire Sunday. Paxon said about 160 additional
personnel had been requested from the Inter-agency Fire Center in
Boise, Idaho, to fight the blaze.
   Officials also planned to use three helicopters to dump water on
hot spots in the fire, which is burning in the High Chisos mountains
of this Rhode Island-size park along the Rio Grande.
   No injuries were reported and no structures were in danger,
authorities said.
   But fire officials were concerned about a pair of Peregrine
falcon nests within 1{ miles of the flames. Paxon said the nests,
which shelter at least four of the endangered birds, weren't at risk
from the flames but would be protected if winds shifted.
   The blaze was believed to have been started by human
carelessness, authorities said.
   About 100 campers, mostly college students on spring break, were
evacuated when the blaze was reported by hikers Saturday. The area's
seven hiking trails also were closed.
</TEXT>
