<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths     03-13 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT cycle designation. No separates have
moved for the PMs cycle.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Philip Reed</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RYE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip D. Reed, a former General Electric Co.
chairman who served in a series of assignments for the federal
government during World War II, died Friday after a long illness. He
was 89.
   He joined GE in 1926 and became chairman of the board at age 40.
Among the posts he held during World War II, when he left the
company temporarily, was chief of the U.S. Mission for Economic
Affairs in London.
   After the war, he led the company's conversion back to production
of consumer goods from the manufacture of military equipment.
   Reed became a director of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York
after retiring from GE in 1958, serving six years as chairman.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Frederick ``Solly'' Seeman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   S. Frederick ``Solly'' Seeman, a national
amateur featherweight boxing champion and a professional lightweight
contender in the 1920s, died Saturday at age 87.
   Seeman, who won 118 of 120 of his professional bouts, was a
member of the 1920 U.S. Olympic team and was once referred to by
Jack Dempsey as ``the smartest boxer I ever knew.'' After his boxing
career, he was the owner of Commercial Machinery Co. in New York.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Carlos Terry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANHAM, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Terry, a former reserve guard for the
Washington Bullets basketball team, died Sunday in a two-car
collision. He was 32.
   Police said a preliminary investigation showed that the car was
going at a high speed and that alcohol contributed to the accident,
which occured on the northbound lanes of Interstate 95.
   Terry, who attended Winston-Salem State University, signed with
the Bullets in 1980 and scored an average of 3 points per game.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Skeeter Vaughan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEQUIM, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Skeeter Vaughan, a Cherokee Inidian whose
knife-throwing and tomahawk skills led him to a career as actor and
stuntman in movies and television, died Wednesday of a heart attack.
He was 66.
   Vaughan appeared in more than 100 movies, television shows and
commercials. His film credits included ``The Last of the Mohicans,''
``Revolution,'' and ``The Great White Hope.'' His TV work included
``Magnum P.I.,'' ``Gunsmoke'' and ``The Six Million Dollar Man.''
   Vaughan, whose Indian name was Grey Otter, began in show business
as a knife-thrower in a medicine show. He was a charter member of
the Hollywood Stuntmen's Hall of Fame.
</TEXT>
