<FIRST>r a PM-McGivern-Parole     03-13 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McGivern-Parole,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Years After Clemency, Convicted Cop-Killer May Go Free</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted cop-killer whose clemency three
years ago drew a sharp rebuke from then-Vice President George Bush
could taste freedom this week, but the controversy over his case may
linger on.
   Gary McGivern, serving 25 years to life for the 1968 shooting he
insists he didn't commit, is to appear for the third time before the
state Board of Parole since getting clemency.
   ``He's going to be paroled,'' predicted Michael Kavanagh, the
Ulster County district attorney who prosecuted McGivern and wants
him to remain behind bars.
   McGivern's long fight for freedom has attracted the support of an
unusual array of people including folk singer Pete Seeger, liberal
attorney William Kunstler and conservative columnist William F.
Buckley.
   McGivern and fellow inmate Charles Culhane received life
sentences for the shooting death of William Fitzgerald, a
Westchester County deputy.
   Prosecutors said McGivern, Culhane and inmate Robert Bowerman
tried to escape from a car while being transported for a court
appearance. Fitzgerald and Bowerman died from gunshot wounds and
McGivern and Culhane were wounded.
   McGivern and Culhane have maintained Bowerman acted alone but a
second deputy in the car, Joseph Singer, said they were involved in
the escape attempt.
   The two men were convicted in a 1975 retrial after a first trial
ended in a hung jury and an appeals court threw out their
convictions in a second trial, citing jury selection errors and
inconsistency in Singer's testimony.
   McGivern became eligible for a parole hearing after Gov. Mario
Cuomo granted clemency on New Year's Eve 1985. The board has
rejected McGivern twice, but at his last hearing in December 1987,
he was allowed to reapply in 14 months instead of the maximum 24
months. That, said Kavanagh, means McGivern is likely to be released.
   ``By the board's own rules, if there's a (wait) of less than two
years, you don't consider the crime, just the institutional record
and the progress,'' explained Edward Elwin, executive director of
the parole board.
   After 20 years in maximum-security prisons, McGivern was moved in
May to a medium-security institution.
   The prospect that the 44-year-old inmate might go free had
prompted prison guards and law enforcement officials to denounce
Cuomo in the past.
   Shortly after Cuomo granted the clemency, Bush went on the attack.
   ``I can tell you one thing about the difference between a liberal
politician and a conservative one: Governor Ronald Reagan kept cop
killers in jail,'' Bush told a New York City political dinner. At
the time, Cuomo was considered a contender for the 1988 Democratic
presidential nomination.
   As lieutenant governor, Cuomo recommended McGivern for clemency
in 1979 after he passed two lie detector tests, but then-Gov. Hugh
Carey refused.
   Cuomo was elected governor in 1982. Two years later, Singer shot
himself to death outside his home in Berwick, Pa. Police said he
left no suicide note.
   Then, six years after his original recommendation, Cuomo signed
the clemency papers himself.
   ``It was a very difficult call. This man is not a cop killer,''
he said.
   Kavanagh, however, insists McGivern is a murderer and a ``con
man'' who has fooled a lot of people.
   ``If this kid wasn't a nice, white, Irish boy who had some very
serious connections with the rich and powerful, this never would
have happened,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
