<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-13 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record High Temperatures Set Across South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell in the northern Pacific Coast region today, while the
South sizzled in record heat that topped 90 degrees in some places
and even hit 100 in one Texas town.
   Low pressure off the Pacific Coast brought showers to northern
California and western Oregon, with snow in some of the higher
elevations. A snow advisory was in effect this morning for the
Cascade Mountains of Oregon.
   The region has had a wet month; a total of 3{ inches of rain has
fallen in Portland, Ore., so far in March.
   Wind gusts of up to 70 mph were reported around Reno, Nev., late
Sunday, and a high wind watch has been posted for today for western
Nevada.
   Across the South and Southwest, several record temperatures were
set Sunday for the date.
   Record highs included Alamogordo, N.M., with 87 degrees;
Albuquerque, N.M., 82; Casper, Wyo., 65; El Paso, Texas, 89; Ely,
Nev., 68; Greer, S.C., 76; Las Vegas, Nev., 86; Lubbock, Texas, 94;
Memphis, Tenn., 84; Midland, Texas, 95; Mobile, Ala., 85; Roswell,
N.M., 93; Tucson, Ariz., 93; and Winslow, Ariz., 80.
   Tucson had its sixth consecutive day of record high temperatures,
while Winslow had its fifth.
   Childress, Texas, though, was hotter. It recorded 100 degrees,
the nation's high temperature.
   The forecast for today: widespread rain showers in Washington,
Oregon and northern California; scattered rain showers in the
northern half of the Plateau region, with snow showers over much of
Montana; scattered rain from the Ohio and Tennessee valleys to
central Virginia and North Carolina; and possible rain mixed with
snow or sleet in the higher elevations of the southern Appalachians.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 30s and 40s in the
northern and middle Atlantic Coast states, from the Appalachians
across to portions of the northern Plains and northern Rockies to
much of Washington; in the 70s and 80s from Southern California
across the desert Southwest, the southern Rockies, the southern
Plains and the Gulf Coast states to Florida; in the 90s in parts of
southwestern Texas; and in the 50s and 60s in most of the rest of
the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation in the Lower 48 states at 2 a.m.
EST ranged from 4 degrees below zero at Massena, N.Y., to 77 degrees
at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 58 fair; Boston 23 cloudy; Buffalo 15 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 55 foggy; Cincinnati 38 showers; Cleveland 26
partly cloudy; Detroit 24 partly cloudy; Miami 57 fair; New York 25
windy; Philadelphia 26 fair; Pittsburgh 25 cloudy; Portland, Maine,
16 fair; Washington 34 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 33 drizzle; Chicago 35 cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 62 fair; Denver 41 fair; Des Moines 35 foggy; Indianapolis 36
showers; Kansas City 38 foggy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 33 foggy;
Nashville 51 cloudy; New Orleans 58 foggy; St. Louis 43 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 48 fair; Anchorage 18 fair; Las Vegas 67 fair;
Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 72 partly cloudy; Salt Lake City 49
cloudy; San Diego 57 fair; San Francisco 53 drizzle; Seattle 41
cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 10 fair; Toronto 14 fair.
</TEXT>
