<FIRST>r a PM-Hostage-Artist     03-13 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostage-Artist,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artist's Daily Subject Is Hostage Terry Anderson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE WOODLANDS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a warm breeze carries the breath
of spring to the serenity of her suburban Houston home, Maureen
Seeba surrounds herself with the horror and anguish of a conflict
half a world away.
   Each day, the professional artist tries to work on a portrait of
Terry Anderson, who on Thursday will reach the fourth anniversary of
his abduction in Beirut, Lebanon.
   Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, is the longest held of 15 foreign hostages in Lebanon,
including nine Americans believed kidnapped by pro-Iranian Shiite
Moslems.
   ``They're easy to forget about when you live like this _ with a
good life, and your kids are at home, and you have enough food to
eat, and you just have to decide where you want to go each day,''
Mrs. Seeba said.
   She focused her artistic interest on Anderson after she saw the
newsman's plea to President Reagan in a tape released by his captors
last Oct. 31.
   ``It was just very heartbreaking,'' she says. ``He's been over
there four years and I have to ask myself, `What have I been doing
the past four years?' because I really haven't been that aware of
him.''
   So in between paintings of flowers, boats and people, the
32-year-old artist began painting likenesses of Anderson _ haunting
portraits that chronicle his ordeal. Nearly all are character
studies of his face. Some show him with a beard. Others are
clean-shaven. Some are in a single color. Others are multihued.
   She has a couple dozen paintings and has thrown out maybe 25 or
30 she didn't like. Her favorite is a yellow portrait showing a
nearly emotionless Anderson.
   ``I'm sure at this point he's about drained of any expression,''
she says. ``The yellow is like a nuclear flash. It's so intense. But
it also could signify the yellow ribbons that are not hanging in
everyone's doorways. I guess that's why I like it.''
   She said she has not contacted any members of Anderson's family,
including his sister, Peggy Say, who has urged national leaders to
work for his release. Her images of Anderson are based in part on
photos and videotapes Anderson's captives have released to news
agencies.
   ``If nothing else, because I'm someone who doesn't know him, by
doing at least one painting of him every day, even if nobody ever
sees it, he's being remembered,'' she said. ``He's not getting out,
but he is being remembered.''
   Mrs. Seeba said her attempts to arrange a showing of her Anderson
portraits have been rebuffed by managers of public buildings in
Houston where art generally is exhibited.
   ``They all say the same thing,'' she says. ``They say it's just
too controversial and they don't want to offend anybody.''
   Any proceeds from the sale of her Anderson works will go to the
Journalists' Committee to Free Terry Anderson, she said, so people
won't accuse her of trying to exploit him for her own fame.
   ``Anguish _ that's what I'm trying to show,'' she said. ``I just
want to raise consciousness. I want the public to remember.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
