<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0831EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceDrugPolicy     03-13 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Drug Policy,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Diego Police May Accept Applicants Who Used LSD</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Police Department is considering lifting a
ban on recruits who have tried LSD or other hallucinogenic drugs.
   ``We want to be current and reflect society,'' said Leroy Brady,
department personnel administrator. ``We don't want to punish what
was experimental drug use. We are losing candidates.''
   Some department officials and beat officers question the wisdom
of relaxing the ban while police are trying to crack down on illegal
drugs.
   ``I'd say we're not lowering our standards,'' Brady said. ``We're
looking at it from a practical standpoint of what's happening in
society.''
   Brady said several police agencies accept applicants who
experimented with hallucinogens five to 10 years in the past. San
Diego police haven't determined the proper time frame in which they
may allow past use of those drugs, he said.
   City Personnel Director Richard Snapper said his only concern is
whether such drugs could still prompt flashbacks. But he said,
``We've talked to medical people and we're finding the fear of
flashbacks is unfounded.''
   Police officials say up to 60 percent of recent applicants
admitted drug experimentation. Up to 40 percent of recruits who
passed written exams were disqualified because of past drug use,
Brady said.
   The ban applies to such drugs as mescaline, peyote and
phencyclidine, or PCP. Also banned are heroin and illegal steroids.
   City policy allows people who have used marijuana up to six
months before applying to become officers. Cocaine use as recent as
two years earlier also is acceptable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
