<FIRST>u i PM-IslamicMeeting 1stLd-Writethru a0515 03-13 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Islamic Meeting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0515,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Islamic Ministers Said to Oppose Recognizing Rebel Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name of Afghan guerrilla official in 11th graf ``The
guerrillas' foreign...'' CORRECTS name to Hekmatyar in 13th graf ``Hekmatyar
sais some...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most foreign ministers gathered at a
conference of Islamic nations oppose Saudi Arabia's bid to win
formal recognition of the Afghan guerrillas' newly declared
government, diplomatic sources said today.
   However, the Saudis are expected to gather enough support to
reject Iran's campaign to persuade the 46-member Organization of the
Islamic Conference to back its stand on Salman Rushdie's novel ``The
Satanic Verses.''
   Saudi Arabia and other Islamic countries have criticized Rushdie
and banned his novel, saying it blasphemes Islam. But they have
refused to support the call by Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
for the British writer's death.
   Shiites Moslems, who dominate in Iran, comprise only a tenth of
the world's 1 billion Moslems and the Iranians are clearly
outnumbered in their bid at the conference to gain support for
Khomeini's death decree.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said an Iranian
delegation headed by the deputy chief of the Islamic Propagation
Organization, Mohammad Ali Taskhiri, left Tehran on Sunday to attend
the gathering.
   Saudi Arabia broke off diplomatic ties with Iran last year,
accusing it of fomenting terrorism among Shiites in the kingdom.
   The Saudis have been regarded for centuries as the most
influential state within the Moslem world.
   King Fahd inaugurated the four-day meeting today and was expected
to deliver a lengthy speech at its first session.
   Only two member states, Saudi Arabia and Sudan, have formally
recognized the Afghan guerrillas' Pakistan-based interim government.
The guerrillas are trying to topple the Soviet-backed Kabul
government of President Najib.
   The Saudis want the other group members to both recognize the
interim government and accept it as Afghanistan's representative to
the Islamic organization.
   The guerrillas' foreign minister, Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, told
reporters that delegations were visiting Islamic countries to seek
recognition of his government, which Iran opposes.
   Iranian-backed Afghan guerrillas walked out of the conference
that created the interim government because of a dispute over
sharing power with more powerful, Pakistani-based groups.
   Hekmatyar said some Islamic countries have ``put conditions,
asking for a broad-based government to be eligible for recognition.''
   ``As for the Iran-based groups, it is an internal problem and
should not be taken as a pretext to delay recognition,'' he said.
   However, one Asian diplomat speaking on condition of anonymity
suggested that member governments were hesitating for other reasons.
   ``Most Islamic governments don't seem to easily digest the idea
of recognizing a rebel government, because that would be a dangerous
precedent and an unsettling example to be emulated by maverick
political groups elsewhere in the Islamic world.''
   The guerrillas created their interim government less than a month
after the Soviets completed their withdrawal from Afghanistan,
ending a costly nine-year intervention.
   The Islamic representatives also planned to consider collective
action to create an independent Palestinian state.
   Conference sources said the ministers were expected to discuss a
diplomatic offensive to force Israel to relinquish territories it
occupied in 1967 and accept a Palestinian state there.
</TEXT>
