<HEAD>Satanic Verses Controversy Complicates Hostage Situation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to CORRECT that 15 foreigners held in Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATAVIA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As he enters his fifth year as a hostage in
the Middle East, Terry Anderson may be suffering from backlash over
British author Salman Rushdie's novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' says
Anderson's sister Peggy Say.
   The book worsened relations between the West and Moslem
extremists who hold Anderson captive, diminishing his prospects for
release, Mrs. Say said Sunday.
   ``The situation has fallen apart again,'' she said. ``It seems
like every time we get close, something unpredictable happens.''
   Mrs. Say's comments came after a prayer service for Anderson in
his hometown. It was the first of several observances of the
anniversary of Anderson's kidnapping March 16, 1985, in Beruit.
   Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, is the longest held of 15 foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   Mrs. Say, a leading advocate for her brother, said that
immediately after the inauguration of President Bush, there were
signs that Anderson might soon be freed.
   She didn't specify what signs but said the political climate at
the time was more encouraging than it had been in many months.
   With the publication of Rushdie's book, which many Moslems
consider blasphemous, there has been increasing animosity between
the two cultures, she said.
   ``But we're not going to give up,'' she said.
   About 100 residents of Batavia listened to a roll call of the
hostages in a high school gymnasium Sunday and heard Mrs. Say urge
them not to allow Anderson to be forgotten.
