<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-BookFair     03-13 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Book Fair,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Rushdie Sales at Israel's Largest Book Fair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie's novel ``The Satanic Verses''
set a sales record in the opening hours of Israel's largest book
fair, according to organizers of the 100,000-book display from 42
countries.
   Israeli officials said the thousands in attendance and 1,000
publishers exhibiting are showing support for the Jewish state at a
time when it is confronted with a declining image after 15 months of
Palestinian rebellion.
   The star of the 14th Jerusalem International Book Fair at its
opening Sunday was Rushdie's book, which has been banned in several
countries because many Moslems consider it blasphemous. The book
prompted Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini to urge Moslems to hunt
down and kill the Indian-born British author.
   Israeli publishers at the opening called on their colleagues
abroad to unite in condemnation of the Iranian threats against
Rushdie, which include a bounty of $5.2 million.
   ``The history of our people and other nations in this century
teaches us that we can't keep silent and let a bloodthirsty ruler
pursue his criminal threats,'' said Racheli Edelman of the Israeli
Publishers' Association.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir was whisked past an exhibit of
Rushdie's book to avoid an encounter that could upset Israel's
Moslem minority. He declined comment, saying: ``I'm just visiting.''
   The Israeli Keter publishing house proudly displayed copies of
the novel beside a large sign: ``The Satanic Verses _ shortly in
Hebrew.''
   At the Jerusalem Post stand, an official said he sold 20 copies
of the English-language version in the first two hours of the fair _
a record for the Hebrew-speaking country where the 547-page novel
costs $32.70.
   Only 150 copies were sold in Israel before the fair, said an
official who expects to sell up to 600 copies before the exhibition
closes Saturday.
   Some of the 1,000 publishers are attending for the first time,
such as representatives of China, the Soviet Union, Fiji and Nepal.
Also included are Eastern bloc countries that have no diplomatic
ties with Israel _ Poland, Hungary and Yugoslavia.
   This year's fair is the largest since the weeklong biennial event
began in 1961, said Jerusalem city spokeswoman Bonnie Boxer.
   ``This is another proof that Jerusalem, the eternal capital of
the Jewish people, can overcome the difficulties and confrontations
and appear as the heavenly Jerusalem, sending to the whole world
messages of peace and justice,'' Shamir said at the opening.
   Security was heavy. Guards searched visitors' purses at the
entrance, and inside, other security men patrolled with portable
radio telephones.
   Among exhibits are a British facsimile edition of the Rothshild
Miscellany, a 15th century Italian Jewish manuscript priced at
$6,000.
   Side-by-side were a display of new Soviet books, one of Russian
translations of Western thrillers, and a biography of President Bush.
   Shamir was presented with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
book, ``Perestroika and the New Thinking.''
</TEXT>
