<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Elections 1stLd-Writethru   03-13 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0500,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Leader Says Election Shows Dangerous Trend</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to UPDATE with criticism from Jewish leader. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of West Germany's
Jewish community today said strong showings by extreme rightist
parties in state elections indicate a voter trend that must be
halted to protect democracy.
   The extreme-right National Democratic Party picked up seven seats
in the Frankfurt city legislature Sunday as well as seats in the
Main-Kinzig district council east of Hanau and in the city of Bad
Hersfeld, near the East German border.
   The ultra-right Republican Party gained seats in two district
councils and in the city council of Bad Nauheim north of Frankfurt.
In January, the Republicans gained 11 seats in the West Berlin city
legislature.
   The far-right parties support expulsion of foreign workers and
asylum-seekers from the country.
   Heinz Galinski, the head of the Jewish community, bitterly
attacked the outcome.
   ``The move to the right and the renunciation of the democratic
parties represent the trend of the Federal Republic (West Germany)
in the 40th year of its existence,'' Galinski told The Associated
Press.
   Galinski added: ``The year 1989 is more suitable to reflect on
democracy and to protect it.''
   In voting across Hesse state, the Christian Democrats suffered
losses of 6.8 percent compared with the 1985 elections. That
includes losing power in Frankfurt, which the party had controlled
for 12 years.
   The left-leaning Social Democrats will have 40 seats in the newly
formed city parliament, the environmentalist Greens 10 seats and the
Christian Democrats 36.
   ``Right-wing radicalism must be decisively combated,'' the
Christian Democrats' general secretary, Heiner Geissler, told Hesse
state radio.
   Less than two months ago, the Christian Democrats were ousted
from power in West Berlin.
   The Greens and Social Democrats are expected to form a governing
coalition in West Berlin, and Christian Democrats fear the same
could happen on the federal level after next year's elections.
   Critics claim the Christian Democrats are as a result trying to
appeal to more conservative voters and have been adopting some of
the causes of the far right.
   Some members of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's governing party called
today for a revamping of its strategy.
   In Bonn, prominent Christian Democratic politician Juergen
Todenhoefer urged an emergency meeting of the party.
   ``For six years, the party has been experiencing one election
fiasco after another, without making any serious analysis
afterwards,'' he said in a letter to Kohl. He released a copy to the
news media.
   Statewide in Hesse, the extreme right made gains.
   The Frankfurt vote gives the party a small but vocal opposition
force in one of West Germany's most important cities and its
financial capital. It is the first time since 1968 the National
Democrats have had representation in Frankfurt.
   In the town of Woelfersheim, the party won nearly 16 percent of
the vote or more than double its results in the last elections in
1985.
   The Republicans gained seats in local councils in the Rheingau
Taunus district near the Rhine River and in the Wetterau district
northeast of Frankfurt. The exact number of seats was not determined.
</TEXT>
