<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Vatican-USBishops 1stLd-Writethru a0444 03-13 1078</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vatican-US Bishops, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,1030</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede VATICAN CITY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs with comments today, picking up at pvs 4th graf,
Cardinal Bernard, and editing May reference in pvs 14th graf, Archbishop
John</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American bishops of the Roman Catholic Church
returned home after four days of meetings at the Vatican today and
said Pope John Paul II and others in the church hierarchy
``recognize that it is no easy job to be a bishop, especially in
America.''
   Archbishop John May, president of the U.S. Conference of Catholic
Bishops, told reporters: ``I believe that, as a result of this
meeting, the bridge between Rome and the United States is stronger
than it has ever been in recent memory.''
   May said he and his fellow clerics ``have a heightened sense that
Pope John Paul and the members of the Curia understand our situation
and support us in our work _ that they recognize that it is no easy
job to be a bishop, especially in America.''
   ``Clearly, there were some differences of perspective ... as
might be expected in any gathering of five dozen such people, but
these differences have to do with approach and not with doctrine,''
he said.
   The archbishop said, ``Many of the factors that make America
distinctive are the ones that make her great _ the freedom of
thought and expression, the pluralism of cultures and religions, the
democratic spirit which values the opinion of each individual.''
   ``That this would conflict at times with the hierarchical nature
of the church is not surprising,'' he said. ``What we came to Rome
to say (and it was received calmly and well) was that this spirit of
America must influence our own approach in the states,'' he said.
   If the summoning by the pope of the U.S. hierarchy seemed
extraordinary, and if the two sides said not all their differences
were meant to be resolved at the meeting, Americans prelates left
the impression in earlier comments in Rome that both sides agreed to
leave things be and not pursue any substantial follow-up action.
   Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston said he didn't see the meeting
triggering a ``great moment of change'' in the U.S. church.
   ``We will continue to go about our ministry as we have in the
past,'' declared Chicago's Cardinal Joseph Bernardin.
   Vatican officials criticized the moral climate in the United
States, signaling out the efforts of Planned Parenthood to promote
birth control and the greed and adultery typified by the TV series
``Dallas''.
   At the same time, they acknowledged the bishops' achievements in
working in such a highly secular atmosphere and stressed the
influence they have on Europe and the developing world.
   But they also pointed to specific problems and raised questions
on such issues as the granting of annulments, the preparation of
priests and the response to the feminist movement.
   ``Without departing from a fundamental optimism about the church
in the U.S., I think I must signal some matters on which we should
work together better to insure the interest of the family,'' was the
way Cardinal Eduard Gagnon, the Vatican's chief on family matters,
put it.
   The U.S. bishops defended their performance and said
participation in the life of the church by Americans compares
favorably with that in other Western countries. They stressed that
their work should be evaluated in the context of their democratic
society.
   ``This is not a meeting that has winners or losers,'' said
Monsignor James Lynch, secretary of the U.S. Conference of Catholic
Bishops. ``Except that truth is being served.''
   Here is a sampling of some of the comments and give-and-take
during the meeting that ended Saturday.
   On the role of the bishop _
   May, president of the bishops' conference:
   ``...to assert that there is a church teaching with authority
binding and loosing for eternity is truly a sign of contradiction to
many Americans who consider the divine right of bishops as outmoded
as the divine right of kings. Accordingly, bishops live and work
constantly in this atmosphere.''
   Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, the Vatican's chief theologian as head
of the Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith:
   ``The criterion for the truth is such that it's worth suffering
for it. Those who announce the Gospel must also be martyrs in the
most profound sense of the word.''
   On American democracy _
   Cardinal Bernardin of Chicago:
   ``We work our destiny in full view of the public's eye. This is
an element of our ministry that we are not always able to control.
Perhaps this is a special blessing of our experience _ although some
would see it as a mixed blessing.''
   On the declining number of priests _
   Cardinal William Baum, an American who heads the Vatican's
Congregation for Catholic Education:
   ``A positive approach to vocations must shrug off the pressures
to mute the priesthood that come from people who want women priests,
married priests, part-time priests or simply optional celibacy.''
   Archbishop Daniel Pilarczyk of Cincinnati:
   ``How attractive is a lifetime of service in a culture which
stresses self-satisfaction and in which lifetime commitment seems
more and more difficult even in marriage?''
   On annulments and marriage _
   Archbishop Achille Silvestrini, prefect of the Holy See's highest
court, pointed out that of the 45,632 annulments granted worldwide
in 1986, 36,180 were in the United States.
   Archbishop John Quinn of San Francisco:
   ``By providing a place where families can socialize together with
others who share their commitment to the person and message of
Christ, the parishes of the United States help to compensate for the
rootlessness and lack of social and religious support that are
inherent in our society with its secularistic stance and high
mobility.''
   On feminism _
   Cardinal Gagnon, the Canadian who heads the Pontifical Council
for the Family:
   ``It is evident that ideological feminism has a deterious
influence on the family. But conversely the best way to counter its
influence will be to care more about the family and make every one
in it more conscious of his or her vocation `to serve and not to be
served,' as Christ has taught us.''
   On Mass attendance _
   Archbishop Daniel Kucera of Dubuque, Iowa:
   ``Nearly one-half of American Catholics attend Sunday Mass each
week. The vast majority receive Holy Communion at these masses.
While this statistic shows a greater level of participation than in
many other developed Western countries, we are seeking more
effective ways of encouraging participation of non-practicing
Catholics.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
