<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HijackingTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0431 03-13 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijacking Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0431,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Hopes Skyjacking Trial Will Discourage Other Plane Takeovers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to update with deliberations resumed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials hope that a conviction in the
sky piracy trial of Fawaz Younis will send a message to potential
terrorists that the United States has a long arm that can haul them
to justice.
   ``You can send that hijacker a message,'' Justice Department
lawyer Karen Morrissette said in her closing argument to the jury.
The panel of seven women and five men resumed deliberations today.
   Critics say that even conviction and life imprisonment for Younis
would do little to dissuade hijackers, and that acquittal would be
at best costly and embarrassing, and could undermine America's
counterterrorism efforts.
   The U.S. government has gone to enormous effort and expense to
capture and try Younis, who admitted on the stand that he led a band
from Lebanon's Amal militia in hijacking Royal Jordanian Airlines
flight 402 from Beirut on June 11, 1985.
   Two Americans were held hostage in the hijacking. No one was
killed.
   Critics of the government cite the relative obscurity of Younis,
who was a minor figure in Amal, a Shiite Moslem group that controls
most of West Beirut.
   ``He is no Abu Nidal,'' said terrorism expert Neil Livingstone of
a far more notorious terrorist leader.
   Moreover, trial by an American jury is not the most effective
weapon against terrorists, who generally come from regions torn by
violence and lawlessness, said another think-tank specialist, Robert
Kupperman.
   ``Terrorism should be treated as a national security issue and
not as a criminal justice issue,'' said Kupperman, of the Center for
Strategic and International Studies in Washington.
   Jailing Younis won't end world terrorism, but it could be a small
step in that direction, respond supporters of the government policy.
   The trial of Younis is part of a ``coherent policy on
terrorism,'' said Bruce Hoffman, a terrorism specialist at the Rand
Corp. in California.
   Younis ``may not be Abu Nidal, but you have to start somewhere''
in developing legal precedents for apprehending, trying and
convicting terrorists, said Hoffman.
   ``The message is that if you are going to attack U.S. citizens
and property, we are going to come looking for you, and if we catch
you, you will get a fair trial and if you are guilty will be
convicted,'' said Hoffman.
   Victoria Toensing, a deputy assistant attorney general who helped
plan the Younis case, described the trial as a victory for
cooperation among the Justice, State and Defense departments and the
first test of a 1984 statute under which the United States asserts
jurisdiction over cases involving the taking of U.S. hostages abroad.
   ``Not only did we use the long-arm statute for the first time,
but we showed that we could capture one of these defendants under
the law and bring him back and try him,'' she said.
   Younis was lured aboard a yacht and arrested in international
waters in the Mediterranean Sea on Sept. 13, 1987, by a team
including the FBI hostage rescue squad, the U.S. military and
intelligence agencies.
   Federal officials have not disclosed the cost of the Younis case,
but besides paying the salaries of the FBI agents, intelligence
operatives, sailors, pilots, lawyers and federal marshals involved,
the government has relocated and given new identities to at least 15
Middle Easterners under the witness protection program.
   In deciding to grab Younis instead of a bigger fish, said
Toensing, government officials were swayed by the strong case
against him.
   ``There are always several possibilities out there. You have a
combination of the `getability' of somebody, plus the case ready to
go to trial,'' she said. And a conviction against Younis could open
the season on bigger fish.
   ``Look at dope dealing. Bigwigs don't touch the stuff. It is
always harder to get the top guy. They always send underlings,''
said Toensing, who served as deputy assistant attorney general in
the criminal division for four years in the Reagan administration.
She left the government for private practice last August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
