<FIRST>r a PM-LosAlamosGuards     03-13 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Los Alamos Guards,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Alamos Lab Security Guards Go on Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security guards at Los Alamos National
Laboratory went on strike today and were replaced at their posts by
non-union workers and supervisors.
   ``The security of the laboratory is not in any jeopardy,'' said
James Breen, a spokesman for the government complex where the atomic
bomb was developed during World War II and where military research
is still done.
   The walkout began over alleged unfair practices by Mason &amp;
Hanger-Silas Mason Co., the contractor that operates the guard force
at the laboratory.
   About 25 union members set up a picket line at the entrance to
headquarters building for lab guards, the only spot where picketing
is authorized. The pickets waved signs and chanted but did not
obstruct operations there.
   The union instructed guards to abandon their picket stations and
go back to work immediately if an intruder tries to get in, said
Ernesto Salazar, union business manager.
   ``Our main concern is national security,'' Salazar said Saturday.
``We are Americans and we will defend our country.''
   Breen said the force guarding the lab numbers about 340, but he
declined to say how many were taking part in the strike, citing
security concerns.
   Guards and other workers who are not part of the union will staff
the guard posts along with Mason &amp; Hanger employees from other
defense facilities, officials said.
   The guards' contract with Mason &amp; Hanger expired Feb. 8, but a
mediator was called in. Talks were scheduled to resume Tuesday.
</TEXT>
