<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Environment     03-13 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Environment,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Vows War on Polluters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today called for ``throwing the
book'' at ocean dumpers and vowed to support more aggressive
criminal prosecution against them and other despoilers of the
environment.
   Promising to chart a course of environmental activism, Bush told
a group of state attorneys general that ``on many issues the time
for study has passed.''
   The president said his administration would soon submit to
Congress legislation to re-authorize the Clean Air Act and to set
new standards to reduce industrial emissions that cause acid rain.
   He also said he favors stepping up the Superfund cleanup program
and assuring compliance with hazardous waste laws.
   And, Bush told the White House session, ``I think working with
you all we can do a lot of throwing the book at those engaged in
illegal ocean dumping.''
   He told the legal officers they should closely study the cases
now before the involving environmental abuse. ``I'd like you to
think about the most serious cases where we've got to move beyond
civil penalties toward criminal enforcement,'' he said.
   Bush said criminal charges brought against those who abuse the
environment would serve ``both as a sanction and as a deterrent.''
   He praised states for taking the lead on environmental issues and
said, ``We're going to find solutions and we've got to find state
and federal roles that work.''
   In his 10-minute address, the president focused exclusively on
the environment and on the war on drugs.
   ``As I look at your agenda, it's clear to me that this
association and the White House are fighting the same battles,''
Bush said.
   He characterized drugs as ``like a chemical weapons that a
society turns on itself,'' and declared: ``We've got to see our
great cities no longer held hostage to drug lords.''
   The president got good marks for his talk.
   Outside the White House, Robert Abrams, attorney general of New
York state and president of the National Association of Attorneys
General, praised Bush's ``personal and dramatic'' commitment on
environmental issues.
   ``He applauds and recognizes the role of the states,'' Abrams
told reporters.
   He also said that William Reilly, administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency, ``wants things to happen and he
wants them to happen quickly.'' Reilly addressed the group after
Bush.
   Tom Miller, Iowa's attorney general, said ``a new day is
dawning'' in terms of state-federal relations on environmental
issues. ``There's a real sense that we're in this together.''
   ``I heard all the right words,'' Miller added. ``However, we have
to recognize that words are the easy part of it.''
   Jeffrey Ameston, Vermont attorney general, recalled the past
practice of states filing lawsuits against the EPA to force federal
action on environmental cleanup. ``That will change in this
administration,'' he said.
   ``I'll take the message back to Vermont that this administration
is an environmental administration,'' he added.
</TEXT>
