<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-CongressRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0530 03-13 1003</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0530,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Putting Cheney Nomination on Fast Track</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOP 8 grafs new with Cheney hearings to begin Tuesday; picks
up 5th graf pvs, The 52-year-old.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is moving quickly on the nomination
of Rep. Dick Cheney, R-Wyo., as defense secretary, with hearings on
President Bush's replacement for John Tower to begin Tuesday, it was
announced today.
   House Republican Leader Robert Michel and Sens. Alan Simpson and
Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., will formally introduce Cheney to the Senate
Armed Services Committee, said Pete Williams, a spokesman for Cheney.
   The opening of hearings was scheduled for Tuesday afternoon, the
committee announced.
   Williams said Cheney spent this morning in briefings at the White
House and was expected to go to the Pentagon later in the day.
   Bush selected Cheney after the Senate rejected Tower last
Thursday by a 53-47 vote. One member of the Armed Services Committee
expressed hope today that consideration of Cheney could be wrapped
by by week's end, when the Senate begins a two-week recess.
   Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo., said on NBC's ``Today'' show: ``The
more rapidly we get through this the better. I would hope we could
be done by the end of this week.''
   The Senate also turns this week to impeachment charges against
District Judge Alcee L. Hastings of Miami, accused of plotting to
obtain a $150,000 bribe and lying about it at his 1983 conspiracy
trial.
   The congressional agenda includes new House Ethics Committee
sessions on Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, plus possible legislative
action on the Eastern Airlines strike and a Senate vote on increased
job protection for government ``whistleblowers'' who report waste,
fraud and abuse.
   The 52-year-old Hastings, the first black district judge in
Florida, was acquitted in the 1983 trial but now faces an effort to
remove him from the bench and take away his $89,500 salary.
   Hastings' attorney, Terence J. Anderson, maintains that the trial
should have settled the matter and that th impeachment effort,
prompted by complaints from fellow judges, represents a classic case
of double jeopardy.
   Anderson also claims that Hastings cannot receive a fair hearing
because key witnesses have died and many senators are not planning
to attend the hearings at which evidence will be presented. Instead,
they plan to rely on videotapes of the proceedings.
   The House approved a 17-count bill of impeachment 413-3 on Aug.
3, alleging that Hastings plotted with prominent Washington lawyer
William Borders to obtain a payoff from two brothers convicted in
Hastings' court of skimming money from a Teamsters pension fund loan.
   It also says Hastings perjured himself in testimony at the trial
and, in an unrelated count, that he improperly divulged information
obtained from a wiretap and thus torpedoed a federal investigation.
   House prosecutors say impeachment is not the same as a criminal
proceeding and thus the double jeopardy argument does not apply.
   The Senate plans to hear arguments Wednesday and decide Thursday
whether to dismiss the charges.
   Meanwhile, the House Ethics Committee starts closed-door
deliberations this week on six broad allegations that Wright used
his office for personal financial gain and improperly lobbied
government regulators.
   Under tight secrecy, the panel of six Democrats and six
Republicans has held two weeks of hearings to determine whether
disciplinary action is warranted. The defense is set to wrap up its
presentation Tuesday.
   Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said deliberations could take
two or three days with final action possibly spilling into next week.
   Among other things, Wright stands accused of skirting outside
income limits through bulk sales of a book and accepting free use of
a luxury car and Fort Worth condominium.
   Wright mailed letters to Texas constituents last month, saying
the case represents a politically motivated ``game of sack the
quarterback.''
   ``If they can't injure you and knock you out of the game, which
is their first choice, then they'll try at least to batter you
around enough to spoil your concentration,'' Wright said.
   The House plans to take up a measure that would establish an
emergency board to find a way to end the International Association
of Machinists strike against Eastern. Approval of the labor-backed
bill is likely in the House but the Senate could prove less
receptive to the measure, which is opposed by the White House.
   The Democratic chairmen and senior Republicans on the House and
Senate Budget committees plan to meet through the week with White
House Budget Director Richard Darman, in a continuation of talks
that began last Thursday.
   The group is seeking agreement on at least the rough outlines of
a spending plan for fiscal 1990 before Congress leaves March 23 for
its Easter recess. They will try to find a combination of spending
restraints and new revenue that would reduce the federal deficit to
$100 billion.
   The House Education and Labor Committee on Tuesday considers a
raise in the minimum wage to $4.65 an hour from its current $3.35.
It is similar to a plan that already has cleared its committee
hurdle in the Senate.
   The plan is advancing under threat of a presidential veto with
Bush calling for a version that includes a lower, ``training wage''
and increases of 30 cents an hour every year for three years.
   Lawmakers are shooting for House floor action before Easter but
the Senate is unlikely to act before April.
   Elsewhere, the Senate plans a vote on stepped-up job protection
for federal employees who expose squandering and mismanagement.
Under the bill, a compromise between Senate sponsors and the
administration reached last week, whistleblowers would have to be
reinstated in their posts if they could show reprisal for such
actions contributed to their firing or demotion.
   Stripped from the bill under the compromise was a provision
approved last year that would have allowed a special government
counsel to go to court on behalf of whistleblowers.
   President Reagan pocket vetoed last year's version after
unanimous approval by both houses, saying it would result in the
government filing suit against itself.
</TEXT>
