<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Malawi-Floods     03-13 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Malawi-Floods,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>Floods Kill Six, Leave 37,000 Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLANTYRE, Malawi (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torrential rain and floods in southern
Malawi killed six people and left 37,000 homeless, officials said
Monday.
   Floodwaters that swept away mud huts and prefabricated shelters
in Chikwawa and Nsanje districts drowned the six victims, including
two children, local administrators said.
   About 20,000 people are homeless in Nsanje, near the southeastern
border with Mozambique, according to a government administrator.
   Red Cross officials said 17,000 other homeless are receiving
food, blankets and tents at Chikwawa, about 70 miles south of
Blantyre.
   Some displaced families are being sheltered in schools, churches,
government and other brick buildings that withstood the flooding,
they said.
   Travelers arriving in Blantyre told of entire villages being
destroyed and widespread damage to corn crops in the worst floods
recorded since 1956.
</TEXT>
