<HEAD>Peaceful Services Remember Student Whose Death Sparked Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at two Rangoon campuses held
peaceful memorial services Monday for a student whose killing a year
ago prompted a serious challenge to authoritarian rule in Burma.
   Students ignored calls from left-leaning politicians to stage
street protests in memory of Maung Phone Maw.
   The 23-year-old student at the Rangoon Institute of Technology
was killed when riot police quashed a March 13, 1988, confrontation
between students at the institute and people living nearby.
   Anger over his death led to months of nationwide street marches
and demonstrations and caused resignations of two government leaders.
   Some concessions were made. But military commander Gen. Saw Maung
seized power in a September coup and his forces killed more than 500
people to crush protests.
   Saw Maung's military council since has allowed opposition
political activity and announced a general election will be held
early 1990.
