<SECOND>PM-Chicago Mayoral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0575,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sawyer Says Will Remain Neutral In Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to ADD no immediate comment from Evans campaign;
PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Sawyer, 54 ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lame-duck Mayor Eugene Sawyer today refused to
endorse a candidate in next month's mayoral election, despite
pressure from black leaders to throw his support behind third-party
hopeful Timothy Evans.
   ``After careful consideration, I have decided not to endorse any
candidate,'' Sawyer said.
   The Evans campaign had no immediate comment.
   Sawyer, 54, lost the Feb. 28 Democratic primary to Richard M.
Daley, 46, the son of Richard J. Daley, the legendary political boss
who ran City Hall for 22 years.
   Evans, 45, a black alderman, bypassed the primary to run as an
independent in the April 4 general election and will face white
candidates Daley and Edward Vrdolyak, 51, the Republican nominee.
   Analysts said Evans' lack of support for Sawyer, who also is
black, contributed to low primary turnout in black wards and was a
factor in Daley's victory. Sawyer today said he was not bitter about
Evans' failure to endorse him in the primary.
   Since the primary, a number of black community leaders, including
Jesse Jackson, have urged Sawyer to endorse Evans.
   ``All candidates have sought my endorsement,'' Sawyer said,
adding that he would do ``everything I can to ensure a smooth
transition'' for whoever is elected mayor.
   Sawyer also discouraged supporters from launching a write-in
campaign on his behalf. ``My race for mayor is over,'' he said.
   Daley spokeswoman Marj Halperin said that while Daley would have
liked Sawyer's endorsement ``we feel we are getting the support of
his supporters and that's what counts in the voting booth.''
   ``You have to ask the Evans campaign how it plays for them,'' she
added. ``With any endorsement issue, if they're not going to work
for us, we'd prefer they not work against us.''
</TEXT>
