<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1413EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     03-13 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Team Spirit' Exercises Begin Tuesday; North Korea Issues Warning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joint U.S.-South Korea military
maneuvers involving about 200,000 soldiers begin Tuesday amid
repeated warnings from North Korea that the exercises push the
peninsula closer to war.
   The 10-day ``Team Spirit'' exercises, an annual event since 1976,
will last until March 23 and take place in various parts of the
country, officials from South Korea and the United States said
Monday.
   As in past years, the emphasis will be on improving defensive
readiness of the two countries, the officials said.
   President Roh Tae-woo, visiting a command post north of Seoul,
said the exercises are needed to guard the safety of South Korea
against invasion from North Korea.
   ``The latest situations on the peninsula are pointing to the
danger of a war, and a close security alliance between the two
countries (the United States and South Korea) is really needed,''
Roh said.
   North Korea has protested the maneuvers in past years. It put its
army on combat alert over the weekend and issued another protest
Monday.
   ``The tension between the North and the South has been screwed up
to the highest pitch, and a dangerous situation has been created on
the Korean peninsula in which a war may break out any moment,'' said
Pyongyang's official Korean Central News Agency.
   The peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
capitalist South Korea at the end of World War II, when U.S. and
Soviet troops ended Japan's colonial rule over the region. The two
Koreas have remained bitter enemies and fought a war from 1950 to
1953.
   A U.S. military spokesman in Seoul said this year's ``Team
Spirit'' involve about 70,000 American troops, including 43,000
stationed in South Korea and 27,000 from Hawaii, Okinawa and the
U.S. mainland.
   As in previous years, South Korea invited North Korea and China
to observe the exercises. The two communist nations rejected all
past invitations, and there was no response as of Monday.
   Officials of the United Nations Command speculated the ``Team
Spirit'' controversy was behind North Korea's request for a meeting
of the Korean Military Armistice Commission, the watchdog body set
up to monitor the 1953 Korean War Armistice agreement.
   North Korea asked for a session Friday but gave no reason. The
U.N. Command proposed it be held Saturday.
   Also Monday, the South Korean government said it spent more for
U.S. troops stationed in the country than any other nation in the
world last year.
   The report by the Defense Ministry said an active publicity
campaign is needed to make Washington understand that South Korea's
share of defense burden is greater than those of NATO and Japan.
   According to the report, Seoul's support for the 43,000 U.S.
troops in South Korea was worth $2.2 billion last year, $313 million
more than in 1987.
</TEXT>
