<FIRST>u a AM-Shuttle-Experiments Bjt   03-13 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Experiments, Bjt,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rats and Chicken Embryos In Space!</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-two fertilized eggs, courtesy
of Kentucky Fried Chicken, are whirling through space aboard
Discovery along with four white rats to test how weightlessness
affects growth and broken bones.
   The projects, both designed by students, are among five
experiments to be conducted during the five-day shuttle mission,
which began Monday and is to end Saturday.
   The chicken embryo experiment, developed by college senior John
Vellinger, is a copy of one destroyed in the Challenger explosion
Jan. 28, 1986.
   Vellinger's experiment, nicknamed ``Chix in Space,'' is an
incubator containing 32 eggs, half of which were fertilized two days
prior to launch and half nine days before.
   A copy of the same experiment will be conducted on the ground,
said Vellinger, a senior in mechanical engineering at Purdue
University. The eggs on the ground will be turned to mimic the
action a mother hen would take to keep the developing yolk from
sinking.
   But in zero gravity, the yolks should float in the center and not
have to be turned, said the 23-year-old student, who first thought
of the idea as a ninth-grader in Lafayette, Ind.
   After the flight, half of each group will be opened and the
remaining half will be allowed to hatch. Both sets will be studied
to determine the effects of weightlessness on the growing embryo.
The experiment may one day help scientists determine whether a human
fetus could develop normally in space, Vellinger said.
   Richard M. Detwiler, spokesman for Louisville, Ky.-based Kentucky
Fried Chicken, said NASA approached the company several years ago
about sponsoring the project.
   ``It was an exciting educational program worthy of our support,''
Detwiler said, adding tongue-in-cheek: ``And if it helps us crack
the exterrestrial chicken market, then all the better.''
   Detwiler said the company had spent more than $50,000 on the
project. Vellinger has been a summer intern at the company's
engineering department.
   For the rat experiment, a veterinarian removed a small piece of
bone from the rear leg of 
shortly before liftoff. Four of the rats were put on the shuttle,
while the others remain on Earth.
   ``This is an extremely non-traumatic procedure,'' said student
Andrew Fras when asked about using animals for experiments. ``They
should be carrying on as normal about an hour after the procedure is
done.
   Fras, a 22-year-old medical student at Brown University who was
in high school in Binghamton, N.Y., when he thought of the idea,
hopes the test will show whether weightlessness and the loss of
calcium that bones sustain during spaceflights inhibit the healing
process.
   After the flight, all eight rats will be killed so the bones'
mending processes can be studied and compared.
   The project has been criticized as cruel and unnecessary by
People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, an animal rights group
based in Washington.
   ``Whatever happens to the bones of those rats in space is not
going to keep people from engaging in space travel,'' said
spokeswoman Mary Beth Sweetland.
   oots grow in space.
Researchers are flying samples of the common daylilly and a weed
named happlopappis gracilis. The results may lead to a better
understanding of plant growth on Earth and should provide
information on how to grow plants on the space station, the moon or
Mars.
   A device that may be used as a cooling system aboard the space
station also is being be tested on Discovery.
   The Space Station Heat Pipe Advanced Radiator Element, resembling
a giant slat of a venetian blind, is riding in the payload bay. It
consists of two small pipes bored through an aluminum core that runs
through the center of a 51-foot-long, foot-wide radiator.
   The device uses liquid ammonia that is vaporized by heat
generated by various shuttle systems. The vapor carries the heat the
length of the radiator through the larger vapor pipe, and the
radiator dissipates into space, leaving cooled, condensed ammonia
that can be recirculated.
   Another experiment, the protein crystal growth project, has flown
on several missions. Crystals can be grown on Earth, but gravity
causes them to sink and fuse together.
   Samples of 15 different proteins are on Discovery, including
renin, an enzyme that plays a major role in controlling blood
pressure, and porcine elastase, an enzyme involved in the
degradation of lung tissue in people suffering from emphysema.
   The crystals could help scientists determine the proteins'
molecular structure and speed development of drugs to combat their
ill effects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
