<SECOND>PM-Vincennes-Bomb, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0511,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Appeals For Help to Solve Bombing of USS Vincennes Captain's
Van</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with federal official saying two
men were spotted in the neighborhood; PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `The FBI ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal law enforcement official today said
two Middle Eastern-looking men were in Will Rogers' neighborhood,
looking for the home of the USS Vincennes skipper, in the weeks
before a van driven by his wife was bombed.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it was
not clear if investigators had been able to piece together detailed
descriptions of the two men. The information was based on interviews
with neighbors, the official said.
   Rogers commanded the missile cruiser that mistakenly shot down an
Iranian airliner in the Persian Gulf last July, killing all 290
people aboard.
   Rogers' wife, Sharon, was driving the van alone Friday when the
bomb exploded, destroying the vehicle. Mrs. Rogers wasn't injured.
   On Sunday, the FBI appealed for information about the bombing.
   ``We would like to find somebody who saw something very
suspicious and out of place,'' FBI spokesman Gene Riehl said.
``We're looking for people who saw anything suspicious.''
   Investigators remained uncertain today whether the bomb was the
work of terrorists retaliating for the jetliner's downing.
   The law enforcement official who said the men were spotted asking
where the Navy captain lived spoke following a report in today's New
York Times that a man of Middle Eastern appearance asked passers-by,
``Where does the captain live?''
   The FBI described the bomb as ``an improvised explosive device''
that wasn't made by the military and may have been homemade. Types
of such devices include pipe bombs, Riehl said.
   Tom Hughes, head of the bureau's San Diego office, said it will
take a lengthy analysis to determine exactly what type of bomb was
used.
   FBI laboratory experts spent Sunday sifting through three drums
filled with debris collected at the intersection where thken to an undisclosed
FBI garage, Riehl
said.
   FBI officials also met Sunday with representatives of the Naval
Investigative Service; the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms; San Diego Police; and the coers had driven the van earlier Friday
for a regular trip to a
nearby doughnut shop and he thought he may have been the intended
target, said Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., who talked with the captain.
   Hughes and Dennis Usery, regional director of the Naval
Investigative Service, met Sunday with the Rogerses. They have been
under the protection of NIS agents at an undisclosed location since
shortly after the bombing.
   ``I think the meeting was more to reassure them a little bit or
to help them through their trouble,'' Riehl said.
   Usery described the couple as being ``in good spirits,'' and said
the security for them would continue indefinitely.
   Chief Petty Officer Craig Huebler, a spokesman for the San Diego
Naval Base, said Navy officials are awaiting FBI findings to
determine when the couple will return to work. Rogers remains in
command of the Vincennes, whose home port is San Diego, and Mrs.
Rogers is a teacher.
   An Iranian newspaper Sunday blamed the FBI for the bombing,
saying Washington tried to implicate Iran in the attack to justify
deportation of Iranian students.
   Riehl declined to comment on the claim, but in Washington, FBI
spokeswoman Kathy Kennedy denied it and added, ``we have never made
any linkage to Iran since this incident happened.''
   ``We haven't gotten to the point (in the investigation) where we
could make such a linkage,'' she said.
   The English-language newspaper Kayhan International linked the
alleged U.S. plot to Western anger at Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
order that novelist Salman Rushdie be killed for his new novel,
``The Satanic Verses.''
   The bombing ``will not be the last attempt to implicate Iran''
over the Rushdie controversy, the editorial said.
</TEXT>
