<FIRST>r a AM-People     03-13 0969</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0999</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syndicated columnist Art Buchwald, Sen. Daniel
K. Inouye and former pro basketball star Julius ``Dr. J.'' Erving
are among 10 winners of this year's Horatio Alger Awards, given to
Americans who have triumphed over ``humble beginnings and
adversity'' to achieve success.
   Humorist Buchwald, 63, grew up during the Depression in an
orphanage and foster homes, the awards group said, while Inoyye, 64,
D-Hawaii, grew up in a Japanese ghetto area of Honolulu. Erving, 39,
helped support his family by working odd jobs as a teen-ager.
   Also honored were S. Truett Cathy of Atlanta, founder of the
Chick-fil-A restaurant chain; Robert H. Dedman of Dallas, founder of
ClubCorp International; Jean Nidetch of New York, founder of Weight
Watchers International Inc.; Carl R. Pohlad, a Minneapolis banker
and owner of the Minnesota Twins baseball team; D.B. Reinhart of La
Crosse, Wis., chairman of Gateway Foods Inc.; Dr. Robert H. Schuller
of Garden Grove, Calif., senior pastor of the Crystal Cathedral, and
R.J. Ventres of New York, chairman of Borden Inc.
   The awards will be presented at a May 19 banquet by the
42-year-old, non-profit association of Horatio Alger Award
recipients. Banquet proceeds will support the group's youth
programs, including college scholarships for outstanding high school
students of limited means.

</TEXT>
<NOTE>This item for release 6 p.m. EST, time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Larroquette, who plays the prosecutor on the
television comedy ``Night Court,'' says he considered suicide before
conquering alcoholism.
   ``I sat down one night, put a pistol on the table and wrote a
suicide note,'' Larroquette said in an interview in the April issue
of Redbook magazine.
   ``But I realized that I didn't consider any of the notes funny
enough. I thought. ...`You can't do it until you figure out the
perfect exit line. It seems you want to have some sort of effect on
this world.' So I talked myself out of it,'' said Larroquette, 41.
   The Louisiana-born actor said he struggled to quit drinking for
three years before going cold turkey on Feb. 6, 1982. ``One night I
said to myself, `There are no more deals. Whatever it takes, I don't
want to feel like this anymore.'''
   The next year, he was hired for the role of Dan Fielding on
``Night Court'' and went on to win four Emmys in a row.
   ``An old man once told me, `Boy, you've been insane. Insanity is
the repetition of the same action, expecting different results,'''
said Larroquette. ``One day I said, `I'm not going to repeat those
actions today.' And lo and behold, different results occurred.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>This item for release 6 p.m. EST. Time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Walsh, host of Fox Television's
``America's Most Wanted,'' says death threats he has received will
not sway the dedication he feels to the program.
   Walsh, in an interview for the March 18 edition of TV Guide
magazine, said he vowed after the abduction and death of his
6-year-old son, Adam, in 1981 that he would do anything he could to
see that criminals are brought to justice.
   ``This show is a very tough thing for me to do,'' said Walsh, 43.
``I'm not Dan Rather or Tom Brokaw. I am the father of a murdered
child.''
   Walsh said, ``I don't look at it as a TV show. I look at it as if
it were a job as important as addressing the Legislature.''
   Walsh set up the National Center for Missing and Exploited
Children and has pushed for laws to protect children from abduction.
   The program made its premiere in February 1988 and has led to the
arrests of 64 of the 124 fugitives it profiled.
   Walsh said the negative side of the television program is that he
and his family have received numerous death threats. A son and a
daughter have been born since Adam's death and Walsh reported that
he and his family have moved several times. He said the family now
lives in Florida in virtual hiding.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When people hear that a U.S. Supreme
Court justice is in their midst, they often walk up to John O'Connor
and tell him how pleased they are to meet him.
   John's not the justice, of course. His wife, Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor, shared that and other anecdotes about her experiences on
the high court with the Louisiana State University Law Center
Fellows on Saturday at Nottoway Plantation.
   Mrs. O'Connor spent the day at the Law Center, where she talked
with students and learned to eat Louisiana's succulent seasonal
specialty, crawfish.
   She said her nomination in 1981 to be the first woman on the
Supreme Court was a surprise to her and she was not ready for the
sudden fame.
   ``The first year made me yearn for obscurity,'' she said. ``The
press was there constantly.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II will not renew the contract of
Dick Hern, who has trained horses for the queen since 1967 and from
a wheelchair since a 1984 hunting accident, Buckingham Palace
announced Monday.
   A statement by the queen's press secretary said Willie
Hastings-Bass will replace Hern, 68, one of the most successful
trainers in Britain since World War II.
   No reason was given for the decision to let Hern's contract
expire in November, but he has been under pressure to retire in
recent months because of his health. He broke his neck in the 1984
accident and underwent major heart surgery last fall.
   Hern, who began his racing career in 1952, has been national
champion trainer four times and saddled more than 1,000 winners.
   Hastings-Bass, 41, who has trained horses for the queen for 10
years, saddled 31 winners last year to win the equivalent of
$280,000.
</TEXT>
