<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     03-13 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Fashion Looks East for New Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As designers gear up for the frenetic winter
ready-to-wear marathon in Paris, one of France's top fashion
executives is packing his bags for China, where he sees a big new
market for French clothes.
   ``We have to stay one jump ahead of the game,'' Jacques Mouclier,
president of the French Federation of Couture and Ready-to-Wear,
said in an interview.
   Fashion affairs are moving steadily eastward, with a resurgence
of individual enterprise in China and the Soviet Union, Mouclier
said.
   The ready-to-wear shows start in Paris on Wednesday.
   Mouclier is leaving March 24 for Beijing and Shanghai, where
Chinese audiences will get a look at French luxury in shows
featuring 150 outfits by about 25 French designers.
   Western markets are nearing a saturation point and the United
States is slowing up as a giant consumer, Mouclier said.
   ``We'll maintain our exports to the U.S.A., but I don't see any
increase,'' he said.
   He and other industry experts foresee the big increases coming
from countries such as South Korea.
   ``They are heading the way of Japan,'' he said. ``That means they
will work in the framework of French fashion and become big
consumers of it.''
   Mouclier himself brought Japanese into the French fold when he
saw they were gaining momentum in design and manufacture.
   At the end of the 1970s, many Japanese were showing in Paris
ready-to-wear shows under the aegis of the French Fashion
Federation. That meant, in theory, that they were not blatantly
lifting French ideas to manufacture solely for their own profit in
Japan.
   In the long term, he sees China, India and the Soviet Union as
the major sources of industry and growth, beginning with China.
   ``Russia is not quite ripe for us yet. Though they seem to be
changing fairly rapidly, it will take time for us to make real
inroads there,'' he said. ``The Chinese are more adaptable and have
a history of trade and commerce.
   ``Pierre Cardin and Yves Saint Laurent have already shown
individually in China, and Cardin has manufacturing agreements,'' he
said.
   India has an excellent future as a market, but the situation
there is tricky, as well. ``The population is huge, of course. But
so far only a certain class is concerned by what we're selling. And
they're dispersed all over the subcontinent. The problem is that
there is no one city center or area for reaching potential
consumers.''
   While aiming at market expansion, Mouclier believes French
fashion is financially healthy, with a $54 million turnover in haute
couture, with 3,000 clients. Ready-to-wear and accessories total
about $750 million, with a regular yearly increase of 10 percent.
   He admits the figures are a drop in the bucket compared with
heavy industry. ``But you can't compare clothes to cars,'' he added.
   Mouclier estimates about 7,000 will see three shows at the
Beijing Opera and 1,000 in Shanghai. ``There's enormous demand. I
don't know how the audiences will be chosen.''
   ``Think of the potential consumers in China,'' said Mouclier.
``Their population is over a billion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
