<FIRST>u a PM-HelicopterCrash 5thLd-Writethru a0613 03-13 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helicopter Crash, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0613,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helicopter Crashes Over Desert; 15 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to ADD weather and light conditions and ADD
spokesman saying helicopters were not close together; PICKS UP 9th graf
pvs, `Roque said ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY12, LaserPhoto NY13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force helicopter crashed and burned
in the desert on a night training mission, killing all 15 people
aboard, authorities said today.
   Workers at the crash site 25 miles from Davis-Monthan Air Force
Base recovered the last bodies late this morning after using a crane
to move the burned-out wreckage, said base spokesman Capt. Carlos
Roque.
   The Vietnam-era CH-3E ``Jolly Green Giant'' helicopter, with four
Air Force crew members from the base, went down on a clear, moonless
night Sunday while ferrying 11 Army personnel stationed at Fort
Bragg, N.C., authorities said.
   Another helicopter was in the area, Roque said.
   A witness said he saw what appeared to be flames from the
helicopter before it crashed. Another said the copters were flying
so low that ``you could throw a rock and hit them.''
   Roque said that the cause of the crash was under investigation
but that the crew's night-vision goggles were not a factor. News
reports have implicated the light-amplifying goggles and lack of
moonlight in previous crashes.
   Roque said in previous crashes involving the goggles, the
aircraft were on low-level flights or close to other aircraft.
   ``In this case, they were flying above the minimum FAA (Federal
Aviation Administration) altitude,'' Roque said, though he could not
specify the FAA minimum ceiling for the site or the helicopter's
level prior to the crash.
   He said the two helicopters Sunday night were not close together,
but he had no specific distance.
   Roque said the helicopter was transporting Army personnel from
Fort Huachuca to the Air Force's Gila Bend Gunnery Range, 200 miles
apart.
   Mike Skrekas said he saw the crash from his house a few miles
away.
   ``I looked up and I seen a yellow ball, like flames, coming out
of the back,'' he said. ``Five seconds later I saw it hit the
ground, and then there was a red fireball.''
   Another nearby resident, 31-year-old Gary Williams, said he did
not see the crash but heard two helicopters flying ``real low'' just
before one hit the desert floor.
   ``They were flying so low you could throw a rock and hit them,''
he said.
   Since 1978, 37 of 41 Army helicopter crashes in which night
goggles were used occurred when there was not enough moonlight for
the light-amplifying devices to operate properly, the Orange County
(Calif.) Register reported Sunday.
   Those crashes killed 65 soldiers when mechanically sound
helicopters flew into mountains, oceans, lakes, trees and power
lines, the newspaper reported.
   The Army's policy of flying under overcast and moonless nights
with night-vision goggles never has been cited as a contributing
factor in a crash, military records show.
   The CH-3E, which was most noted for its use in combat rescues
during the Vietnam War, is made by Sikorsky, according to Jane's All
the World's Aircraft.
   ``In wartime their mission would be to rescue downed pilots from
behind enemy lines, consequently they do a lot of night training for
combat rescue,'' Besich said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Shuttle-Voice     03-13 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Voice,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Counts Down Discovery Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first woman to serve as NASA
commentator for the liftoff of a spaceship carrying astronauts said
Monday she was pleased with her performance _ even though she jumped
the gun in one of her reports.
   ``I said the ice team had already made their report to
management,'' Lisa Malone, 27, said in an interview. ``And I thought
that they had. This was one of those times when there was a lot
going on. It was just a few minutes later, then they came on and
gave their report.''
   Malone, who sat in the top row of the firing room a few seats
down from the launch director for Discovery's liftoff, said ``It was
just a matter of time'' before NASA used a woman as launch
commentator.
   After the launch, she was back in her office at the Kennedy Space
Center's press headquarters where she works as space shuttle
specialist. But instead of analyzing weather and engineering
reports, she was kept busy by reporters asking her to analyze her
performance.
   ``I think I did alright,'' she said, adding that it went more
smoothly than she expected ``because the launch team did such a good
job they made my job easier.''
   She said she was surprised journalists were asking her about her
pioneering role as launch commentator.
   ``I guess (it's) because they've always heard a male voice during
commentary,'' she said.
   ``There are so many woman newscasters,'' she said. ``I don't
really consider this job that much different from what they're
doing.''
   As commentator, Malone explained to the public what took place
behind the scenes as the countdown clock ticked to zero and the
shuttle rumbled skyward from its launch pad. Her job lasted longer
than she had bargained for, as bad weather delayed the liftoff by
nearly two hours.
   Malone, who was a bachelor's degree in journalism from the
University of Alabama in Tuscaloosa, took part in a work-study
program for three semesters at Kennedy Space Center beginning in
1982. She accepted an offer of a full-time job as public relations
specialist with the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
during her last semester as an intern.
   Malone edited the space center newsletter, Spaceport News, for
three years before she was assigned to the shuttle beat.
   To prepare for Monday's debut, Malone provided launch commentary
for some unmanned Atlas Centaur and Delta launches and for the early
portions of some shuttle countdowns and hired a voice coach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
