<FIRST>r p AM-Cheney-Sharratt     03-13 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney-Sharratt,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>1988 Democratic House Nominee Wants Cheney's Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Democrat who was trounced by U.S. Rep.
Dick Cheney in last November's election said Monday he should
receive his party's nomination for Cheney's seat if the Republican
becomes defense secretary.
   Bryan Sharratt said he deserves the nomination because of the
time and money he devoted to trying to unseat Cheney in 1988 and
that any other Democrats who seek it would be ``opportunistic.''
   The Wheatland attorney, who lost the general election race by a
vote of 118,350 to 56,527, said he believed there was one major
reason why he didn't defeat Cheney.
   ``And that is that I was running against one of the most powerful
Republican 10-year incumbents in the nation,'' he said.
   Cheney, who last fall won a sixth two-year term as Wyoming's lone
member of the House of Representatives, was President Bush's second
nominee for defense secretary. While Bush's first nominee, former
Sen. John Tower, was rejected by the Senate following lengthy debate
over allegations of heavy drinking and womanizing, Cheney is
expected to easily win confirmation.
   When that happens, it would be up to Wyoming Gov. Mike Sullivan
to set a special election within 40 days for the selection of a
successor to Cheney. The state's Republican and Democratic central
committees would each choose a candidate.
   Other Democrats believed interested in the seat are state Sen.
John Vinich, who narrowly lost his bid to unseat incumbent U.S. Sen.
Malcolm Wallop last fall, and Pete Maxfield, a former University of
Wyoming professor who lost the Democratic Senate nomination to
Vinich.
</TEXT>
