<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 2140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CollegeDesegregation     03-13 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-College Desegregation,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiations Fail To Settle Dispute, Hearings Ordered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attempts to settle the 15-year-old Louisiana
college desegregation lawsuit broke down Monday, and a federal
official called for immediate public hearings.
   ``There's not an agreement,'' said John Kennedy, attorney for the
state. ``I think we're all disappointed by that. The only thing
worse than not having a consensus is having a bad consensus.''
   Kennedy would not say what sticking points prevented a settlement
during the intense negotiations under way since Wednesday.
   ``I don't think there has been a complete consensus on any
issue,'' he said.
   The court-appointed special master who must oversee any
desegregation plan, Paul Verkuil, called for the opening of the
hearing after meeting with lawyers in private for more than an hour.
   State Sen. William Jefferson, representing Southern University,
one of the predominantly black institutions in the state system,
blamed the stalemate at least in part on Gov. Buddy Roemer.
   He accused the governor of having ``submarined'' the process, but
he would not be specific.
   The attorneys said they had no idea how long the hearing would
last or when a decision would be issued.
   Verkuil has decided to limit the hearing to rebuttal testimony,
to let the different sides dispute the abundant testimony already in
the printed record. The hearing was scheduled to begin last week,
but Verkuil postponed it until Monday in hopes a trial could be
avoided.
   In the lawsuit, the U.S. Justice Department accuses the state of
maintaining a long-standing system of predominantly black colleges
like Grambling and Southern and predominantly white universities
like Louiana State Univesity.
   The state, Southern University, the Justice Department and the
Grambling State University Alumni Association have four different
integration plans before Verkuil.
   The governor insists on consolidating the four boards that
oversee higher education in the state into one ``superboard'' and
creating a statewide community college system. The alumni of the
traditionally black schools feel that such plans will make it harder
for underprivileged youngsters to get the kinds of assistance they
need to succeed at four-year colleges.
   The alumni want to move programs to the historically black
colleges to promote integration, but state and federal officials say
that approach has not worked in other states.
   Verkuil is president of the college of William &amp; Mary in Virginia
and a former dean of Tulane Law School. He was appointed by federal
court to oversee the case.
</TEXT>
