<FIRST>u i PM-Botha 2ndLd-Writethru a0524 03-13 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Botha, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0524,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with party caucus calling for Botha's
replacement. Pickup 5th graf, `De Klerk...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the governing
National Party today adopted a resolution calling for the party's
new leader, Frederik W. de Klerk, to replace P.W. Botha as president.
   Botha, 73, who suffered a stroke in January, said he plans to
return to work Wednesday and wants to stay in office at least until
next year, despite widespread calls for his resignation.
   He said in a televised interview Sunday that he would not call an
early election this year, dampening hopes within his party that he
would step down within a few months and make way for de Klerk.
   De Klerk, who succeeded Botha as party leader on Feb. 2, had
called for the National Party's 34-member federal council _ its
highest body _ to meet in Cape Town to discuss the crisis.
   De Klerk has not disavowed reports that he is seeking either
Botha's early resignation or a formal share of policy-making powers.
   The independent South African Press Association reported today
that National Party officials were angered by Botha's refusal to
call an election this year. The latest date for the next election is
March 1990.
   ``The situation is intolerable and will have to be settled this
week,'' one unidentified party official was quoted as saying.
   The state-run South African Broadcasting Corp., which has
endeavored to be neutral in its reports on the power struggle, also
said this week would be ``of decisive importance in the present
turbulence in the party.''
   Beeld, the country's biggest Afrikaans-language daily, said in an
editorial today that the time has come for a new political order to
take hold.
   Botha, said in the television interview Sunday that de Klerk was
``being misused by some people'' and insisted there was no personal
conflict between them.
   The Star newspaper of Johannesburg, South Africa's
largest-circulation daily, said some of de Klerk's backers were
``dismayed by Botha's impressive performance'' during the interview.
   The president looked healthy during his 15-minute appearance and
said he would remain in office out of a sense of duty rather than a
desire to cling to the position he has held since 1978.
   Botha indicated he was upset by suggestions that a de Klerk
presidency would open the way for new political reforms, saying, ``I
originated the concept of reform.''
   De Klerk, 52, was education minister when he took over as leader
of the National Party. He holds solid support from National Party
parliament members. He also has won at least tacit backing from
pro-Nationalist newspapers, which view him as more pragmatic and
open-minded than Botha.
   During Botha's convalescence, de Klerk has suggested in speeches
that the government is willing to lessen its reliance on racial
classification as the foundation for political and social structures.
   However, he has told white voters he will not betray them and has
affirmed his commitment to segregated residential areas for whites
who want them. Like Botha, de Klerk has given no indication he is
willing to consider full voting rights for the country's black
majority.
</TEXT>
