<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-NuisanceBeavers Bjt   03-13 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuisance Beavers, Bjt,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Furry Engineers Make Too Spectacular a Comeback to Massachusetts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beavers, which sustained the Pilgrims
but nearly disappeared from Massachusetts during the height of the
fur trade, have made such a comeback in the last half century that
they are a nuisance.
   And a state relocation program has been called off because there
simply is no corner of the state where the toothy, dam-building
rodents are not entrenched.
   ``We've run out of places where there aren't already beavers,''
biologist James Cardoza said Monday in a telephone interview from
the Massachusetts Division of Fisheries and Wildlife headquarters in
Westboro.
   He said it is impossible to estimate the number of beavers in
Massachusetts because of their reclusive aquatic lifestyle, but last
year the division tried to resolve 185 complaints about the furry
engineers.
   Massachusetts is not alone.
   Robert J. Naiman, a beaver expert and director of the Center for
Streamside Studies at the University of Washington, said California
and Nevada introduced beaver several years ago and now are having
second thoughts because of the havoc the critters are playing with
trout streams.
   Wisconsin is about to launch a six-month beaver hunting season on
March 15, the largest in state history, to try to control the beaver
population. State Wildlife and Fisheries Management spokesman Ryan
Groener said beavers damming trout streams and cutting valuable
timber have driven state wildlife officials to authorize the hunt
and to pay $7.50 per pelt.
   Naiman said Tierra Del Fuego in the southern tip of Argentina
also introduced beavers in 1942 and is now blaming the animal for a
decline in the trout industry.
   Witney Tilt, project director for the Fish and Wildlife
Foundation of Washington, D.C., a non-profit agency, said the beaver
population in the United States could have been as high as 400
million before Europeans arrived. The current population is
estimated to be as many as 12 million.
   The industrious animals helped the state's first settlers
survive, Cardoza said. ``The beavers were the reason they were able
to sustain the Colony because their sponsors wanted to bargain with
the Indians for furs.''
   By the Revolutionary War, however, beavers had disappeared from
Massachusetts and most of New England because of year-round trapping
and the draining of wetlands for farming.
   After an absence of two centuries, two beaver colonies took hold
in Berkshire County in the 1920s. One had drifted downstream from
northern New England and the other may have been brought to
Massachusetts by a resident who wanted to re-establish the
population, Cardoza said.
   The animals flourished, so much so that in the 1950s a beaver
hunting season was opened. Another state biologist, Tom Decker, said
the four-month season that ended in February yielded fewer pelts
that usual because the market price was down.
   Among some of the biggest beaver headaches in Massachusetts was a
colony in the town of Montgomery that drew spectators for years,
until the beavers set their sights in 1986 on a brook flowing under
Main Street.
   The animals built dams faster than work crews could demolish
them, causing the brook to threaten to overflow the main
thoroughfare of the town of 500 people and inspiring one resident to
hang a sign bearing a score: ``Beavers 33, Waterworks 10, Highway
Department 0.''
   In 1985 an epidemic of the intestinal disease giardiasis that
affected more than 1,000 people in Pittsfield was blamed on beaver
droppings contaminating the city water supply. The beavers were
killed by trappers.
   Some scientists now suspect, however, that the beavers were not
to blame and Cardoza says the rodents are often scapegoats. ``The
potential from human contamination has been vastly overlooked,'' he
said.
   Wildlife biologists are advising residents about humane ways to
sidestep beaver problems without destroying the animals. Residents
may kill beavers without a permit only if property damage is serious.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
