<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 2134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NationalService     03-13 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-National Service,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nunn Says National Service Plan Will Help Military Recruitment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to provide financial incentives to
young people who participate in civilian or military service would
enhance military recruitment, not undermine it as some critics have
charged, the chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee said
Monday.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said the national service legislation he
and Rep. Dave McCurdy, D-Okla., introduced in January is not
intended to make civilian service more attactive than military
service.
   He said proposed incentives might have to be adjusted to ensure
that military service remains the most attractive option, but the
net effect of the bill would be an overall increase in young people
willing to serve their country.
   ``If you create a huge increase in the pool of people who want to
serve, either in civilian or military service, it is my firm belief
that you're going to have more people going into the military, not
less,'' he said.
   During a news conference called to announce the U.S. Jaycees'
endorsement of the national service proposal, Nunn and McCurdy
responded to criticism of their bill.
   Robbie Dawkins, national vice president of the group which has
240,000 members aged 21 to 39, said such voluntary national service
would ``promote a new spirit of citizenship and commitment.''
   Under the legislation, young people who serve two years in the
military would get $24,000 for college or vocational school or for
buying a house. Two years of civilian service would net $20,000 in
education or housing aid. It would make national service a
requirement for young people to qualify for federal college loans
and grants.
   Rep. Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss., a senior member of the House
Armed Services Committee and chairman of the House Veterans Affairs
Committee, said last week he opposes the idea because it would draw
high-quality people away from the military by paying them for
community service.
   Similar complaints were voiced to a House Armed Services
subcommittee last week by Grant S. Green, the Pentagon's manpower
chief. He said the bill's ``lucrative alternatives for civilian
service or shorter enlistments'' would ``reduce recruit quality,
increase training costs and adversely affect the productivity of
military personnel.''
   Montgomery said armed services would be forced to accept two-year
volunteers whether they need them or not. He also said the bill's
incentives would undermine the GI Bill, which provides $10,800 in
education aid after three years of military service.
   McCurdy, however, said the plan would enhance the GI Bill by
providing vocational school or housing benefits to young people who
serve but don't want to go to college. The existing GI bill, he
said, offers nothing to such people.
   ``The bottom line is we want to keep having the military be the
most attractive option,'' Nunn said.
</TEXT>
