<DOCNO> AP890313-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-LeipzigFair     03-13 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leipzig Fair,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany's Economy Slowing Down; Joint Ventures Difficult</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twice a year, Communist East Germany
welcomes thousands of capitalists from around the world to the
sprawling Leipzig Trade Fair.
   But visiting trade officials say that despite an increasing
interest in trade with the West, East Germany still is far from
embracing the reforms needed to encourage joint ventures with
Western countries.
   ``They are afraid that once the West _ and especially West
Germany _ gets a foot in the door, that they'll buy the whole place
up,'' said a high-ranking member of the U.S. trade delegation at the
fair, which opened Sunday and ends March 18.
   West Germany accounts for 64 percent of East Germany's trade with
the West. It also is a key source of hard currency for East Germany,
which needs convertible currency to buy Western-made goods and
equipment to modernize its industries.
   But according to the West German Economics Ministry, trade
between the two countries fell last year and appears headed for a
long period of stagnation.
   The slowdown is in part the result of fewer East German goods
being made available for sale to the West.
   ``The Soviet Union is now demanding better products from East
Germany at a time when increased exports to the West are needed to
earn vital hard currency,'' another U.S. trade official said. ``All
this has to be done while still trying to provide quality goods to
its national consumers.''
   East German economists admit privately the economy is facing
growing pressures.
   ``The days of the guaranteed `brotherhood' trade agreements (with
other Communist countries) are passing,'' said an East German
government official, referring to special trade agreements among
Warsaw Pact nations.
   The official said competition for hard currency sales has grown
fiercer between East European nations. Many are scrambling to
implement reforms and increase Western trade ties to shore up their
economies.
   The government official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
confirmed that the Soviet Union _ East Germany's biggest trading
partner _ is pressing for delivery of more top-rate goods. That
reduces East Germany's potential hard currency trading stocks with
the West.
   Another senior government official admitted that East Germany's
industrial base is rapidly becoming obsolete.
   ``Our industrial infrastructure, once state of the art in the
early 1970s, has now outlived its usefulness,'' the official said.
   Modernization has lagged in part because 80 percent of the
nation's high-grade machinery goods are exported rather than used at
home, said John F. Nosworthy, director general of the London-based
Machine Tool Trades Association.
   Nosworthy said East German insistence on reciprocal trade
arrangements also hinders broader development of import-export
agreements.
   East German restrictions on foreign travel also hinder business
ties with the West.
   Those restrictions are aimed in part at preventing politically
embarrassing and economically damaging defections, like the case
last month of Reinhard Fichte. The head of East Germany's renowned
Meissen porcelain factory defected to West Germany while on a trade
fair visit to Frankfurt.
   It will be difficult for East German authorities to make joint
venture proposals that are attractive to Western partners as long as
East German managers and engineers are restricted in the type and
frequency of visits they can make to the partner's facilities, one
American executive said.
   ``In order to make a joint venture work, you need a smart,
powerful and flexible partner,'' the executive said. ``You don't get
that here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
