<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Jamming     03-13 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Jamming,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Liberty Broadcast to Soviet Union Jammed, Activist Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in more than three months, the
Soviets jammed U.S.-financed Radio Liberty on Monday as it broadcast
news of a demonstration in Moscow and criticism of a member of the
Politburo, an activist said.
   ``It was completely jammed for 45 minutes,'' said Yuri Mityunov,
a member of the Democratic Union, an independent political party,
and a journalist whose commentaries are carried on Radio Liberty's
Russian-language broadcasts, which are beamed at the Soviet Union.
   Mityunov said in a telephone interview that the jamming stopped
momentarily Monday, but resumed later Monday night.
   On Nov. 29, 1988, the Soviets stopped jamming Radio Liberty and
several other foreign radio stations, including West Germany's
Deutsche Welle and the Voice of Israel.
   That step was heralded as another move in President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's campaign for ``glasnost,'' or greater openness.
   Mityunov said Radio Liberty was jammed Monday night as it
broadcast a report about a demonstration Sunday in Moscow in honor
of the 1917 February Revolution, which toppled Russia's czardom. The
Bolsheviks seized power later that year, sweeping away the
Provisional Government established in February.
   Mityunov said an editorial he wrote also was jammed. He said his
editorial accused Moscow party boss Lev N. Zaikov, a member of the
Politburo, of trying to prevent the nomination of his predecessor,
maverick communist Boris N. Yeltsin, as a candidate in the March 26
elections to a new national assembly.
   Mityunov held the recever of his telephone up to his radio so the
whine of the jamming was audible.
   ``They used to call this `Khrushchev music,' or `Brezhnev
music,''' he said, referring to former leaders Nikita S. Khrushchev
and Leonid I. Brezhnev. ``Now we'll have to call it Gorbachev
music.''
</TEXT>
