<FIRST>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral     03-13 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sawyer Says He'll Remain Neutral In Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer declared Monday that he would
not endorse a candidate in next month's mayoral election, despite
pleas from Jesse Jackson and others to support the only black
candidate in the race.
   Sawyer, the city's second black mayor, spurned calls from Jackson
and several local committeemen to help mend a deep rift in the black
community by backing Alderman Timothy Evans.
   Evans, who did not support Sawyer in last month's Democratic
primary, is running as a third party candidate in the April 4
election against Democrat Richard M. Daley and Republican Edward
Vrdolyak.
   ``After careful consideration, I have decided not to endorse any
candidate,'' Sawyer told reporters in a short statement.
   Evans spokeswoman Deborah Scott later downplayed the lack of
Sawyer's help in the campaign, denying that Evans would lose votes
because of Sawyer's neutrality.
   ``I don't think it's going to impact on turnout either,'' Scott
said. ``People who were saying there was no candidate to inspire
them (in the primary) now have a candidate to inspire them (in
Evans),'' she said.
   Daley, flanked by a multiracial group of Sawyer supporters who
are now in his camp, said later that he could benefit from Sawyer's
non-endorsement.
   ``I think him not endorsing anyone is very helpful to ... my
campaign, sure,'' Daley said at a news conference.
   Sawyer, 54, was soundly defeated in the Feb. 28 Democratic
mayoral primary by Daley, 46, the Cook County state's attorney and
son of the late Richard J. Daley, who was mayor for 21 years.
   Evans, 45, bypassed the primary to run as an independent in the
general election against white candidates Daley and Vrdolyak, 51.
   Some knowedgeable observers believe that Evans' lack of support
for Sawyer, who also is black, contributed to a low primary turnout
in some predominantly black wards and was a factor in Daley's
primary victory.
   Jackson has often referred to the Evans-Sawyer split among blacks
and other allies of the late Mayor Harold Washington _ the city's
first black mayor _ as a ``civil war.''
   But Sawyer answered ``no'' when asked Monday if he was bitter
about Evans' failure to endorse him in the primary.
   ``All candidates have sought my endorsement,'' Sawyer said,
adding that he would do ``everything I can to ensure a smooth
transition (for whoever is elected mayor).''
</TEXT>
