<FIRST>r i AM-Tibet     03-13 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tibet,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock-Throwing Incidents Reported in Lhasa; Martial Law to Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official Monday reported
rock-throwing incidents in Tibet's capital, despite a crackdown by
Chinese authorities, and he said martial law will continue until
anti-Chinese protests end.
   A Chinese businessman in the capital, Lhasa, told state TV he was
afraid to open his shop because he feared more riots.
   The nationally televised news showed police surrounding major
intersections in Lhasa. One frame showed an old woman being
searched. Another showed several soldiers checking the identity
cards of bicyclists. The report said the city was calm.
   The scene was photographed Saturday, but the official at the
provincial office of Tibet in Beijing said troops continued to
patrol the city.
   ``Right now there is no possibility of the order being lifted,''
said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Martial
law in Lhasa will end only when the authorities are assured that the
situation will stay calm.''
   Martial law took effect March 8, after three days of riots in the
capital of the remote region.
   ``Things have gotten better with martial law,'' said one Chinese
businessman in Lhasa, interviewed on television. ``But these rioting
Tibetans were very scary. I don't dare open the store.''
   All residents of Lhasa are required to have an identity card and
show it upon request. Last week, the television news said more than
1,000 people had applied for cards in one day.
   The official said Tibetans defying the crackdown had been dealt
with ``harshly and in accordance with law.''
   He did not say when the rock-throwing incidents occurred, but
sketchy reports reaching Beijing said some Tibetans attempted a
protest Thursday.
   By official count, 16 people died and about 100 were injured in
three days of riots that began March 5 when Tibetans tried to
commemorate the first anniversary of another clash.
   On March 5, 1988, anti-Chinese protesters clashed with police in
Lhasa, and an estimated 24 people died.
   Although last week's protests were initially led by Buddhist
monks and nuns, later riots, during which Chinese-owned businesses
were ransacked and Chinese bicyclists attacked, were headed by
Tibetan youths.
   The government apparently ordered the crackdown to avoid more
protests to commemorate a March 10, 1959 uprising against Chinese
rule in which hundreds died and Tibet's god-king, the Dalai Lama,
fled to India.
   More anniversaries are coming. March 17 is the day the Dalai Lama
left Lhasa for India in 1959. On March 19 and 20, 1959, the Chinese
army used heavy artillery to suppress the uprising.
   Beijing claims that Tibet has been part of China since the 13th
century. Tibetans say their homeland was really independent for most
of that time.
</TEXT>
