<FIRST>r a AM-CruseTrial     03-13 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruse Trial,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opening Arguments Of Cruse Trial Raise Question Of Sanity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a retired librarian accused of
killing six people and wounding 10 others in a shooting rampage
began Monday with the prosecution saying the defendant methodically
shot his victims.
   But the defense maintains William Cruse is a paranoid
schizophrenic and is innocent by reason of insanity.
   Cruse, looking frail with unruly gray hair, is charged with
killing six people, including two police officers, wounding 10,
shooting at 18 others and kidnapping two at two Palm Bay shopping
centers during a seven-hour crime spree April 23, 1987.
   In opening arguments Monday before Circuit Judge John Antoon,
both sides agreed Cruse suffered delusions and believed his
neighbors thought he was a homosexual.
   A prosecutor said his festering anger triggered the shooting
spree at the Publix and Winn-Dixies grocery stores at the two
shopping centers in the community located in central Florida.
   But the defense said it was the obsession of a paranoid
schizophrenic who twisted words and gestures into a sinister plot
against him, believed the whole world was interested in his sex life
and thought doctors programmed him during surgery to stare at men's
crotches.
   Chronic and severe mental illness, pre-existing brain damage and
alcohol, ``combined into a very deadly mixture'' and he lost touch
with reality, said defense attorney Paul Arlt, setting the stage for
the insanity defense.
   The state said Cruse bought a high-velocity, semiautomatic rifle
a month before the shooting, then bought six 30-round clips and
sufficient ammunition a week before the massacre.
   ``He had control of his weapon at all times,'' said Assistant
State Attorney Wayne Holmes. ``When he needed to bring it to eye
level and (take a) marksman stance, he did so.''
   ``His mental disease in no way justifies killing six, wounding
10, shooting at numerous others and kidnapping two,'' Holmes said.
   But Arlt said Cruse's ``psychiatric illness overwhelmed him, he
was totally out of touch with reality.''
   The trial is expected to last four weeks.
</TEXT>
