<FIRST>r w AM-DrugParaphernalia     03-13 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Paraphernalia,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Announces Big Seizures of Drug Paraphernalia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of pipes, scales and other items were
arrayed Monday at U.S. Customs Service headquarters as Commissioner
William von Raab announced seizures of up to $10 million in drug
paraphernalia over the past few weeks.
   One of the pipes _ a shiny brass item marked $16.95 _ contained a
warning, ``This product not intended for illegal use,'' as well as
more prosaic instructions on how to maintain the ``gloss finish.''
   But the warning didn't dissuade the Customs Service from seizing
the items in Northern Virginia last month or from seizing a
40,000-square-foot warehouse full of similar items March 1 in
Nashville.
   The Tennessee seizure of some 306,000 items at the Contempo
Products Inc. warehouse, was the ``largest ever,'' von Raab said.
The second largest occurred March 4 at the Award Distributing Co. in
Philadelphia, he said.
   ``We're going to take away from the drug abuser the tools of his
trade,'' von Raab said. Those who manufacture and distribute such
products ``are putting yourself at risk to lose millions of dollars
of your inventory,'' he said.
   The Nashville seizure filled eight 48-foot containers, while the
Philadelphia seizure filled four, he said.
   Even so, von Raab acknowledged that the amount confiscated would
``probably not have a measurable impact'' on the drug paraphernalia
industry. He estimated that hundreds of millions of dollars worth of
drug paraphernalia is sold annually.
   There have been no arrests in any of the recent cases, but von
Raab said U.S. attorneys around the country ``are identifying people
who might be indicted.''
   The seizures are part of the Paraphernalia Interdiction Program
for Enforcement, known as PIPE, which von Raab created last April 15
as an outgrowth of the Mail Order Drug Paraphernalia Act of 1986.
   The PIPE effort has led to 13 major drug paraphernalia cases
conducted by the Customs Service, and about $15 million worth of
such items has been seized thus far, the service said. In addition
to Nashville, Philadelphia, and Northern Virginia, seizures have
been made by Customs officials in Washington, New York City,
Detroit, Houme, La., and Tallahassee, Fla.
</TEXT>
