<SECOND>AM-People-O'Connor,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor's Recovery `Excellent'; `Heat' Calls In Joe Don Baker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carroll O'Connor, star of NBC-TV's ``In the Heat
of the Night,'' was moved out of intensive care Monday as he
recovers from cardiac bypass surgery at Emory University Hospital.
   Meanwhile, in Los Angeles, publicists for the show announced
Monday that actor Joe Don Baker has been signed as a guest star for
the four episodes remaining in the 1988-89 season.
   The scripts will have Baker portraying a neighboring sheriff who
fills in while Police Chief Bill Gillespie _ O'Connor's character _
represents his state at a seminar on terrorism.
   ``Everyone at MGM@UA (producers of the show) is thrilled and
grateful that Carroll has come through the procedure with flying
colors,'' said David Gerber, chairman of MGM@UA Television.
   ``Joe Don responded to my call for help immediately,'' Gerber
added. ``He expressed tremendous concern for Carroll as well as his
enthusiasm for the show. ... We are relieved that Carroll will be
able to rejoin the company for next season.''
   Emory University Hospital spokeswoman Eve Patterson said Monday
that O'Connor continues to recover well from his six-graft cardiac
bypass surgery Saturday. He is expected to remain hospitalized
another week or so.
   ``He's making excellent progress,'' she said. ``His doctors say
his heart muscle was undamaged, and that's adding to his recovery.''
   The need for bypass surgery was determined after O'Connor had a
positive heart stress test while undergoing an examination in nearby
Covington, where he has been filming ``In the Heat of the Night.''
   O'Connor is perhaps best known for his role as Archie Bunker on
the trailblazing situation comedy ``All in the Family.''
