<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Protests     03-13 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Protests,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Detained at Demonstrations; Radio Report on Protest Jammed</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Stands as 1st Ld-Writethru to AM-Soviet Jamming, a0670</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities detained at least 240 demonstrators in
two cities who likened communism to czarist tyranny, and officials
jammed U.S.-financed Radio Liberty on Monday as it reported on the
protests, activists said.
   The actions marked the widest reported crackdown on demonstrators
in Moscow and Leningrad in months and the first jamming of Radio
Liberty since the Soviets halted the practice last fall under
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program for greater openness.
   Valery Terekhev, 40, said he was one of more than 200 people
detained Sunday in Leningrad in connection with an unauthorized
three-hour demonstration calling for multiple-party democracy in the
Soviet Union.
   ``I think there have never been so many people detained in
Leningrad,'' Terekhev said in a telephone interview.
   All of those detained were released pending trials set for
Wednesday through Friday, said Terekhev, a member of the Democratic
Union, an independent party that challenges the Communist Party's
monopoly on political power.
   He said 15 buses brought about 2,000 police backed up with dogs
to round up protesters in Leningrad who were demonstrating on the
72nd anniversary of the 1917 overthrow of the Russian monarchy.
   Terekhev said the date of the demonstration was chosen to show
that the current ``totalitarian'' one-party system in the Soviet
Union should be replaced with a democratic, multiparty system and a
free press _ just as the 1917 revolution ended czarist
totalitarianism.
   The 1917 revolution took place in February under the old-style
religious calendar then in use.
   In Moscow, about 40 people were detained Sunday during a similar
protest on Mayakovsky Square, said Yuri Mityunov, a Moscow-based
member of the Democratic Union.
   One of the slogans of the multi-city demonstrations was:
``Against the absolutism of the Communist Party,'' which echoed a
slogan of the forces that toppled the Russian monarchy in 1917:
``Against the absolutism of the czar,'' Mityunov said.
   One of those taken away by Moscow police, Sergei Grigoryants,
editor of the now defunct magazine Glasnost, was given a 10-day jail
term, said Viktor Rezunkov, another editor of the magazine. The
magazine was raided by police last year.
   Radio Liberty's reports on the demonstrations and similar
protests in the Siberian city of Irkutsk and the Volga industrial
city of Kuibyshev were blocked when Soviet authorities suddenly
began jamming them, said Mityunov, a journalist whose commentaries
are aired on the radio's Russian-language broadcasts beamed at the
Soviet Union.
   ``It was completely jammed for 45 minutes,'' Mityunov said. He
said in a telephone interview that the jamming stopped momentarily,
but resumed later Monday night.
   Mityunov said the mass detention of protesters reminded him of
abuses committed under the Russian monarchy. ``It's a rebirth of the
same absolutism,'' he said.
   On Nov. 29, the Soviets stopped interfering with the broadcasts
of Radio Liberty, based in West Germany, and several other foreign
radio stations, including Deutsche Welle, also in West Germany, and
the Voice of Israel, Israel's state-run station.
   Mityunov said Radio Liberty was also jammed Monday as it aired an
editorial he had written. He said his editorial accused Moscow party
boss Lev N. Zaikov, a member of the party's ruling Politburo, of
trying to prevent the nomination of his predecessor, maverick
Communist Boris N. Yeltsin, as a candidate in the March 26 elections
to a new national assembly.
   Mityunov held the receiver of his telephone up to his radio so
the whine of the jamming was audible.
   ``They used to call this Khrushchev music, or Brezhnev music,''
he said, referring to past Soviet leaders. ``Now we'll have to call
it Gorbachev music.''
   The Communists seized power in Russia in November 1917, sweeping
away the Provisional Government created to succeed the czar after
the February Revolution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
