<DOCNO> AP890313-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 2225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WeatherService     03-13 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weather Service,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Stations To Remain For Time Being</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher on Monday
directed that all the government's weather stations remain in
service while a program to restructure the National Weather Service
is developed, ending speculation of imminent station closings.
   ``It is not in the best interests of the nation to close any
weather station until the modernization plan is operational,''
Mosbacher said.
   While the department said there would be no immediate closings,
it said plans to modernize the Weather Service make some eventual
closings inevitable.
   Speculation that the department planned to close down or curtail
service at some weather stations because of budget constraints had
prompted criticism from members of Congress concerned about cutbacks
in their home states.
   Mosbacher said the administration's proposed budget for fiscal
1990, which starts Oct. 1, includes a request to finance a
modernization and restructuring program for the Weather Service that
would improve forecasting and weather warning systems.
   The new system would include advanced weather radar, observation
automation and a new communications system.
   ``Closing any of the stations at this point might reduce service
to the public, when we are, in fact, working to improve that
service,'' Mosbacher said. ``I intend to work closely with the
Congress to insure maintenance of the quality and coverage of the
National Weather Service.''
