<FIRST>r w AM-Skinner-MassTransit     03-13 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinner-Mass Transit,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Announces Plan to Encourage Local Mass Transit Funding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner told
state and local mass transit officials Monday to stop looking for
more federal funding, and he announced a program to reward
communities that raise more than required to match federal funds.
   Skinner, who was chairman of the Chicago area mass transit system
before joining President Bush's Cabinet, said mass transit needs
federal help but not as much as it has been getting. He also said
more transit systems should contract with private business for some
services.
   Skinner told the American Public Transit Association he would
lead a ``push for greater state and local involvement in mass
transit funding.''
   ``If we become too dependent in mass transit upon Washington, we
will be subject to their whims; we will not control our own
destiny,'' he said.
   Skinner said that communities that ``overmatch'' federal funds in
mass transit programs will get a higher priority and faster funding
from his department.
   He also said he would travel to communities which are having
difficulty raising funds and appear before legislatures or city and
county officials to appeal for an increased local role.
   Money would be available to fund experimental projects that
support local fund-raising, he said.
   Skinner also said he would support programs to provide more
transportation for jobless city dwellers who want to get work in
suburban areas where jobs are more plentiful.
   ``This administration is going to do everything we can to see
that people can get those jobs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
