<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1838EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Quebec-Blackout     03-13 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quebec-Blackout,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Power Failure Cuts Electricity For Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Quebec residents were left without
power in their homes and businesses Monday and Montreal's subway
shut down when a power failure knocked out electricity to most of
the province.
   The blackout occurred at about 2:45 a.m. near the James Bay
hydroelectric project in northern Quebec and affected about 6
million residents of Montreal, Quebec City and most of the rest of
the province.
   ``We don't know the exact cause, but usually with this type of
failure the problem is on a line or in a substation,'' said Jacques
Henri Couture, a spokesman for the provincial electric company,
Hydro Quebec.
   About two-thirds of Quebec had power restored by noon, and crews
were ordered to work through the night if necessary to restore full
power in all areas of the province.
   Traffic lights were knocked out, and there wasn't enough power to
start up the extensive Montreal subway system, which carries about
600,000 commuters a day. Service stations couldn't pump gasoline
because the pumps work on electricity.
   Residents of Quebec, including Energy Minister John Ciaccia,
expressed anger at the power company.
   ``This is very upsetting, not only for the people but for the
government,'' Ciaccia said of the blackout, the third province-wide
failure since April.
   Ciaccia said he demanded a meeting with top Hydro officials for
an explanation. He said the power failures would affect the
utility's credibility in the United States, where it has negotiated
huge sales contracts.
   Some people blamed the big sales of electricity to the United
States for contributing to the blackout by straining the system.
   ``They're selling electricity left, right and center to the
Americans and it's the people in Quebec who are paying for it,''
said Fernand Mathurin, assistant manager at a convenience store in
the Gaspe region of eastern Quebec.
   The outage caused an instant 1,200-megawatt shortage in New
England, which imports Hydro Quebec electricity directly from Quebec
and through New Brunswick, but regional utilities brought operating
reserves on line within 10 minutes, New England Power Pool spokesman
William Sheperdson said.
   After tapping additional generating capacity, the power pool was
shipping 300 megawatts of power back to Quebec through power lines
in northern New Hampshire and Vermont, Sheperdson said.
   Sheperdson and Vincent Iacopino, chairman of New Hampshire's
Public Utilities Commission, said there was no indication that Hydro
Quebec's power sales to New England were to blame for the outage.
   The provincial utility now sells only excess power to New
England, though it plans larger, guaranteed power sales along
dedicated lines to New England in the 1990s as it develops more
hydroelectric resources in the vast James Bay complex of northern
Quebec.
   But Iacopino said the blackout ``confirms that there has to be
some strengthening of the Canadian system for us to rely on that
power.''
   At the Fairmount Bagel Factory in Montreal, the wood-burning
ovens were working, but the bagels weren't coming off the line
because the the dough-making machines were out.
   The Rachel Farm poultry factory was also having problems.
   ``My workers have been here since 3:30 a.m., but we can't do
anything because the plucking machines aren't working,'' said a man
at the poultry farm who identified himself only as Joseph.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
