<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 2237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-MadagascarEln     03-13 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Madagascar Eln,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Winning Slight Majority in Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Didier Ratsiraka was
winning a slight majority in election returns Monday night, a
dramatic reversal from previous votes in which the socialist leader
ran up huge majorities.
   All three opposition candidates blamed the 52-year-old
presidsent's policies for economic decline on the island off
southeast Africa. Interior Ministry figures released after about
half the 5.5 million votes had been counted gave the president 56.2
percent.
   In the 1982 election Ratsiraka got 80 percent of the votes, and
he won a 1975 referendum on his presidency with 95 percent.
   He must finish with a majority this time to avoid a runoff with
the leading challenger. As expected, Manandafy Rakotonirina of the
Proletarian Movement Party was in second place with 28.89 percent of
the vote.
   No major incidents were reported during the balloting Sunday.
Ratsiraka had denied an opposition request to allow foreign
observers but the Federation of Christian Churches said it would
monitor the vote in case of fraud.
   Final figures were not expected for several days because of
transport and communications problems on the Indian Ocean island of
226,658 square miles.
   The ruling military chose Ratsiraka as president in 1975. He
broke many ties with France, the former colonial power, and with
other Western countries and set the nation on a socialist course,
nationalizing many foreign-owned industries.
   Natural disasters ranging from cyclones to droughts beset the
island and, with the economy near bankruptcy in 1982, Ratsiraka
began restoring economic ties with the West.
   He and his opponents in this campaign all claimed they had the
support of Western governments and lending institutions.
</TEXT>
