<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 2242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChurchProtest     03-13 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Protest,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Vote To Reopen Church Closed After Polish Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic church that was closed
to end a protest by dissident Polish parishioners will be reopened,
with warnings that troublemakers could be arrested, a parish
corporation member said Monday.
   The corporation's five-member executive board, which includes
Bridgeport Bishop Edward Egan, voted privately Friday to reopen
predominantly Polish St. Michael the Archangel Roman Catholic
Church, probably by Sunday, which is Palm Sunday, said Edward
Tulinski Sr., one of two lay members of the corporation.
   ``We've been away from home too long,'' Tulinski said.
   The church has been closed since Feb. 18, when church officials
called police into the church to end a weeklong sit-in staged by
about 200 parishioners who were upset by the transfer of a popular
Polish priest, the Rev. Roman Palaszewski.
   On the advice of the corporation's lawyer, signs will be posted
threatening the arrest of anyone who attempts to occupy the church
or start any activity not authorized by the pastor, the Rev. John
Bambol, Tulinski said.
   The dissidents have held prayer vigils outside the church each
Sunday since the closing. They have charged that Bambol engineered
Palaszewski's ouster because he was too active in the Polish
community. They also questioned Bambol's commitment to maintaining
the church's Polish character.
   Bambol and his supporters have blamed much of the unrest on
recent immigrants from Poland, and church officials have refused to
meet with the dissidents.
   Henry Chmiel, one of two parishioners arrested when they refused
to leave the church, vowed to continue the protest despite the
arrest warning.
   ``I'll be the first to get arrested again,'' he said.
   The dissidents are talking about filing a lawsuit challenging the
church's authority to have them expelled last month, said Halina
Chmiel, Chmiel's wife and one of the dissident leaders. They planned
to meet with an attorney this week, she said.
   But Monsignor Nicholas V. Grieco, a spokesman for Egan, said the
protesters' demands remain non-negotiable: Palaszewksi will not be
returned to the church and Bambol will not be removed.
   Tulinski said church officials did not publicize Friday's meeting
or announce plans to reopen the church because they did not want it
to become a media event. A letter was sent to registered
parishioners.
   Tulinski would not divulge exactly when the church will be
reopened and referred questions to the church rectory, where the
telephone was answered by an answering machine and calls weren't
returned.
</TEXT>
