<FIRST>u a AM-Shuttle-Fletcher     03-13 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Fletcher,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Administrator Says Replacement To Be Named Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA administrator James C. Fletcher,
who said months ago that he wanted to retire, announced on Monday
that he expects President Bush to name a new space agency leader
within two weeks.
   ``I think he (Bush) will have a successor named hopefully next
week or the week after,'' Fletcher said in an impromptu news
conference following the launch of space shuttle Discovery.
   Fletcher said he had been in contact with the White House and is
``getting a little anxious about my situation. I'm a lame duck, so
to speak.''
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration chief blamed
the delay in announcing his successor, in part, on the fight between
the White House and the Senate over the failed appointment of former
Sen. John Tower to be secretary of defense.
   ``They (Bush administration officials) got tied up with John
Tower and a lot of other appointments,'' he said. ``I've been
assured _ of course, I was assured it would be February _ that in a
week or two there would be somebody new.''
   Fletcher has twice served as NASA administrator. He first held
the job in the 1970s, and then took it again in the aftermath of the
Challenger disaster in 1986.
   Asked if he thought NASA had improved since the space shuttle
blew up and killed seven astronauts.
   ``You bet I do,'' he said. ``I'm really proud of the team. They
have come a long way.''
</TEXT>
