<FIRST>r i AM-LoveandLvov     03-13 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Love and Lvov,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Tells American Girl Love is Just Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The other young Americans wanted to know about war
and economics. But Nichole Pitman loves a young Russian, so she
asked the Politburo member if it would be all right to marry him. He
said yes, but not just yet.
   Nichole, 18, is from Cincinnati, Ohio. She put the question to
Lev N. Zaikov, 55, the Moscow Communist Party boss, who is more
accustomed to talking about President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform
programs.
   She chose the question, Nichole said, because Pavel Lvov, a
17-year-old Moscow student, visited her school on an exchange
program in January and they fell in love. She wanted to know if
Soviet laws would keep them from marrying.
   At the end of the question-and-answer session, Nichole approached
Zaikov and showed him Lvov's picture.
   When she asked for his views on Americans marrying Russians, ``he
said they should, if they're in love,'' Nichole reported later. ``He
wanted to know how old we were. When I told him, he said, `Well,
that's kind of young,' and he suggested we wait awhile.''
   She attends Princeton High School in Cincinnati and was among 140
American high school students received by Zaikov and other officials
at the Moscow city hall.
   ``I was almost afraid to ask,'' said Nichole, who is in her
fourth year of Russian language study. ``Everyone else was asking
about nuclear war and `Star Wars' and economics. But I wanted to
know, so I asked.''
   Her question and part of Zaikov's answer were shown later on
Vremya, the evening television news.
</TEXT>
