<HEAD>Name National Security Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday announced the
appointment of seven special assistants for national security
affairs.
   They are:
   _ William W. Working, formerly an intelligence officer with the
CIA and staff member of the Senate Select Committee on Intelligence,
who will serve as senior director for intelligence programs at the
White House.
   _ Charles Nicholas Rostow to serve as legal advisor to the
National Security Council, a position he held in the Reagan
administration.
   _ David C. Miller Jr. to be senior director of both international
programs and African Affairs. A former ambassador to Zimbabwe and
Tanzania, Miller has been on the board of the African Development
Foundation since 1988.
   _ Robert D. Blackwill, a career foreign service office, who will
specialize in European and Soviet affairs.
   _ Virginia A. Lampley, an executive with a Washington-based
consulting firm representing international corporations, to serve as
director for legislative affairs.
   _ Richard N. Haass, a lecturer in public policy at Harvard
University's John F. Kennedy School of Government, as senior
director, Near East and South Asian Affairs.
   _ Karl D. Jackson, senior director for Asian Affairs. Since 1986,
Jackson has been deputy assistant secretary of defense for East Asia
and Pacific Affairs.
   The president also named Burton Lee III as physician to the
president.
   Lee, 59, has been associated with the Sloan-Kettering Cancer
Center in New York since 1960, most recently as senior attending
physician.
   He is a specialist in leukemia-lymphoma diseases and served as a
member of President Reagan's AIDS commission in 1987-88.
   Bush also said he will nominate Kathleen M. Harrington to be
assistant secretary of labor for congressional affairs. She has been
assistant administrator for public affairs at the Federal Aviation
Administration since last year.
