<FIRST>r a AM-TortureTrial     03-13 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Torture Trial,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant Convicted In Torture-Slaying Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who admitted murdering his teen-age
sister-in-law because ``women flaunt their bodies'' was convicted
Monday of raping and mutilating the girl before killing her.
   John R. Weber, 25, of Phillips in northern Wisconsin, was found
guilty on seven counts of sexual assault and one count each of
mutilation and false imprisonment in the November 1986
torture-murder of Carla Lenz, 17, the sister of his wife, Emily, 22.
   The verdict sets up the second phase of Weber's trial, which will
focus on the defendant's sanity in the death of Miss Lenz and the
attempted murder of his wife last November. Prosecutors said Weber
planned a similar fate for his wife almost two years after killing
Miss Lenz.
   Circuit Judge Gary Carlson ordered the second phase of the trial
to begin Tuesday.
   ``I don't have any reaction to the verdict,'' said attorney John
Reid, who along with lawyer James Lex defended Weber.
   County District Attorney Paul Barnett said he was ``obviously
pleased'' with the verdict. ``If you're asking me if he got what I
think he deserved, yes.''
   During the trial, jurors heard a gruesome tape recording, which
authorities said was Weber's voice describing the torture and murder
of his sister-in-law.
   The tape, found in Weber's car, was played as the prosecution
completed its case Saturday. It said the teen-ager died because
``women flaunt their bodies and think they can get anything they
want.''
   Weber's wife identified the voice on the tape as that of her
husband. The defense rested its case Monday without calling a
witness.
   As the trial was about to start last week, Weber pleaded guilty
to half of the 18 charges against him, including the kidnapping and
first-degree murder of Miss Lenz and the attempted murder of his
wife. But he maintained he was innocent by reason of insanity.
   But Weber pleaded innocent on the nine charges involving the
torture and rape of Miss Lenz.
