<FIRST>r w AM-US-JapanConstruction     03-13 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan Construction,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Complains of Bid-Rigging at U.S. Base in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senator complained on Monday that Japanese
contractors rigged bids at the U.S. naval base of Yokosuka on Tokyo
Bay and were let off too lightly by the Japanese government.
   Sen. Frank Murkowski,R-Alaska, was testifying at an investigation
of access to Japanese projects for American construction firms. The
hearing, conducted by the office of U.S. Trade Representative Carla
Hill, was required by the Trade Act of last summer.
   ``The bidding on projects at the U.S. base is supervised by
Japanese nationals employed there, and I'm told that American
contractors have been unable to win any contracts,'' Murkowski said
in an interview afterwards.
   ``I would think we would have enough Americans there to supervise
the bidding.''
   After the investigation, President Bush may have to decide
whether or not the U.S. construction industry has been hurt by
Japanese practises, and if so what retaliation, if any, he wants to
take.
   Murkoswki said that last December, the Japanese Fair Trade
Commission fined 70 Japanese firms for rigging bids on projects at
Yokosuka and issued warnings to 70 others. He quoted a book on the
Japanese industry by Koji Tatezawa as saying that the Japanese
Construction Ministry refused a recommendation from the commission
to ban the firms for six to nine months from bidding on official
projects, and banned them only for a month that ended Jan. 8.
   Murkowski said:
   ``One wonders how this type of penalty is going to effectively
deter firms from engaging in dango'' -- which he defined as a system
for rotating the winning bid among Japanese firms.
   He recalled that last May Japanese Ambassador Nobuo Matsunaga and
Commerce Secretary William Verity exchanged letters on making it
easier for U.S. firms to enter the Japanese construction market.
Significant barriers nevertheless remain, Murkowski said.
   ``The only way these barriers can be removed is through a
commitment by the Japanese government to expand the coverage of the
arrangement, and to devote more resources to the enforcement of laws
prohibiting anti-competitive practices such as dango,'' he concluded.
</TEXT>
