<FIRST>u w AM-Scowcroft-Disclosure     03-13 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scowcroft-Disclosure,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Sununu-Finances</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scowcroft Got Handsome Honoraria, Consulting, Director Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National security adviser Brent Scowcroft, who
made at least $527,894 last year as a private consultant and
speaker, has removed himself from decision-making affecting some 70
U.S. companies, including such corporate giants as General Motors
and General Electric.
   Scowcroft's government disclosure form, required under provisions
of the Ethics in Government Act of 1978, also shows the retired Air
Force general was unable to specify for whom he provided services as
a hired consultant for Kissinger Associates.
   In an letter about his financial reporting form, Scowcroft told
White House counsel C. Boyden Gray that former Secretary of State
Henry A. Kissinger, who heads Kissinger Associates, ``denied my
request for a list of the clients for whom I worked.'' Scowcroft
reported receiving $293,300 for his services to Kissinger.
   Scowcroft said that ``under my contractual relationship with
Kissinger Associates, I worked for the company, not directly for its
clients.''
   Scowcroft has at least temporarily removed himself from decisions
involving dozens of companies in which he has a financial interest.
The list reads like a virtual ``Who's Who'' of corporate America,
including several major defense contractors and high-technology
giants such as IBM, Lockheed Corp., the RAND Corp., and Aerospace
Corp. Scowcroft received over $16,000 in consulting fees from
Lockheed, for example. He also got $50,000 to perform as a
consultant to the National Council for Peace and Security.
   The disclosure form showed Scowcroft has extensive bank and stock
holdings. Because officials are required under the law only to list
the valuations of assets in monetary ranges, the form indicated that
Scowcroft's holdings in 1988 were worth between $1,079,000 and
$3,265,000.
   Scowcroft reported liabilities ranging from $200,002 to $500,000.
   Because a part of his income came from interest and dividends,
which also needed only to be listed in value ranges, Scowcroft's
report showed he earned between $527,894 and $649,994.
   In the letter to Gray, Scowcroft said he intends to ``place my
common stock holdings'' in a qualified blind trust _ over which
he'll have no control _ and he would authorize the trustee ``to sell
off my stock in companies that perform services that could create a
conflict or an appearance of a conflict with my duties.''
   In the meantime, he said, ``I am recused from all matters that
have a direct and predictable effect on, or affect the financial
interests of, the entities identified'' in the disclosure form.
   ``Given the industry and sector-wide effect of most matters that
come before the assistant to the president for national security
affairs,'' the letter said, ``I plan to request a ... waiver with
respect to any of my interests that are not so substantial as to
affect my actions in matters involving broad policy issues.''
   Deputy White House press secretary Roman Popadiuk said White
House lawyers are reviewing Scowcroft's holdings to determine which
of the 70 companies could be taken off the recusal list.
   The disclosure form also showed that Scowcroft, formally national
security adviser to President Gerald R. Ford and later a member of
the presidential commission that investigated the Iran-Contra
affair, was a hot commodity on the mashed-potato circuit.
   Scowcroft reported earning $53,751 in speaking honoraria,
including appearances before such diverse audiences as the high-tech
giant, TRW, the Bonneville Knife &amp; Fork Club of Salt Lake City and
Lawrence Livermore Laboratories.
   Scowcroft, whose national security post pays about $89,000 a
year, also received $49,452 last year for his membership on various
corporate boards.
</TEXT>
