<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Ship     03-13 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Ship,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report One Dead, 15 Rescued After Ship Goes Aground</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto LON8</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. IVES, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A seaman being winched from a cargo ship
that went aground off southwest England slipped from the harness and
fell 180 feet into the raging sea, helicopter crewmen said Monday.
   He was reported missing and presumed dead.
   Air force and navy helicopters rescued all of the other 15
crewmen, most of whom were Koreans or Filipinos, from the 2,500-ton
Panamanian-registered ship Secil Japan.
   Officials said the vessel's cargo of timber shifted as the ship
was battered by heavy seas Sunday night.
   The captain radioed a distress call when the ship was six miles
off the north coast of the county of Cornwall in southwestern
England, said John Shephard of the Falmouth coast guard service.
   He said the Secil Japan was listing heavily and was driven by
winds into Hell's Mouth, a cliff-encircled bay near St. Ives, and
ran aground on rocks.
   Local residents lined up their cars on the cliff tops and
illuminated the scene with the headlights to help rescuers.
   Petty Officer Marty Dodd who was aboard one of the navy
helicpters told reporters of the unsuccesssful rescue effort.
   ``We got a high line out on to the ship but nobody made an
attempt to pick it up,'' he said. ``Then one man came out and got
into the strop and we brought him through the water as the ship was
engulfed in waves.
   ``But as he got near us he opened his arms, slipped away and fell
into the sea. We could see him swimming in the surf but we were only
five yards from the cliff and couldn't get down to him.''
   A navy spokesman said the harness was checked and no faults were
found.
   There was no immediate identification of the missing crewman.
</TEXT>
