<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-13 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Wintry Weather Over Northern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow and freezing rain were scattered across the northern Plains
and Great Lakes on Monday, and rain spread across the Southeast and
the Northwest.
   A cold front extending from Canada across the northern Plains
brought scattered snow showers to northern sections of the Great
Lakes and freezing rain from western North Dakota into southern
Montana.
   Cold air was expected to drive southward into the northern
Rockies, increasing wind and bringing snow through the region
Tuesday. A high wind watch was posted along the mountains of
southeastern Wyoming through Tuesday.
   As much as 5 to 8 inches of snow was expected around the
Yellowstone National Park region.
   A stationary front separated unseasonably warm air across the
Gulf Coast states from cooler air across the central Plains and Ohio
Valley, and rain was scattered along the front from Kentucky through
North Carolina.
   Low pressure west of Vancouver Island continued to spin off a
series of upper air disturbances across the Northwest. Showers were
scattered along the northern Pacific Coast and Eugene, Ore., had
received 1.74 inches of rain in 24 hours.
   Farther inland, 3 to 6 inches of snow fell overnight in the
mountains near Lake Tahoe, on the Nevada-California border, and wind
gusts over 70 mph were measured south of nearby Reno, Nev.
   But Colorado Springs, Colo., warmed to a record 70 degrees, one
degree above the former record set in 1959.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 18
degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., to 93 at Junction, Texas. Monday's low
for the Lower 48 states was 19 degrees below zero at Fort Kent,
Maine.
   For Tuesday, widespread showers were forecast from the Pacific
Northwest coast into northern Idaho and from northern Iowa into the
upper Great Lakes and northern Illinois. Thunderstorms, some
possibly severe, were forecast from eastern Missouri and much of
Kentucky across Illinois, Indiana and southern Lower Michigan into
western Ohio. Widespread snow was forecast from the Montana Rockies
through the northern Plains into the upper Mississippi Valley.
   Highs in the 20s were predicted from northwestern Montana through
North Dakota and northern Minnesota into northwestern Wisconsin; in
the 30s and 40s from the northern Rockies and the central
Intermountain areas through the middle Missouri Valley and much of
the Great Lakes region into New England; in the 70s from the
southern California valleys through central parts of Arizona and New
Mexico, much of Oklahoma, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys into South
Carolina; in the 80s from the desert Southwest across the southern
Rockies, much of Texas, the lower Mississippi Valley and Gulf Coast
region into Florida; in the 90s across the middle Rio Grande Valley
of Texas; and in the 50s or 60s across much of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
