<FIRST>r a AM-DogEaters 1stLd-Writethru a0619 03-13 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dog Eaters, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0619,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Cambodian Refugees On Trial After Killing Dog For Food</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes grammar in 4th graf, `Chea and ...,' and restores dropped
word in 6th graf, `The defense said...' Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys defending two Cambodian
immigrants who killed a German shepherd puppy for food say the two
are innocent because the animal was killed humanely.
   Sokheng Chea, 32, and Seng Ou, 33, both of Long Beach,
acknowledged they killed the 4-month-old puppy late last June. They
hit it over the head with a blunt object, slashed its throat and
began skinning it.
   But police, alerted by a neighbor who heard the dog's yelps,
arrived and arrested the men.
   Chea and Ou went on trial last week in Municipal Court for
misdemeanor cruelty to animal charges, which carry a maximum penalty
of one year in jail and a $2,000 fine.
   The trial is being watched by both Asian community leaders and
animal rights groups.
   The defense says the dog was killed humanely in a way consistent
with contemporary slaughterhouses, while the prosecution says the
killing was a crime because it was done in an unnecessarily cruel
way.
   ``If the dog had been some other kind of animal _ like a chicken
or a duck or a pig _ these people wouldn't be in court,'' said Joe
Beason, an attorney representing Chea. ``While Americans consider it
completely acceptable to go out and shoot a deer, those same hunters
would disapprove of killing a dog for food.''
   But prosecutor Sarah Lazarus said, ``We intend to prove that this
was cruelty. It's cultural to the extent that each segment of our
society has its own cultural customs, but some of those customs can
be woven into the fabric of our society and others cannot.''
   Judge Bradford L. Andrews ruled last week that killing a dog for
food is not in itself illegal, and the prosecution must prove the
dog was ``maimed, wounded, tortured, mutilated or tormented'' in a
manner beyond that required to prepare it as food.
   Chea and Ou have refused comment until the case is over.
   Local Asian leaders said dogs and cats are considered delicacies
in some Southeast Asian countries, and fear publicity from the case
may result in intensified anti-Asian bias. At least one death threat
has been received by the defendants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
