<FIRST>u w AM-ContraAid 2ndld-writethru a0735 03-13 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contra Aid, 2nd ld-writethru, a0735,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Will Be Asked for More Than $50 Million for Contras</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: To update with New York Times report, adds 2 grafs after 11th
graf previous, ``he did''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is expected to ask
Congress for more than $50 million in additional humanitarian aid
for the Nicaraguan Contras to ensure their survival until early next
year, U.S. officials said Monday.
   The existing $27 million program, which provides for food,
clothing, shelter and medical services, expires at the end of the
month. The request is likely to be sent to Capitol Hill before the
lawmakers begin a two-week spring recess this weekend.
   Later, Contra leader Adolfo Calero told reporters after a meeting
at the State Department he was informed that the administration
request would be ``40 some odd million dollars.''
   As described by officials speaking on condition of anonymity, the
request is part of a broad array of activities by the new
administration designed primarily to achieve a democratic outcome in
Nicaragua through a bipartisan approach by the administration and
the Congress.
   If the Sandinista government shows a willingness to establish
western-style democracy, the administration is prepared to move
toward more normal trade and diplomatic relations with Nicaragua.
   Alternatively, the administration has prepared a list of
potential punitive measures if the Sandinistas do not allow a
democratic system to take root.
   More than 10,000 Contras are assembled in Honduras at camps near
the Nicaraguan border.
   Some members of Congress are prepared to try to link any new aid
program for the Contras to their resettlement in Nicaragua or in
third countries. This would be consistent with the wishes of the
five Central American presidents, who last month called fo the
drawing up of a plan within 90 days for the demobilization of the
rebels.
   In return, Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega promised to move up
national elections from November 1990 to February 1990. The
administration wants the Contras to remain intact until after
elections as an incentive for the Sandinista government to ensure
opposition forces are treated fairly during the electoral process.
   U.S. officials who asked not to be identified said they are
worried that the Hondurans may be too eager for the demobilization
of the Contras. To underscore the administration's concern, Robert
Kimmitt, the State Department's third-ranking official, was in
Tegucigalpa on Monday to explain the U.S. position to Honduran
leaders.
   He did not plan to visit other Central American countries. But
the special U.S. envoy for Central America, Morris Busby, was in the
region last week sounding out the presidents of the four countries
friendly to the United States _ El Salvador, Guatemala, Costa Rica
and Honduras.
   The United States asked Honduras on Monday to let the Contras
remain in Honduras for another year, the New York Times reported.
   The appeal was made by Kimmitt, the new undersecretary of state
for political affairs, during a meeting in Honduras with President
Jose Azcona Hoyo, the newspaper reported in its Tuesday editions.
   Alluding to the stepped-up pace of Central American diplomacy,
State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Monday, ``It's a very
intensive and fast-paced process that's going on.''
   Meanwhile, the fate of the Contras was the subject of a meeting
Monday in Washington between Honduran diplomats and Contra
representatives.
   A Honduran statement issued after the meeting said the meeting
was part of a process of consultations with all parties on how to
achieve both democracy in Nicaragua and the ``reintegration of the
Nicaraguan resistance into Nicaraguan society.''
   On Tuesday, United Nations officials will hold further
discussions on the creation of an international force with a mandate
to report on violations of border security in Central America.
   West Germany, Canada and Spain have agreed to provide military
personnel to the force.
</TEXT>
