<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0903EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-ChildWarriors Adv20   03-13 0908</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Warriors, Adv 20,0932</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs March 20 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Palestinian Children at Forefront of Clashes with Israeli</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMOUN, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whenever 7-year-old Seif Hashim
spots Israeli troops approaching this West Bank village, he grabs a
rock, pulls a checkered Arab keffiyeh over his face and runs into
the street shouting, ``The army's coming!''
   Seif and his grade school friends belong to the ``Palestinian
cubs,'' a group linked to the Palestine Liberation Organization.
They set up barricades and throw stones at soldiers in the narrow
alleyways of this village 66 miles north of Jerusalem.
   ``My job is to get the soldiers if they come into the village,''
explained Seif, his big blue eyes flashing. ``There are about 45
kids in my gang. Some are older than me _ they're 8.''
   Leaning back in his chair, Seif added in a high-pitched voice
that he supported Nayef Hawatmeh's pro-Communist Democratic Front
for the Liberation of Palestine.
   ``I want to be a PLO guerrilla when I grow up,'' he said. ``Or a
dentist.'' Increasingly, Palestinian children _ some as young as 5
and 6 _ are at the forefront of violent clashes with troops in the
occupied territories. Sixty-one children 16 and younger have been
killed out of a total of about 390 since the start of the 15-month
uprising. Casualties among youngsters are on the increase, according
to United Nations figures.
   One reason for the involvement of increasingly younger children
is that many of the older youths who spearheaded protests are in
jail or in hiding from the Israeli security forces.
   The phenomenon has prompted charges from Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin that Palestinians are putting children in the front lines of
confrontations to win international sympathy and portray Israeli
troops as ruthless.
   ``This is the major problem Israel faces ... Palestinian
protesters surrounding themselves with kids and women at the
front,'' Rabin told visiting U.S. Jewish leaders recently.
   He said clashes with stone-throwers make up 90 percent of the
violent incidents in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. ``And 60 percent
of these involve children from the age of 6 to 14 or 15,'' Rabin
said.
   Children have participated alongside adults and older youths in
protests since the start of the Palestinian revolt. But increasingly
children _ some as young as 5 _ are taking on Israeli troops alone.
   ``The soldiers are now facing situations where the only targets
are young kids,'' said an international relief worker who declined
to be identified. ``That has changed the equation of the conflict.''
   According to U.N. figures, in the first six months of the
uprising that began in December 1987, 65 children 15 or under were
shot in the occupied Gaza Strip. By the second six months, the
number of young shooting victims had increased nearly five-fold to
307. Of the total, 21 died of their wounds in Gaza.
   In January, 61 of the 129 shooting casualties in Gaza were 15 and
under, according to the Arab-run Human Rights Information Center in
east Jerusalem. Three of the children died of their wounds.
   The center's Jan Abu Shakr estimated that hundreds of under-16
youths had been detained during the uprising but said fewer than 100
were currently held. Israeli army spokesmen stressed no one under 12
could be jailed.
   In Tamoun, Seif and about 400 boys 5 to 12 years old belong to
the cubs, which has no relation to non-violent scout groups. Each
week the children participate in anti-occupation marches,
broadcasting nationalist slogans through megaphones and carrying
outlawed Palestinian flags and pictures of PLO Chairman Yasser
Arafat through village streets.
   Children are organized by uprising leaders well aware of the
propaganda value provided by children facing heavily armed soldiers.
   ``We are teaching these kids to be active resisters,'' said
Shehad Gharaybeh, 30, a youth organizer. ``The personality of the
child is formed in the early years. These children will be stronger
than us. They are the PLO's plan for continuing the struggle.''
   ``Also, punishing children is a sensitive issue for the Israeli
army. We know that and it is something we use,'' he added.
   Two boys, 9 and 16, have been killed in Tamoun in the uprising
that began in December 1987, and 13 children have been wounded. The
youngest shooting victim was Ziad Omar Sharat, 7, a member of Seif's
cubs group, who was wounded in the arm in November.
   ``The marches are nice, but I prefer clashing with soldiers,''
said Riad Omar Mohammed Sharat, 13, brother of Ziad. ``I'm not
afraid of soldiers. They have weapons, and we have weapons. Our
weapons are firebombs and stones.''
   Shafiq Masalha, a clinical psychologist at Bir Zeit University in
the West Bank, said the children were not fully aware of the dangers
they faced.
   ``These children cannot really imagine themselves being injured
or killed,'' he said in an interview. ``They don't calculate the
risk in advance. They don't really understand the risks.''
   Seif disagrees. He said he knows what a martyr is:
   ``Being a martyr means that I was attacking the army with stones
and I was hit by a bullet. My family could not get me to the
hospital in time because the army blocked the road. So I died on the
road. Then the other boys had a march in the village for me. That's
a martyr.
   ``Afterward, you go to paradise.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs March 20</NOTE>
