<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 0854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-WalterMears Adv14   03-13 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, Adv 14,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Mar 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson, Democratic Leadership Council Disagree on Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson was not among allies _ anything
but. So when they lectured him on political science, he lectured
right back.
   In the resulting standoff, the edge belonged to Jackson, the
twice and future candidate for the White House.
   ``The issue is not just who leads us but who needs us,'' the
black leader from Chicago told establishment Democrats, who know
well that they badly need him to stand a chance regaining the
presidency in 1992.
   It was all quite polite, but the lines were clear at the
Democratic Leadership Council conference this past weekend. Centrist
and conservative Democrats organized the council four years ago,
after the landslide defeat of Walter F. Mondale's ticket, in an
effort to turn the party toward what they consider the voter
mainstream.
   Jackson does not accept their map of the mainstream.
   He suggested there was more to be learned about the next
presidential election on the Eastern Airlines picket lines than in a
seminar at a Philadelphia hotel.
   Jackson told the council that white airline pilots who make
$140,000 a year are on his side now because he went to their sides.
``I am one of the few people around this table who has a net gain in
white supporters,'' he told the conference of Democratic workers and
officeholders. ``I understand how to get white votes.''
   Jackson and the Democratic Leadership Council stand on opposite
sides in the argument over a route back from five defeats in the
past six presidential elections.
   After a campaign in which Republicans made the word ``liberal''
into a political curse, most of the Democrats at the Philadelphia
conference want a change in the message and a move toward the
middle. Jackson insists that the party can win by mobilizing its own
constituency and sticking to its own message.
   The council called in a political science professor for advice
and he said the problem is with swing voters, not with turnout.
William A. Galston of the University of Maryland said if everyone
eligible had voted in 1988, President Bush would have been elected
by an even wider margin.
   ``Democratic support is hemorrhaging in the heart of the
electorate,'' said Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia. Sen. Charles S. Robb of
Virginia said Democrats have to win back the middle class, and can't
afford the ``us against them'' perception he said has taken hold.
   Galston said that to have a chance, the 1992 nominee ``must be
fully credible as commander in chief,'' must respond to the majority
of voters who favor the death penalty and a generally tougher stance
on crime, and must reassure the middle class.
   Jackson listened politely, but if there had been an exam on the
Galston lecture, he would have flunked.
   He offered his summation outside the conference room: ``If we are
all things to all people, we become rather ill-defined, indecisive,
kind of like warm spit.''
   At least Jackson was there, listening and talking to Democrats
who know that his power will remain their problem. He ran first in
13 states and second in 33 in contests for Democratic delegates in
1988, and he shows no signs of slowing.
   Nunn said that despite their differences, ``I also acknowledge
him to be one of the people in the country who has the largest
following ... and the people who support him are an extremely
important element in the Democratic Party.''
   Important enough that none of the establishment Democrats picked
a real fight over Jackson's stance back home in Chicago, where he is
supporting a third-party black candidate against Richard M. Daley,
the Democratic nominee for mayor.
   Robb did mention it, saying Jackson's refusal to support the
primary winner could be a problem for him in 1992. Jackson insists
that the presidential primary elections and party caucuses should
choose Democratic presidential nominees, without intervention by
party leaders.
   ``Let the primary process determine the winner'' in 1992, Jackson
said in Philadelphia.
   But in discussing the Chicago race, Jackson said he had supported
Daley twice in other elections, and ``he's not endorsed me once.''
   ``You should support people who support you,'' Jackson said,
noting that some of those who criticize him now have refused to
support black nominees in the past. ``What is sacred are
relationships, honorable, reciprocal relationships. What is sacred
is not the primary.''
   That's a line that may be replayed when presidential primaries
are again the issue.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Sajak Adv14   03-13 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Sajak, Adv 14,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, March 14, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pat Sajak Says He Goes by `Smile Test' Instead of Ratings</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA11 of March 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Sajak says he judges the success of his
new late-night talk show not by the ratings but by the happy faces
of CBS big shots.
   ``You can drive yourself crazy looking at the ratings numbers
every day and comparing yourself to everyone else,'' said Sajak. ``I
mainly go by the CBS executives. If they smile and stay out of our
way, I know things are going well.''
   CBS executives have a lot to smile about. ``The Pat Sajak Show''
made its debut Jan. 9, and things are going very well.
   Sajak, of course, is not giving Johnny Carson of NBC's ``Tonight
Show'' anything to worry about and probably never will. But that's
not the point, and never was. The biggest fallacy about late-night
programming is the assumption that you're failing miserably if
you're not beating Carson, or at least breathing down his neck.
   The bugbear Sajak had to overcome was previous late-night
programming on CBS, a hodgepodge of original shows, reruns and
movies. Not only were CBS ratings trailing far behind Carson and
ABC's ``Nightline,'' but many affiliate stations were also dumping
the shows to run their own.
   The rating for the CBS late-night shows in December was 3.3,
while Carson had 5.5 and ``Nightline'' 4.9. In its debut week, Sajak
outdistanced all the competition. Part of that was due to curiosity.
   After two months, Sajak's ratings have leveled off and the show
now runs behind Carson by at least two ratings points. In the last
ratings week, Carson had a rating of 5.7, ``Nightline'' 5.3 and
Sajak 3.4. In the February sweeps, Carson got a 5.6 rating, Sajak
3.5.
   The good news is that the ratings are ahead of the previous
late-night programming.
   ``I feel very good about where we are now,'' Sajak said in a
telephone interview. ``I don't want to sound self-satisfied or smug,
but I like the look of the show. We're going through an evolutionary
process. We don't have meetings and say let's change this or that.
But a year down the road we can look at our shows and say they're
different.
   ``As for the ratings, I really don't keep up with them. They go
up, they go down. After the first few weeks to make sure people were
watching, I stopped checking. We're just out to improve what CBS had
in this time slot before. We're starting a talk show from scratch.
We're not taking viewers away from Johnny Carson, but we are
attracting people who previously haven't been watching network
late-night shows.''
   Meanwhile, Carson renewed his contract with NBC for another year.
``I'm having a ball,'' Carson told NBC Entertainment President
Brandon Tartikoff. It will be Carson's 28th year as host of ``The
Tonight Show.''
   Sajak said he is not trying to break new ground. ``I've said many
times we're out to do a strong, traditional talk show,'' he said.
``I don't think there's anything we should be doing that we're not
doing. We've tried some things that haven't worked, like asking
people in the audience about their worst date. But our out-of-studio
stuff has worked great.''
   The Sajak show is seen on 195 stations. Some defecting CBS
stations have returned to the fold, but a few, like Detroit and
Atlanta, do not carry the show. In those cities, the Sajak show is
broadcast by independent stations. Sajak has 95 percent of the CBS
stations, while Carson has 99 percent of the NBC stations.
   Sajak still goes to NBC on weekends to tape ``Wheel of Fortune,''
but he said he has not run into Carson. Both Carson and David
Letterman, whose NBC late-night show is against the last half-hour
of ``The Pat Sajak Show,'' wished Sajak well when he launched his
show.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   LAUGH METER: The nomination ballots are out for ``The Third
Annual Comedy Awards,'' to be shown on ABC on Tuesday, May 23. All
comedy performers who worked during the 1988 calendar year are
eligible. The show was created by producer George Schlatter to honor
comic performers.
   FEMME FATALE RETURNS: Ana-Alicia, who starred on CBS' ``Falcon
Crest'' for eight years, is returning for the 200th episode on March
31. She had been Melissa Agretti, who died at the beginning of the
current season. She will return as Samantha Ross, a dead ringer for
Melissa.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, March 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
