<FIRST>s i BC-Guinea-Bissau-Women Adv19   03-13 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Guinea-Bissau-Women, Adv 19,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Women's Economic Project is One of Guinea-Bissau's Successes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Guinea-Bissau Now, b0684</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   BISSAU, Guinea-Bissau (AP) _ Women are responsible for one
Guinea-Bissau's economic successes.
   With help from the United Nations Development Program, more than
1,400 women work about 123,000 acres of land on the outskirts of
Bissau, growing tomatoes, lettuce and other vegetables that
supplement their families' basic rice diet and provide extra income
when sold in the market.
   ``The problem is that it works too well and they actually produce
too much,'' said Ursula King, who has worked as a U.N. development
officer for Guinea-Bissau, Mali and Sierra Leone. ``What they need
is food processing to preserve the stuff and get some value added.''
   ``Small-scale industries are the way to go,'' said Rosemary
Galli, co-author of ``Guinea-Bissau: Politics, Economics and
Society.''
   ``They give people jobs and promote trade between villages
instead of just with the city of Bissau or Senegal.''
</TEXT>
