<FIRST>u f PM-RJRNabisco-CEO     03-13 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-RJR Nabisco-CEO,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Express President Named CEO At RJR Nabisco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. today named American Express
Co.'s president, Louis V. Gerstner Jr., as chairman and chief
executive officer of the cigarette and food giant.
   Gerstner, 47, succeeds F. Ross Johnson, who left the company
following RJR's acquisition earlier this year by buyout specialist
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. for a record $25 billion.
   Johnson, who resigned on Feb. 9, had led a competing takeover bid.
   Gerstner's appointment follows reports that RJR had been courting
baseball commissioner Peter Ueberroth and Kraft Inc. President
Michael Miles for the job.
   Although Gerstner lacks experience in manufacturing, executives
familiar with his 11-year tenure at New York-based American Express
said his strong management skills made him a good choice to run RJR
through its current transition.
   ``Lou's new job is one of the most challenging in the corporate
world, and I believe he is uniquely qualified for it,'' said
American Express Chairman James D. Robinson III.
   KKR founding partner Henry R. Kravis cited Gerstner's
``distinguished record of leadership at an organization of
comparable size and quality to RJR Nabisco.''
   Gerstner joined American Express in 1978 as president of the
American Express Card Division, and the next year was named
president of the Travel Related Services Group, responsible for
American Express cards, travelers checks and travel service offices.
   When Travel Related Services became a subsidiary of the company
in 1982, Gerstner became its first chairman and chief executive
officer. He became president of the parent company in 1985.
   During Gerstner's career at American Express, the company's card
membership rose from 8.6 million to 30.7 million, and the company
introduced its popular Platinum and Optima American Express cards.
   Gerstner said he was ``delighted to take the helm of a company
with such a rich history as RJR Nabisco.'' He promised to ``work to
further improve the company, grow it, and make it a creative and
exciting place to work.''
   Among RJR Nabisco's operating companies are R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco, Nabisco Brands, Del Monte Foods and Planters LifeSavers.
   Robinson said he will assume the additional duties of president
after Gerstner's departure.
   American Express also announced that Aldo Papone, president and
chief operating officer of Travel Related Services will replace
Gerstner as chief executive officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
