<FIRST>r f PM-Trustcorp     03-13 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trustcorp,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trustcorp Takes $35.9 Loss On Downtown Investments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trustcorp Inc., citing losses on downtown
Toledo projects and other real-estate ventures, announced today that
it would write-off $35.9 million.
   It was the second time in less than three months that the bank
holding company has had to write-off riverfront investments. In
January, the corporation said it would write-off $40.7 million in
connection with loans it had made toward redevelopment in downtown
Toledo.
   A statement released today by the company said the new charges
are ``centered principally in commercial real-estate loans in Toledo
and elsewhere.''
   ``The corporation's financial position remains strong and the
long-term prospects are solid'' despite the charge-offs for bad
loans and loan-loss reserves, said George Haigh, chairman of the $6
billion bank holding company.
   The company did not specify which loans in its portfolio would be
written down or written off.
   The company also said it has rescheduled its annual shareholders'
meeting for June 28. The meeting had been scheduled for April 13,
but was postponed because of a management shake-up last month.
   Several telephone messages left for Katherine Rotte, Trustcorp's
vice president of corporate public affairs, were not returned today.
   In late February, Trustcorp announced a reorganization of its
management because of soured downtown investments. Five officals
retired or were fired in the management shake-up.
   Before the management changes, Trustcorp had announced that it
had formed a committee of outside directors to review the adequacy
of its loan-loss reserves, chargeoffs, and commercial real estate
practices.
   The committee was formed in conjunction with a similar review
being conducted by a federal regulatory agency.
   Banking analysts have said that Trustcorp loaned too much money
to downtown redevelopment projects and did not maintain proper
reserves to cover losses on failing ventures.
   Some analysts also have said that Trustcorp is ripe for a
takeover because of the management changes and bad investments.
   Trustcorp Inc. has offices in Ohio, Michigan, Indiana and Florida.
</TEXT>
