<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has agreed to ban
financier Michael Milken from ever working at the firm and forbid
other workers from talking business with him even if he's acquitted
of expected criminal charges, sources said.
   Sources familiar with the firm's plea-bargain settlement talks,
who spoke on condition they not be identified, said Friday the same
restrictions apply to Milken's brother Lowell, a senior Drexel aide
also expected to be indicted.
   Securities and Exchange Commission negotiatiors imposed the
restrictions in talks with Drexel aimed at resolving wide-ranging
civil fraud charges against the firm, the sources said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, in a policy shift one
week after riots in Venezuela, outlined a new plan to slash the
crushing Third World debt burden that threatens Latin American
democracies.
   The recipe for easing the debt crisis, outlined Friday, eases
away from the 1985 ``Baker Plan'' that had favored new lending
instead of debt forgiveness.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment dropped to a 15-year low of 5.1
percent in February as employers created 289,000 jobs, the
government said.
   Friday's report was seen as evidence of surprising, sustained
vigor in the economy.
   The jobless rate, stuck at 5.3 percent or 5.4 percent for five
months, fell 0.3 percentage point in February to 5.1 percent, its
lowest since May 1974. The last time the rate was lower was in
December 1973, when it hit 4.9 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Eastern Airlines Machinists said they
would file their own plan to rescue the carrier from bankruptcy and
they denounced management for threatening to split the union by
replacing unskilled members.
   Bolstered by crucial support on the picket lines they've received
from Eastern's pilots, the Machinists said Friday they'll continue
striking together in the face of what they call the company's
``divide-and-conquer'' strategy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Eastern Airlines Machinists said they
will mount a legal battle to get wages owed to striking union
members and repeated accusations that the crippled carrier timed its
bankruptcy filing to make sure workers went unpaid.
   Machinists who expected to be paid Thursday instead had their
final pre-strike paychecks withheld by Eastern as part of its
petition for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the
federal Bankruptcy Code.
   Robert Clayman, a Washington-based attorney for the Machinists,
said Friday he would file papers soon in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
Manhattan to ``correct the pay situation ``and make sure these
employees get paid as quickly as possible.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anxious to protect itself from potential
asbestos liability claims arising out of a past business, Raytech
Corp. filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
federal bankruptcy laws.
   Raytech, a multinational manufacturing holding company based in
Shelton, Conn., said Friday in a prepared statement that it was
forced to take its voluntary action in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
Bridgeport, Conn., because ``all other potential avenues for
resolution of the issue in the courts have proven to be ineffective
or impossible.''
   The bankruptcy action involves only the holding company and not
any of its manufacturing subsidiaries. Raytech makes specialty
engineered products for industrial, auto, aerospace and military
customers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raising taxes to solve the savings and loan
crisis could save taxpayers $138 billion over the next 30 years, a
congressman critical of federal regulators' handling of the crisis
said.
   Congress and Americans were misinformed about the costs of saving
the troubled thrift industry, said U.S. Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, who
also suggested Friday that top thrift regulators step aside after he
heard that the deficit of the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance
Corp. had quadrupled from $14 billion in 1987 to at least $56
billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two shareholders of BankAmerica Corp. have sued
company officers over a student-loan fiasco that could cost a group
of banks $450 million to $650 million.
   Greenfield &amp; Chimicles, a Haverford, Pa.-based law firm, said
Friday it was representing two shareholders in the suit, filed in
the Court of Chancery in Wilmington, Del.
   BankAmerica announced Wednesday it was boosting its first-quarter
reserves to cover its part in losses that resulted from an unusually
high default rate on student vocational loans for which it acted as
trustee.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community Commission urged the
United States to adopt the European production standard for
high-definition television, saying the European approach would be
better for consumers and the TV industry than a competing U.S.
proposal.
   The commission's Washington delegation sent a letter outlining
its approach and criteria for a single worldwide HDTV production
standard to the State and Commerce departments, it was disclosed
Friday.
</TEXT>
