<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose sharply today, continuing
its rebound from a surprise late last week in the government's
monthly employment report.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 27.68 points to
2,309.82 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 838 up, 378
down and 499 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 51.15 million shares at
midmorning.
   When the Labor Department reported Friday morning that the
unemployment rate had fallen to a 15-year low in February, stocks
and bonds initially sold off on the news.
   The reasoning was that strains on the capacity of the labor force
might intensify inflationary pressures and tend to push interest
rates higher.
   But stocks began a steady recovery Friday afternoon, finishing
the session with only a moderate loss.
   That apparently encouraged traders, and created a general belief
that the market was ready for a new assault on the 2,300 level,
where it bogged down on two occasions last week.
   Brokers said the market got a boost in that effort from program
traders engaged in multiple strategies involving stock-index futures
and individual stocks.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Philip Morris, up 2~ at
118]; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up ~ at 31]; General Electric,
up ] at 45], and International Business Machines, up 1[ at 119].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.42 to 166.27. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.24 at 330.16.
