<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices opened slightly
lower, and wheat slightly higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Corn and soybeans both closed lower Friday and analysts said the
markets were giving ground early in the absence of any fresh news.
   Wheat did better at last week's close following reports the
Soviet Union bid on 515,000 metric tons under the export enhancement
program, and is expected to complete the purchase today.
   And new-crop wheat got a boost from the hot, dry weather over the
weekend in the growing regions of Texas, Oklahoma and Kansas and a
forecast of not much more precipitation for this week.
   At the opening, wheat was { cent lower to { cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.36{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 1\ cents lower, with March at $2.75 a bushel; oats were } cents
lower to \ cent higher, with May at $2.11\ a bushel; and soybeans
were 1 cent lower to 3 cents higher, with March at $7.56 a bushel.
