<FIRST>r f PM-Pennwalt-Centaur     03-13 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pennwalt-Centaur,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Blocks Takeover Firm from Calling Stockholder Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centaur Partners has pledged to appeal a
judge's order blocking a special Pennwalt Corp. shareholders meeting
and says it is determined to take over the chemical company.
   A statement issued Sunday by the investment company also said the
group's $110-per-share tender offer, scheduled to expire March 20,
``remains in full force and effect.''
   On Friday, U.S. District Judge Robert S. Gawthrop III declared
Centaur demands for the special meeting invalid. Centaur had hoped
to use the meeting to replace the board of directors with takeover
proponents.
   Centaur had received enough signed demands from stockholders to
force the meeting late this month under state law.
   In invalidating Centaur's call for the special meeting, Gawthrop
cited a provision included in the group's solicitation to
shareholders.
   Centaur, which owns about 13 percent of Pennwalt's outstanding
shares, had said the call would be voided if a court decided the
shareholders were part of a ``controlling group'' of the company.
   Pennwalt opposed the demand for the meeting, arguing the
shareholders were part of a controlling group, as defined by the
state business code, and financially liable to any stockholders
unhappy with the Centaur offer.
   Gawthrop agreed with Pennwalt.
   ``No one is going to risk that,'' said Stuart H. Savett, one of
the attorneys representing shareholders in the case. ``If you are
part of the control group, you may be liable.''
   For Pennwalt, the court ruling was the first significant skirmish
it has won since Centaur made its first tender offer in December.
   In the statement Sunday, Centaur's principals, Abbey J. Butler
and Melvyn J. Estrin, called the ruling a temporary setback.
   Centaur began buying Pennwalt stock last spring. By December, the
investment group announced an offer of $100 a share for the almost 7
million outstanding shares Centaur did not own.
   In February, the group raised its bid by $10. On Friday the stock
closed on the New York Stock Exchange at $118.50, up 50 cents.
   Pennwalt has repeatedly refused to meet with Centaur and has said
it will explore other options that could include the sale of the
company or further restructuring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
