<DOCNO> AP890313-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BakerHughes-Sale     03-13 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker Hughes-Sale,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Hughes Announces Intent to Sell Mining Equipment Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baker Hughes Inc., the Houston-based oilfield
service company, today said it plans to sell its Mining Equipment
Group in what company officials described as a long-anticipated
restructuring move.
   The mining group, made up of six major and several minor
businesses, manufactures underground equipment for the mining
industry.
   For 1988, the group accounted for $227 million out of Baker
Hughes' $2.3 billion in revenue, the company said.
   ``We have been evaluating our position in that (mining) market
for some time,'' Baker Hughes spokesman Ronald G. Turner said today.
   ``When we segregated the businesses about eight to 10 months ago,
it was clearly with the intention of being better able to analyze
this segment,'' Turner said. ``And this was the conclusion based on
that analysis.''
   The mining group includes about 2,000 of Baker Hughes' 22,000
employees worldwide, he said.
   The First Boston Corp. was retained to assist in the divestiture,
and materials about the mining group were expected to be available
in about 30 days, Baker Hughes said.
</TEXT>
