<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-GeneralMills     03-13 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-General Mills,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Mills' Earnings Up 15 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN VALLEY, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Mills Inc. Monday said its
third-quarter income rose 15.3 percent and per-share profit grew to
a record amount.
   The company reported after-tax earnings of $82.3 million for the
quarter ended Feb. 26, up from $71.4 million a year earlier.
   On a per-share basis, earnings hit a record $1, compared with 83
cents a share during the same period a year earlier. The record
coincided with a decline in the number of outstanding shares from
86.5 million a year ago to 82.2 million shares, Chairman Bruce
Atwater said.
   Sales in the quarter grew 17 percent to $1.45 billion from $1.24
billion the year before.
   Atwater said the increases in the 13-week period ended Feb. 26
reflect strengths in Big G cereals and Red Lobster and The Olive
Garden restaurants. He said cereals have experienced a 19 percent
unit volume gain and 105 new restaurants have opened in the past 12
months.
   Restaurants led the company's third quarter operating performance
with gains in sales and operating profits of 33 percent and 63
percent, respectively, Atwater said.
   Established Red Lobster restaurants showed average unit sales
gains of 14 percent. In the previous quarter, 27 Seafood Broiler
units in Southern California were converted to Red Lobster
restaurants. The conversions cost about $200,000 a restaurant.
   The Olive Garden Italian restaurants opened 14 new units in the
third quarter, bringing the total to 131 in 21 states compared to 75
at the end of last year's third quarter.
   Consumer Foods third-quarter sales and operating profits grew 12
percent and 10 percent, respectively. Volume increased 7 percent in
the third quarter, with more than 80 percent of the gain coming from
established oat-based cereals such as Cheerios and new products,
Atwater said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
