<DOCNO> AP890313-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Coastal-TexasEastern     03-13 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coastal-Texas Eastern,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: This is a repeat for all needing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Coastal Corp. Extends Tender Offer for Texas Eastern Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Corp. officials said today they have again
extended a $2.6 billion offer for Texas Eastern Corp. outstanding
stock, the second extension since Texas Eastern agreed to be
acquired by rival suitor Panhandle Eastern Corp.
   The cash tender offer now will expire March 31, unless it is
further extended, Coastal said. The original expiration date was
Feb. 13.
   Also today, Panhandle Eastern said five co-manager banks have
committed to provide $2 billion in financing for its acquisition of
Texas Eastern. Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. already had agreed to
provide $500 million.
   The battle for Texas Eastern began Jan. 16, when Coastal
announced its surprise takeover bid. But the Texas Eastern board
rejected the offer as too low, signing the merger agreement with
Panhandle Eastern on Feb. 21.
   Panhandle Eastern's $3.2 billion offer includes provisions to buy
up to 80 percent of Texas Eastern's 60.8 million outstanding shares
and a stock exchange at the same $53-a-share value for the remaining
shares.
   The combination of the two Houston-based natural gas companies
would create a 27,000-mile system and result in the nation's
second-largest pipeline company in terms of miles, officials said.
   Coastal spokesman R.W. Wells said Monday that despite the
apparent finality of the Panhandle Eastern deal, Coastal remains
poised for a takeover with its $42-a-share offer.
   ``You've heard the old expression, `There's many a slip between
cup and mouth.' We're just keeping it alive in case something
happens,'' Wells said.
   Separately, Panhandle Eastern said it met last week in Houston
with about 60 financial institutions, including Manufacturers
Hanover and the five co-managing banks: Bank of America National
Trust and Savings Association, Chase Manhatten Bank, Chemical Bank,
Continental Bank N.A. and Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. of New York.
   The combined $2.5 billion commitment amounts to 68 percent of the
bank financing needed for the acquisition, Panhandle Eastern said.
</TEXT>
