<SECOND>BC-Britain Stocks, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0002,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End At Post-Crash Peak Ahead Of British Budget</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange jumped
sharply Monday, closing at a new post-crash peak in a burst of
enthusiasm before Tuesday's fiscal 1990 budget speech by Chancellor
of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson.
   Trading activity was light, however, as institutional players
remained sidelined in the runup to the budget speech, one of
Britain's major economic events of the year.
   Equities were primarily driven higher as Wall Street rose
strongly in early business.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 17.8 points, or 0.9 percent, at 2,103.0, its best level for
the day and its best post-crash close since reaching 2,096.2 on Feb.
8.
   At its lowest level Monday, the index was down 4 points at the
opening.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 14.5 points at 1,739.4
at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 10.61 points
to close at 1,201.05.
   Volume was light, however, as 496 million shares changed hands,
down sharply from Friday's 655 million shares.
