<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     03-13 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Up Slightly, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar drifted higher in uninspired
European trading Monday as dealers awaited some key economic data
from Britain and the United States.
   Gold prices fell.
   ``There was no enthusiasm in the market at all,'' said Martin
Ely, a chief foreign exchange dealer at Midland Bank. ``People do
wish to buy dollars, but they are also worried about central-bank
intervention at higher levels.''
   Another dealer said, ``People are squaring their positions ahead
of the figures due out later this week.''
   On Tuesday, British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson is
scheduled to present the spring federal budget to Parliament, and
the U.S. Commerce Department reports the fourth-quarter current
account trade balance.
   Dealers said they were heading into the week in a fairly bullish
mood. They said the dollar has been driven by technical factors over
the past few weeks, and that the technical factors continue to point
toward a higher dollar.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7125 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7159 dollars Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday:
1.8669 West German marks, up from 1.8629; 1.5965 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5918; 6.3230 French francs, up from 6.3185; 2.1040 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1020; 1,367.40 Italian lire, up from 1,366.00;
and 1.1981 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1987.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.69 yen to a closing 129.57 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 129.86 yen.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $392.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $393.25. In Zurich, gold fell to a
closing bid of $392.75 an ounce, compared with $393.50 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 30 cents to close at a bid
$394.85 an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London to a late bid price of $6.02
a troy ounce from $6.00 Friday.
</TEXT>
