<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SearsShifts     03-13 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sears Shifts,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears Cutting Back on In-Store Outlets for Financial Services, Real
Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. will significantly reduce
the in-store presence of both its financial services and real estate
operations, but expand its insurance outlets, a spokesman said today.
   The number of Dean Witter Reynolds financial service outlets in
Sears, Roebuck stores will be reduced by half _ from about 300 to
about 150 _ and virtually all the Coldwell Banker real estate
offices in about 220 stores will be converted into marketing and
referral booths, said Sears spokesman Doug Fairweather.
   Operations at the company's 824 in-store Allstate Insurance
offices will be bolstered, however, he said.
   Sears, the nation's largest retailer, recently underwent a round
of cost-cutting and adopted a low pricing policy in an effort to
regain market share. Fairweather said there would be few savings in
this latest move.
   ``The way in which we cover these markets has simply changed,''
he said.
   ``We've already experienced a very, very sharp growth since
getting both Dean Witter and Coldwell Banker at the end of 1981. Now
that they're on the map, it makes more sense to emphasize the local
offices as the places to do business and use the store space just
for referrals.''
   Dean Witter has expanded to a total of 650 outlets from just 350
when Sears first acquired it, and the number of account executives
has grown to 8,000 from 4,800. Coldwell Banker has increased from
about 413 offices in 73 residential markets to nearly 2,100 in 298
markets.
   ``In financial services, you do most of your business on the
phone. And most people go to a neighborhood office when they're
looking to buy a house,'' Fairbanks said.
   ``Insurance seems to be the one business where both the timing
and paperwork factors still make an in-store outlet an efficient
service,'' he said.
   Fairweather said there would be a ``minimal'' effect on both
personnel and Sears' bottom line as a result of the changes.
   ``Most of the people who staffed the in-store offices came one
day or so each week from a local office anyway,'' he said. ``Now,
they'll just be spending more time at the other office.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
