<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-13 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0213</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts said technical factors _ decisions to buy or sell based
on price-chart relationships _ led to an upswing in the soybean pits
that spilled over into the grains.
   Most of the technical buying Monday was in the May contract,
which has traded in a range of between $7.60 and $7.80 a bushel in
recent sessions. It settled 13 cents higher, closing at $7.82 a
bushel.
   ``I wouldn't make much out of it,'' said one trader. ``We closed
in the $7.80 range plenty of times and haven't gone beyond.''
   Wheat did get some news, and a boost from the hot, dry weather
that swept the growing regions of Texas, Oklahoma and Kansas over
the weekend.
   On the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 4 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.37{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 1 cent higher, with March at $2.76 a bushel; oats were 1{ cents
to 2} cents higher, with March at at $2.09 a bushel; and soybeans
were 4 cents to 7{ cents higher, with March at $7.61 a bushel.
