<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AutoRecall     03-13 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Recall,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Recalls Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. on Monday recalled more
than a half million 1984 and 1985 Escort, EXP and Lynx automobiles
to check for emission control problems.
   The nation's No. 2 automaker also announced Monday it was
recalling about 57,000 1988 Mercury Tracers to check for worn spark
plug wires or faded bumper covers.
   The company said the cars involved in the emissions recall were
equipped with 1.6-liter engines. Dealerships will make mechanical
changes to vehicles which fail to meet emission standards.
   Cars made for sale in Canada and California aren't subject to the
recall, Ford said.
   Tracers sold in the United States and Canada were recalled to
check for a worn spark plug wire, which can cause poor starting,
engine misfiring, substandard performance and poor fuel economy.
Worn wires will be replaced.
   About 28,200 of the Tracers also will be checked for bumper
covers which have faded from exposure to ultraviolet light. Faded
covers will be replaced with covers with light stabilizers.
   Vehicles owners in each of the recalls will be notified by mail
and repairs will be performed at no cost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
