<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted higher Monday against most key
currencies in quiet worldwide trading as dealers awaited the release
of key economic data.
   Gold prices were mostly lower. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a bid of $393.00 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EST,
down 50 cents from Friday's late bid.
   Daniel Holland, a vice president at Discount Corp., said internal
market influences were largely responsible for the dollar's advance
but that most dealers were keeping a low profile until economic
reports from the United States, Britain and Japan were released
Tuesday.
   ``The market is a little cautious,'' he said.
   British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson will present the
spring federal budget to Parliament, the U.S. Commerce Department
reports the fourth-quarter current account trade balance and Japan
releases its latest report on wholesale prices.
   Dealers said sentiment toward the dollar remained fairly bullish,
although worries of possible central-bank intervention kept trading
in a fairly narrow range.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.69 yen to 129.57 yen. It was quoted at 129.86 yen
in London, and later in New York it stood at 130.175 yen, up from
129.40 Friday.
   The dollar gained against the British pound. It cost $1.7125 to
buy one pound in London, cheaper than $1.7159 Friday. In New York,
sterling fetched $1.71295, down from $1.7177.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late Friday
included: 1.8675 West German marks, up from 1.86175; 1.5970 Swiss
francs, up from 1.58975; 1.19815 Canadian dollars, down from
1.19865; 6.32625 French francs, up from 6.3140; and 1,369.25 Italian
lire, up from 1,366.75.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Friday: 1.8669 West
German marks, up from 1.8629; 1.5965 Swiss francs, up from 1.5918;
6.3230 French francs, up from 6.3185; 2.1040 Dutch guilders, up from
2.1020; 1.1981 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1987; and 1,367.40
Italian lire, up from 1,366.00.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $394.40 a troy ounce, up from Friday's $394.30.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $392.25 an ounce,
compared with late Friday's $393.25. In Zurich, gold fell to a
closing bid of $392.75 an ounce, compared with $393.50 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold fell 30 cents to close at a bid $394.85
an ounce. Silver prices gained. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $6.078 a troy ounce, up from $6.068
Friday. Silver rose in London to a late bid price of $6.02 a troy
ounce, up 2 cents from Friday.
