<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied Monday, rebounding from
the jolt of an unexpectedly strong employment report late last week.
   Trading remained relatively quiet, however.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 24.11 points to a
three-week high of 2,306.25.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 3 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
878 up, 574 down and 508 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 140.40 million
shares, against 146.83 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 165.84 million shares.
   When the Labor Department reported Friday morning that the
unemployment rate had fallen to a 15-year low in February, stocks
and bonds initially sold off on the news.
   The reasoning was that strains on the capacity of the labor force
might intensify inflationary pressures and tend to push interest
rates higher.
   But stocks began a steady recovery Friday afternoon, finishing
the session with only a moderate loss.
   That apparently encouraged traders, and created a general belief
that the market was ready for a new assault on the 2,300 level in
the Dow Jones industrial average, where it bogged down on two
occasions last week.
   Brokers said the market got a boost in that effort from program
traders engaged in multiple strategies involving stock-index futures
and individual stocks.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Philip Morris, up 3\ at
118}; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up 1[ at 31|; General
Electric, up | at 45|; Exxon, up ] at 44~ and International Business
Machines, up | at 118~.
   Shaklee jumped 9\ to 47]. The company agreed to be acquired by
Yamanouchi Pharmaceutical Co. for $28 a share after the payment of a
$20 dividend to Shaklee holders scheduled for next week.
   Shaklee shares trading on when-issued basis without the dividend
rose 8~ to 27{.
   DWG Corp., the most active issue on the American Stock Exchange,
gained 3[ to 10~, while Fishbach Corp., a NYSE stock, fell 1| to 15[.
   A group led by investor Andrew Heine made a $22-a-share takeover
offer for DWG and dropped a previous $25-a-share bid for Fishbach.
   Duriron fell 1 to 22\ in the over-the-counter market. The company
projected higher profits in 1989 but said it doesn't expect growth
to match its 143 percent rise last year.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $18.78 billion, or 0.65
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
1.15 to 166.00.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 3.04 to 341.21, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up 2.44 at 295.32.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market gained
.67 to 406.57. At the Amex, the market value index closed at 330.54,
up 1.62.
