<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Shuttle     03-13 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Shuttle,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bargain Fliers Took Risks Along With Carrier, Observers Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fliers who took advantage of Eastern Airlines' $12
shuttle fare this weekend took risks along with the strike-torn
airline, industry analysts said Monday.
   The slashed fare lured more passengers than Eastern had bargained
for, stranding hundreds of people in airports in New York, Boston
and Washington.
   But, analysts noted, all bargains include risks. And for Eastern
owner Frank Lorenzo, this one was better than the spectre of flying
his airline with empty seats.
   ``Eastern had to get the consumer back. Even though it did
inconvenience people, it was worth it,'' said Paul Karos, airline
analyst at First Boston Corp. in New York.
   Although one-way fares went up to $49 this week starting Monday,
Eastern said it would honor through Friday the $12 tickets sold over
the weekend. After Friday, prices will return to the normal $69 on
weekends, and $99 on weekdays and Sunday evening.
   The cut-rate weekend fare in effect Friday through Sunday was
intended to show the airline is still in business despite the 10-day
old walkout by Eastern Machinists and the sympathy of most pilots.
While it drew 31,500 passengers, many were as surprised as Eastern
when it ran out of seats to take the bargain hunters home.
   An estimated 550 people were unexpectedly grounded Sunday in the
three cities linked by the shuttle.
   Created by Eastern in 1961, the shuttle normally offers hourly
service between Boston, New York and Washington. Pan Am Corp., which
runs a rival shuttle between the three cities, did not match
Eastern's special fare.
   Seats can't be reserved on either the Eastern or Pan Am shuttle,
but they are normally guaranteed, even if it means wheeling out
another plane.
   But with last weekend's unusual deal, Eastern warned in advance
that there would be no backup flights, although the crush forced the
airline to bring out its biggest jets and five backup flights.
Anyone unable to return on the weekend was allowed to fly home free
through Wednesday as long as they took an Eastern flight between 10
a.m. and 3 p.m. EST.
   The gimmick went down well with some industry observers.
   ``They wanted to provoke a public reaction and they did, they
just didn't think deeply about it,'' said Mark Daugherty, airline
analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New York.
   ``Buyer beware whenever there is a good deal; the buyer has to
assume a certain amount of risk,'' he said.
   Flying full planeloads on Eastern's shuttle also helps keep up
appearances for real estate developer Donald Trump, Daugherty
suggested.
   Trump agreed in October to buy the Eastern shuttle and is
awaiting clearance for the $365 million deal from a bankruptcy judge
since Eastern filed for Chapter 11 protection from creditors last
Thursday.
   Bruce Nobles, president of Trump Shuttle Inc., liked the bargain
fare. ``It was a smart idea in this circumstance,'' Nobles said from
his New York office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1718EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SoftwareRetailing Bjt   03-13 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Software Retailing, Bjt,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Software Stores Aren't Just Appealing To Techies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you want to open a software store in the big
city, it helps to have a background in selling shoes. Or groceries.
Or clothing. Or arts and crafts, for that matter.
   Personal computers aren't just for techies anymore, and software
retailers have learned that if they want to sell to a mass market,
they have to adopt the marketing techniques that work for more
mundane products.
   Software Etc. is carrying that concept to new heights this week
with a hype-filled store opening on Manhattan's Fifth Avenue that
was heralded Monday with ads covering the back pages of all four
sections of the New York Times.
   Analysts described Software Etc.'s splash as a sortie in its
escalating battle for market share with rival Egghead Inc., which
runs Egghead Discount Software stores.
   ``This used to be a ma-and-pa industry. Now it's just so
competitive. These companies need to create market dominance,'' said
Teresa Y. Lotzgesell, an analyst at Ragen MacKenzie Inc. in Seattle.
   Among the celebrities scheduled to make appearances at Software
Etc.'s opening this week were William Gates, chairman and co-founder
of Microsoft Corp.; Earl Weaver, former Baltimore Orioles manager;
Andrew Tobias, personal finance writer; Roger Rabbit, the toon; and
``Hacksaw'' Jim Duggan of the World Wrestling Federation.
   The Amazing Kreskin, self-proclaimed mind reader, appeared
Monday. So did Major ``Wild Bill'' Stealey of MicroProse Software,
who demonstrated his flight simulation software on a video wall made
of 16 television screens in a 4-by-4 array.
   The crowds, reminiscent of a good day at Bloomingdale's, warmed
the hearts of the retail-minded executives of Software Etc.
   ``We can't wipe the grins off our faces,'' said Jordan Levy, who
joined the company last year as director of marketing. ``This is
like a real retail store, not like a computer store.''
   Software-only stores scarcely existed in the early 1980s, but
they are catching on quickly, in part because their bulk buying
allows them to offer low prices and take business away from other
outlets, such as computer hardware stores.
   The proliferation of software titles demands the kind of shelf
space that is only available in a software-only shop. Software Etc.
said its Fifth Avenue shop carries more than 2,000 titles, from
desktop publishing to video games.
   According to a survey of large companies by Computer Reseller
Newslast year, about 40 percent of the personal computer software
they bought was through software-only stores, while 27 percent was
through computer hardware stores, 7 percent was by mail order and 7
percent was direct from the software publishers.
   Software Etc. has the most outlets of any chain _ about 240 _
while Egghead leads in revenue.
   Egghead is a public company based in Issaquah, Wash., while
Minneapolis-based Software Etc. is privately held and does not
announce sales or profit figures. Smaller chains include Software
City, Babbage's and Walden Software.
   All the store chains are increasing the support they give
customers, such as having full-time people demonstrating software.
That's part of the user-friendly attitude, which is subsidized in
some cases by the software publishers.
   The top people in the chains are retailers, not technologists. At
Egghead, chairman and founder Victor D. Alhadeff used to sell shoes
at a Seattle department store, while president and chief executive
Stuart M. Sloan also holds down a job as chairman of an upscale
supermarket chain.
   At Software Etc., Levy used to sell computers wholesale. Stan
Hirshman, the vice president of store operations, used to work at
Banana Republic, the Gap and T.J. Maxx. And Dick Fontaine, the
president and chief executive, came from B. Dalton Booksellers and
Michaels Stores, a Dallas-based retailer of arts and crafts and
hobby items.
   Both chains, as well as their smaller rivals, are trying to take
the fear and loathing out of buying computer software.
   ``This has been the kind of business where it's made people
scared of the product,'' Levy said. ``We're creating theater in
here. We're going to have music. We're going to have rock 'n' roll.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;Ls-RealEstate     03-13 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Real Estate,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan Proposed for Dealing With Real Estate of Failed S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House and Treasury Department officials
are reviewing a plan to protect fragile regional economies from the
quick sale of billions of dollars of real estate repossessed from
failed savings and loans.
   The plan was developed by former Deputy Treasury Secretary R.T.
McNamar, who presented it to Bush administration officials last week.
   According to an outline prepared by McNamar and obtained by The
Associated Press, it would create state or local Real Estate
Liquidation Trusts. The trusts would issue bonds, backed partly by
the federal government and partly by state or local governments, and
use the money to buy distressed S&amp;Ls' real estate from the federal
government.
   The trusts would be independent of local government and would
hire staff who would manage the properties with the goal of selling
them at the highest price possible over 10 to 15 years. Trust
managers' compensation would be based on long-term performance of
the properties under their care.
   White House and Treasury Department officials on Monday did not
immediately return telephone calls seeking comment. McNamar, who
started a merchant banking firm in Los Angeles after leaving the
Reagan administration, said in a telephone conversation, ``These are
just some preliminary ideas we've been working on. They are very
consistent with President Bush's program and may or may not be
useful.''
   The McNamar proposal could be warmly received from members of
Congress from energy-producing states such as Texas, where
already-weak real estate markets could be driven into a tailspin by
the quick sale of repossessed property.
   Sen. Timothy Wirth, a Democrat from Colorado, where savings
institutions and local economies have been hard hit by energy-price
problems, said he had not reviewed the plan, but he said it could
prove to be a worthwhile mechanism for holding real estate off
distressed markets.
   ``It's imperative that the authority given to the (S&amp;L
liquidators) include safeguards against property dumping. Clearly
this has to be left to the discretion of (federal regulators) but
they have to understand the fragility of some economies,'' he said
in a telephone interview Monday.
   According to Wirth, S&amp;L regulators now control about $7.5 billion
in repossessed property. Jerome Blank of the National Association of
Realtors told the Senate Banking Committee on Friday that after all
insolvent S&amp;Ls are closed or sold to new owners ``the U.S.
government ... will become the largest landowner in the United
States and will have to dispose of over $150 billion in real
estate.''
   Other legislators, particularly in the House, may not welcome the
McNamar proposal. Members of the House Banking Committee over the
past year and a half have bitterly complained about the performance
and quasi-private structure of the Federal Asset Disposition
Association, an agency set up by S&amp;L regulators to manage
repossessed real estate and bad loans.
   Critics say real estate disposal is best handled by a government
agency less subject to industry influence and directly under the
oversight of Congress. The McNamar outline would put the real estate
outside the direct control of the federal government.
   Bush's plan for restoring the savings and loan industry calls for
selling $50 billion in bonds over the next 2{ years and using the
money to sell or merge insolvent institutions.
   McNamar would use a portion to ``credit enhance'' some portion,
perhaps 20 percent, of the local real estate trust bonds, which
would also be backed to a similar extent by the sponsoring state or
local government.
   The rest of the interest and principal would be paid off by
selling the repossessed real estate. But the proposed mechanism
would allow 10 to 15 years to sell the property, while the Bush
plan, as it stands, would sell all property within five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890313-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     03-13 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures prices surged to a seven-week
high in moderate trading Monday amid reports that fire forced the
shutdown of a major Norwegian oil-producing complex in the North Sea.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the April contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, jumped 53
cents to close at $19.03 a barrel. The last time the near-month
contract closed above $19 a barrel was on Jan. 19, when it closed at
$19.28.
   Other contract months also made strong gains Monday, with the May
contract closing 54 cents higher at $18.63 a barrel.
   Product prices continued to rise, breaking through key technical
levels, analysts said.
   The April contract for unleaded gasoline rose 1.38 cents to
settle at 53.16 cents a gallon, while heating oil rose 1.16 cents to
close at 52.35 cents a gallon. Other contract months also posted
strong gains.
   Analysts said a fire in a crude oil pump unit on a processing
platform forced the closure of Norway's North Sea Ekofisk complex,
including seven crude oil fields.
   The blaze was extinguished quickly but not before damaging
surrounding cables and forcing the shutdown, analysts said.
   The seven fields produce an average of 250,000 barrels a day of
crude oil and about 1 billion cubic feet of gas.
   Phillips Petroleum Co. of Norway, which operates the complex,
indicated the complex could be reopened within the next few days.
   ``It was a strong day,'' said Jim Fiedler, vice president in
charge of energy brokering for E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures
Inc. ``Fundamental news about Ekofisk moved the market. But there
was an underlying strength before that.''
   Traders said prices picked up steam as they broke through key
technical levels that the market had resisted in recent weeks.
   Demand for oil products, particularly heating oil, have posted
gains recently and continued strong in the wake of reports that
European refiners were reducing refinery runs and product
inventories.
</TEXT>
