<SECOND>BC-Earns-Church's,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church's Fried Chicken Revenues Down for 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church's Fried Chicken Inc. on Monday posted a
net loss of $16.6 million in the final quarter of 1988 and
attributed the loss partly to the cost of closing unprofitable
stores and coping with a takeover over.
   Church's management agreed last month to be taken over by A.
Copeland Enterprises Inc., the parent of Popeyes Famous Fried
Chicken and Biscuits, for $11 a share in cash and preferred stock.
The tender offer is set to expire March 21.
   Church's loss for the 16-week period ended Dec. 25 contrasted
with a profit of $1.8 million, or 5 cents a share, in the same
period a year earlier. Revenue rose to $128.9 million from $119.8
million a year earlier.
   For the full year, the company had a loss of $14.5 million, in
comparison with a profit of $9.5 million or 26 cents a share a year
earlier. Revenue rose to $419.6 million from $400.5 million a year
earlier.
   Ernest E. Renaud, president and chief executive officer of
Church's, said earnings were affected by higher food costs and
increased operating expenses, plus a provision for revaluation of
properties held for disposal of $20.2 million in the fourth quarter
as a result of closing 109 unprofitable stores with 1988 pre-tax
operating losses of $7.4 million.
   The company also incurred approximately $6.7 million in
investment banking and legal fees related to a tender offer for the
company's shares by Copeland.
   At the end of 1988, Church's operated 998 stores and franchisees
operated 371, a total of 1,369 units. At the end of 1987, Church's
had 1,495 restaurants. The company operated 1,075 units; the
remaining 420 were franchised.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
