<FIRST>r f AM-MillerAds     03-13 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miller Ads,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miller Pulls Ads From College Newspapers Over Sexism Complaints</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Miller Brewing Co. has withdrawn college
newspaper advertising supplements that were intended to capitalize
on the rollicking atmosphere of spring vacation but instead sparked
complaints of sexism.
   More than a million copies of the supplement, titled ``Beachin'
Times,'' were to run in 67 college newspapers across the country to
promote Miller's spring-break welcome centers in Daytona Beach,
Fla., and South Padre Island, Texas.
   But after receiving criticism from some college newspapers and
being censured by the Wisconsin Student Association at the
University of Wisconsin-Madison, Miller announced Feb. 24 it would
withdraw the supplement.
   ``As soon as we heard the reaction, we took immediate steps to
try to stop it,'' said Robert Bertini, a Miller spokesman. But he
said Miller was able to stop the inserts only in 10 papers.
   For the 57 newspapers that already used the supplement, Miller
sent each an apology through a letter to the editor.
   The 16-page insert includes advice to women to ``never trust a
guy who uses an opening line like `That's a great-looking bathing
suit, but it'd look better on my motel room floor.'''
   The supplement has a page on ``Why I are a college student''
gives such reasons as: ``Better than working,'' ``Six years of high
school was enough,'' ``So I can learn to write gooder,'' and
``Unbelievable babes,'' which was listed three times.
   ``We think we blew it in terms of the tone and the content of the
publication,'' Bertini said. ``It was intended as a humorous
takeoff. We did not intend it to be offensive or inappropriate.''
   The insert ran in late February in the Daily Cardinal newspaper
at UW-Madison. The next day, the student association censured Miller
and urged students to boycott Miller products until the
Milwaukee-based company apologized for the material.
   ``Many people in the (WSA) office found it offensive,'' said
Michael Olds, assistant university affairs director for the student
government organization. ``Different women's groups found it
extremely offensive.''
</TEXT>
