<SECOND>AM-Ford Moves,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Great Grandson Moves from Switzerland to Trucks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Clay Ford Jr., great-grandson of
automobile pioneer Henry Ford, will become head of Ford Motor Co.'s
heavy truck engineering and manufacturing operations in July, the
company said Monday.
   Ford, 31, has been chairman and managing director of Ford of
Switzerland since Sept. 11, 1987. He will return to the United
States in May and take over his new position July 1 when Edward
Mabley retires.
   Ford joined the company in 1979 as a product planning analyst.
His father, Ford Vice Chairman William Clay Ford, retires from the
company at the end of this month. Both are members of Ford's board
of directors.
   The company also announced Monday that vice presidents Walter
Hayes and James Bakken will retire May 1.
   Hayes, now vice chairman of Ford of Europe, was elected a Ford
vice president in 1977. His most recent U.S. assignment was as vice
president for public affairs from 1980-84.
   Bakken also was elected a Ford vice president in 1977. He has
been vice president for corporate quality since last year.
   Hayes and Bakken have their 65th birthdays next month.
</TEXT>
