<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-OilFleet     03-13 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Oil Fleet,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pemex Rescinds Private Lease, Will Build Its Own Tanker Fleet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state petroleum monopoly Pemex has
canceled a leasing contract with a private Mexican company and
announced it will build up its own fleet of oil tankers.
   The board of directors of Petroleos Mexicanos, S.A., decided to
cancel the contract with Flota Petrolera Mexicana S.A. at a late
Sunday meeting because they aren't consistent with current policy,
the oil company said in a press release published in Monday's
newspapers. It offered no further explanation.
   But the independent newspaper Excelsior quoted unnamed sources as
saying cancelation followed ``a series of irregularities observed
recently'' with that company. An editorial in the government
newspaper El Nacional linked it with accusations of corruption
within the petroleum monopoly and its union.
   Neither newspaper went into details.
   Flota Petrolera Mexicana S.A., owned by Isidoro Rodriguez, a
businessman with close ties to several former Pemex directors, had
been leasing two tankers to Pemex since Nov. 29, 1985.
   The powerful Oil Workers Union has claimed the contract leasing
the tankers Antonio J. Bermudez and Antonio Dovali Jaime, signed
shortly before Mario Ramon Beteta stepped down as Pemex director to
run for government of Mexico state, was illegal.
   Union leader Joaquin Hernandez Galicia claimed the lease price of
$19.5 million each was too high and corruption was involved. Beteta
denied any wrongdoing and accusations flew back and forth for more
than three years.
   The attorney general's office, the comptroller general, Pemex and
a special commission in the Chamber of Deputies said their
investigations found no wrongdoing.
   Hernandez Galicia and 50 other oil union leaders were arrested in
a government crackdown Jan 10. Five were released for lack of
evidence.
   The longtime union boss and the other 45 face charges ranging
from homicide to illegal weapons possession and fraud.
   In an editorial Monday, El Nacional called Pemex's cancellation
of the contract a ``drastic correction'' to the problem and praised
the monopoly's decision to build its own tanker fleet.
   Leasing those tankers was ``part of a system of enclaves that
created suspicions, made (Pemex) lose credibility, and strengthened
interests that had nothing to do with Pemex,'' the editorial said.
</TEXT>
