<FIRST>u f AM-Shaklee-Yamanouchi     03-13 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shaklee-Yamanouchi,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Pharmaceutical Firm To Buy Shaklee; Stock Jumps 9\</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yamanouchi Pharmaceutical Co. and Shaklee
Corp. on Monday announced a merger agreement under which the
Japanese firm would buy the direct marketing company for $395
million in cash.
   The $28-per-share bid by Yamanouchi, which bought Shaklee's
Japanese subsidiary last month, apparently foiled an unsolicited
offer from an investor group led by takeover specialist Irwin Jacobs.
   Following the announcement Monday, Jacobs said he would not make
a new offer for Shaklee.
   ``We will not be competing on it,'' Jacobs said. ``They have a
chance to do very well. We wish them a lot of success.''
   Yamanouchi said the $28 it would pay for each of Shaklee's 14
million outstanding shares would be in addition to a one-time
$20-per-share dividend Shaklee recently declared. That meant each
shareholder would receive $48 per share.
   The merger agreement met with strong approval on Wall Street
Monday, as Shaklee's stock shot up $9.25 to close at $47.37{ a share
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``I feel it's a very fair price for shareholders,'' said O. Lee
Tawes, III, an analyst with New York-based Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   Yamanouchi, which had net income of $173 million and sales of
$1.42 billion last year, beat out a $40-per-share, $528 million cash
offer by Jacobs' group on March 3. The group, which included
Minnesota Twins owner Carl Pohlad, said its offer would be reduced
to $20 per share if the $20 special dividend was paid.
   Jacobs, reached at his Minneapolis office, said his group stood
to make up to $44 million in profit from the Yamanouchi deal.
   ``We're disappointed we didn't get the company, but I'd be a fool
if I said I was disappointed financially,'' said Jacobs, who had
hoped to mesh Shaklee with Watkins Co., a direct marketer of
household products he bought 10 years ago.
   Shaklee had earnings last year of $27.2 million on sales of $627
million. Almost half its 1988 earnings and more than a quarter of
its sales came from the Japanese unit, which it sold to Yamanouchi
for $350 million.
   Shaklee said its board had unanimously approved the merger
agreement. Company President David Chamgerlain said there were no
financing conditions attached to the tender offer or merger.
</TEXT>
